<H3><A NAME = "cover">Cover Package: Backing it up</A></H3>
<H4><A NAME = "flawed">Flawed anecdotes hurt journalistic credibility</A></H4>

By Kevin Carmody and Randy Lee Loftis<P>

The anecdote has become the weapon of choice in the campaign to 
rewrite the nation's environmental laws, and lazy journalists are 
allowing themselves to be used as unwitting accomplices.
<P>

Imagine this:<P>

The mayor calls a press conference to announce that his 
administration has achieved a 93-percent public approval rating. 
Therefore, he says, the City Council has a duty to approve his 
proposed budget without debate or amendment.<P>

Journalists' response would be automatic: they would demand 
proof. Who did the poll? When? What was the margin of error? And 
most important, where's the documentation? If the mayor refused 
to back up his claim, reporters would rightly dismiss his 
announcement as a stunt and Hizzoner himself as a con man.<P> 

Now imagine this:<P>

The mayor tells those same reporters that some anonymous 
bureaucrat ordered his city to spend hard-earned tax dollars 
testing the local drinking water for a pesticide used only on 
pineapples -- a crop that has never grown anywhere near his 
Midwestern city. Foolishness and folly! Meddling by overpaid, 
underworked Washington officials! With this outrage exposed, the 
mayor says, Congress has a duty to pass regulatory relief with 
due haste.<P> 

What would the journalists do? This time they would take the 
mayor at his word and put his story on the air or in print 
without a second thought.<P> 

Right?<P>

Right. That second scenario is exactly what happened last year in 
Chicago (and many other cities). The mayor was a real one, 
Richard Daley. The pesticide is real, too -- dibromochloropropane 
(DBCP). Indeed it was used on pineapples, far off in tropical 
Hawaii. News coverage mirrored the mayor's spin, and Chicagoans 
may have been left with the impression that environmental 
"wackos" in the EPA had struck again.<P> 

There was only one problem with this story: It wasn't true. DBCP 
is not just a pineapple pesticide. Until about 1980, DBCP was 
registered for use on about 40 crops, including some widely 
farmed in the upper Midwest, such as soybeans. Pineapples simply 
were the final permitted use. More importantly, DBCP is a 
persistent pesticide that continues to show up in drinking water 
wells across the nation and the upper Midwest.<P> 

The mayor forgot to mention that part. So did the reporters. So 
did their editors and news directors. Although a reporter might 
be fired for reporting a mayor's bogus political poll as fact, it 
seems that a reporter who reports a bogus environmental anecdote 
as fact suffers no consequence at all.<P> 

Anecdotes are supposed to illustrate the truth, reflecting the 
findings of the thorough reportorial or investigative process. In 
authors' past lives as editors, each of us has seen how a 
compelling, tangible example can make an otherwise dry story come 
alive. However, there are two requirements for an honorable 
anecdote. First, it has to be true. Second, it has to reflect the 
greater reality. By itself, an anecdote proves nothing -- as 
every reputable scientist knows.<P> 

That standard, sadly, has fallen into disuse. Instead of picking 
apart the claims of partisans, many journalists are spreading 
them unchallenged. The politics of the day dictate that most of 
the current crop of whoppers comes from opponents of existing 
environmental laws -- partisans trying to turn public opinion.<P> 

In newsrooms throughout the country, it is trendy to ask whether 
environmental laws, not polluters, are the real public enemy. The 
hot story is the "high cost of environmental regulation,'' not 
the people or resources harmed by the violation or abandonment of 
those regulations. In times past, it might have been the 
proponents of environmental regulation who were using dubious or 
exaggerated stories to make political points. (Reporters need to 
be just as diligent about critically examining the claims of 
environmental advocates; their studies and claims are no less 
likely to contain flaws today, and might be more likely to suffer 
from hyperbole whenever the political pendulum swings back.)<P> 

It is good to ask whether public policy is working and how it 
might be flawed. Unfortunately, the process by which some 
journalists are answering this question is the problem.<P> 

Tim Noah, reporting from Washington for <EM>The Wall Street Journal,</EM> 
put it this way: "Five years ago, environmental issues were 
subjected to far too little skepticism in the press. Journalists 
were faddish and unthinking in their coverage of some stories," 
he said. "Now there is a faddish, unthinking, knee-jerk reaction 
in the other direction. The truth is in neither extreme.''<P> 

Here's another way to put it: No matter where a half-truth or an 
outright fib comes from, it's our job to stomp the life out of 
it. We are not always doing our job. Here are some ways in which 
environmental reporters can make amends -- good things for all of 
us to keep in mind:<P> 

<OL><LI><STRONG>All reporters should fact-check everything.</STRONG> Once in 
circulation, flawed anecdotes and bogus "facts" take on lives of 
their own (like ghost stories around campfires) and are likely to 
be lifted and used by other reporters without any fact-checking. 
(The world "factoid" was coined to describe such provably wrong 
but widely accepted assertions. Factoids are to facts as androids 
are to humans.)<P> 

Take the case of the so-called fire rat. Opponents of the 
Endangered Species Act (ESA) say that regulations protecting the 
Stephens kangaroo rat led to the destruction of 29 houses in the 
California wildfires. The tale took hold when a real estate-connected 
opponent of the ESA got a <EM>Los Angeles Times</EM> reporter to 
publish his claim that his neighbors lost their homes because the 
law prohibited their digging up grassland to create 
firebreaks.<P> 

The Stephens kangaroo rat claim then turned up in a <EM>20-20</EM> report 
by ABC's John Stossel. After the Stossel piece aired in late 
1993, the General Accounting Office investigated and torpedoed 
the rats-versus-houses tale, concluding that the wildfire, pushed 
by 80 mph winds, "moved with such ferocity that clearing hundreds 
of feet of ground would not have helped because firestorms of 
this magnitude can blow searing embers and ashes a mile away or 
even farther ... weed abatement techniques become moot.'' More than 
a year later, Connie Chung's now-defunct <EM>Eye to Eye</EM> did the same 
story, focusing on the same discredited allegations while giving 
the GAO conclusions brief mention. Philip Howard exaggerated the 
tale even further in his popular book, <EM>The Death of Common 
Sense.</EM><P> 

There is a little sunshine in this otherwise bleak area. <EM>Time</EM> 
magazine on April 10 detailed some the flawed anecdotes that 
plague Howard's book, including one that Senate Majority Leader 
Bob Dole borrowed to lead off an anti-regulatory op-ed piece in 
the <EM>Washington Post.</EM> (That hasn't kept Howard's book 
off the best-seller lists.) The <EM>Washington Post's</EM> Tom 
Kenworthy did a front page piece on March 13, exposing the use of bogus anecdotes 
by anti-regulation crusaders in Congress. CNN and NBC's <EM>Dateline</EM> 
have broadcast similar pieces.<P> 

And in July, National Public Radio skewered some of the juiciest 
horror stories -- including an alleged action by the government 
to require holes in the bottoms of buckets.<P> 

NPR also told the story of a woman who supposedly was prohibited 
from planting rose bushes in her front yard because they might 
endanger some protected species. Several members of Congress have 
claimed that the woman lived in their state or district, NPR 
noted, but she never seems to be identified.<P> 

That members of the greatest deliberative body on Earth would 
attempt to forge public policy using such shoddy tricks ought to 
be embarrassing. It's the journalist's job to examine, expose, 
and deflate them. The public has a right to be happy, sad, or mad 
about anything it chooses -- but it ought to have the option of 
doing so based on facts, not fantasies.<P> 

<LI><STRONG>In general, reporters should take care to delineate sources' 
facts from their assumptions, opinions, wishes, or fantasies.</STRONG> We 
must renew our allegiance to the facts. We have an obligation not 
only to report accurately what's being said, but to report things 
that are true.<P> 

Here's a widely reported example from the Southeast. Ben Cone, a 
North Carolina farmer, has said that he has cut down his trees 
rather than let some government scientist find nests of the 
endangered red-cockaded woodpecker there.<P> 

The story of that one farmer has now spun out of control. 
Opponents of the Endangered Species Act now use the anecdote to 
claim that the law itself is the biggest factor in habitat 
destruction -- because huge numbers of landowners are nuking 
their property preemptively rather than face federal 
restrictions. Members of Congress from Texas repeated the claim 
recently in an attempt to scuttle federal protection for that 
state's golden-cheeked warbler.<P> 

Journalists should have a simple solution when they hear people 
make a claim like that: Make them prove it.<P> 

Fred Smith of the Competitive Enterprise Institute repeated the 
habitat-destruction claim at SEJ's Southeastern regional 
conference in July. <A HREF="#backlasher">(See related story.)</A> He was immediately 
challenged to cite a single valid scientific study proving its 
truth. The only proof he could cite was the same anecdote that 
triggered the claim in the first place: Ben Cone in North 
Carolina. (The claim that private parties are intentionally 
destroying their own habitats also clashes with the oft-repeated 
assertion of free-market advocates that private owners are better 
stewards of the land than public agencies. That might make an 
interesting story.)<P> 

<LI><STRONG>The lost art of attribution should be rediscovered.</STRONG> Some 
things, of course, aren't provable. We should feel free to say 
so. But we can use that old standby, attribution, to narrow some 
of the factual gaps. Who said it, and what do they have to gain 
by saying it? That information is often as vital to readers as 
what was said.<P> 

Some people have noted that attribution seems to have fallen on 
hard times. The AP's Terry Anderson, who was held hostage in 
Beirut for seven years, said after his release that the 
disappearance of attribution was one of the most disturbing 
changes he noticed in American journalism during his captive 
years.<P> 

Attribution is perhaps the journalist's best insurance against 
attack -- and the best way to judge credibility. In a review of 
Gregg Easterbrook's book <EM>A Moment on the Earth</EM> which appeared in 
the July-August issue of <EM>Audubon</EM> magazine, T.H. Watkins hammers 
Easterbrook for not citing sources for most of his broad 
statements. The evidence shows that the biosphere is in pretty 
good shape, Easterbrook asserts. Watkins responds: "Who says? He 
(Easterbrook) says."<P> 

Even assuming that every word of Easterbrook's book is true, the 
lack of attribution in places makes it a much easier target. 
Watkins rightly demands scientific proof from a source more 
reliable than a mere reporter. Head back to the library in a 
spare moment and flip through a scientific journal. You'll find 
that every statement will be footnoted to a source. In reporting 
on scientific conflict, we should be no less rigorous.<P> 

Attribution can also make for spicier stories. When Mayor Daley's 
staff was eventually pushed to identify the source of the 
pineapple pesticide tale, they said he got it from the mayor of 
Columbus, Ohio.<P> 

<LI><STRONG>Editors, producers, and news directors should only assign 
reporters who know what they're doing to cover environmental 
stories.</STRONG> Those who don't are far more likely to be snookered. 
Don't let any reporter take an environmental assignment until he 
or she can accurately explain, in 45 words or fewer, the 
difference between ground-level ozone and stratospheric ozone. 
Let that be a litmus test before journalists are unleashed on an 
increasingly suspecting public.<P> 

<LI>And finally, all reporters should review the advice that hard-
bitten old city editors have been giving to rookie reporters for 
better than a century: <STRONG>Check, ask, demand, then check again.</STRONG> If a 
mayor tells you that a crazy eco-fascist effort to preserve some 
endangered species of hog has led the government to ban bologna 
and require children to eat stale peanut butter sandwiches for 
lunch -- well, you know.<P> 
</OL>

<EM>Randy Lee Loftis is the environment writer for </EM>The Dallas Morning 
News. <EM>Kevin Carmody covers the beat for </EM>Chicago's Daily 
Southtown. <EM>Both are members of the SEJ board.</EM><P> 

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME = "statistics">Statistics: advantage or potential minefield</A></H4>

By Robert J. Griffin<P>

<P>Like most folks, reporters sometimes cringe when they encounter 
statistical information, even that generated by their own news 
gathering efforts. For example, when the <EM>Milwaukee Journal</EM> 
discovered last fall that a graph accompanying their story on 
single-parent households had incorrectly presented some census 
data they had gathered, the editor involved observed that he 
approaches any story based on statistics, done under deadline 
pressure, as "a potential minefield."<P> 

If the data are provided by someone outside the news 
organization, the minefield can become truly explosive, as <EM>Time</EM> 
magazine discovered to its dismay after running the ill-fated 
cover story on "cyberporn" this past summer. <P> 

<EM>Time's</EM> July 3 piece on Internet pornography was based on a flawed 
and unrepresentative study which had not been peer-reviewed. This 
study grossly overestimated the amount of pornography available 
on the Internet. The cyberporn episode 
illustrates, reporters from any media who do not think critically 
about information -- be it verbal or numeric -- which they get 
from sources can find themselves and their audiences misled. <P> 

Since it seems so easy to misstep, wouldn't it be better just to 
avoid using statistics in stories? Given the use (and misuse) of 
data by all sorts of news sources, the advent of computer-
assisted reporting and ready access to statistical analysis 
packages, the need for journalists to deal competently with 
numbers and the scientific methods that generate them is 
certainly not going away. In fact, it seems that capable 
reporters with computer and statistical acumen might have a real 
advantage in the tight journalistic job market, according to a 
recent article in <EM>Quill</EM> (Christopher J. Feola, "Making the Cut," 
March, 1995, pp. 24-26).<P> 

Environmental journalists in particular can find some real news-
gathering advantages in the combined use of databases, surveys, 
and statistical analyses.<P> 

For example, hazardous chemicals are present quite commonly in 
communities of all sizes. Reporters can use the computerized 
Toxics Release Inventory (TRI) database to discern trends and 
make key comparisons about the release of these chemicals into 
the environment locally and nationally. (A fine guidebook, 
<EM>Chemicals, the Press, and the Public,</EM> discusses some of the 
strengths and weaknesses of TRI data and is available free to 
reporters from the National Safety Council's <A HREF="mailto:ehc@cais.com">Environmental Health 
Center</A> in Washington, D.C.) <P> 

Assessing public reactions to health risks from hazardous 
chemicals and other potential pollutants has become an 
increasingly important part of environmental policy debates. 
Often, those people most at risk from pollution have relatively 
little political or economic clout. Survey techniques could help 
shed light on a couple of key questions for just about any 
community: <P> 

<UL><LI>What risks are acceptable to the people who must, for 
example, live near the local plant which provides jobs but spews 
pollutants?

<LI>Given that people who live in the backyards of industries are 
typically lower-income and less educated, how aware are they of 
possible danger from chemicals and what to do about these 
dangers?</UL><P> 

If properly conducted, surveys can gather information which 
reflects the public's views on health risks and other 
environmental issues, views which are essential for the 
development of good public policy. Such views usually are not 
well-represented by the posturing of politicians, bureaucrats, 
special interest groups, public hearing testifiers, talk-show 
callers, petition signers, op-ed writers, and writers of letters 
to the editor. <P> 

Of course, gathering any information and assessing its value are 
only part of the journalist's job. Interpreting the meaning of 
information for audiences is yet another task. This task can be 
daunting, especially when the information is statistical and such 
a large portion of the general public seems to suffer from 
"innumeracy," (a term coined by Temple University mathematics 
professor John Allen Paulos to describe the widespread problem of 
mathematical illiteracy.)<P> 

Given that most reporters are much more likely to encounter data 
provided by others than to generate it themselves through 
techniques such as surveys, the ability to think critically about 
data encountered in the news can be a very valuable intellectual 
ability on any beat. Journalists who engage in such statistical 
reasoning instead of holding data at arm's length can do a lot to 
help audiences understand the news. <P> 

Statistical reasoning is the application of a basic set of 
logical rules of evidence based in the sciences. One of the most 
serious errors in statistical reasoning occurs when people jump 
to the conclusion that one thing causes another simply because 
the two correlate.<P> 

A case in point: this past summer an environmental activist group 
claimed that the large number of nuclear power plants surrounding 
the Great Lakes and the high incidence of breast cancer in the 
region demonstrate the danger from nuclear power plants. <P> 

Informal observation showed that some local media, at least in 
the Milwaukee area, covered the story in the point-counterpoint 
way usually applied to political coverage -- by conveying the 
group's allegations and then reporting that various experts 
disagreed with them. <P> 

However, other Milwaukee news media illustrated for their 
audiences right away the faulty statistical reasoning involved in 
simply assuming causality from correlation. One local television 
station, for example, quoted an epidemiologist who explained how 
urbanization around the Great Lakes lurks as the likely culprit, 
contributing separately to both the cancer rate and the demand 
for power met in the past by building nuclear plants.<P> 

In general, statistical reasoning usually involves much more 
"reasoning" than "statistics." For journalistic purposes, 
statistical reasoning commonly concerns: 

<UL><LI>The kinds of evidence required to show that one thing 
causes another (e.g., carefully ruling out other explanations 
lurking behind the scenes);  

<LI>The representativeness and generalizability of the 
findings of research (e.g., appropriately using some form of 
random sampling in surveys and, especially, not drawing 
conclusions about a group from one or two cases); 

<LI>Probability (e.g., carefully interpreting risk estimates, 
properly applying a margin of error to survey results);  

<LI>Basic statistical rules, especially rules for making fair 
comparisons (e.g., when comparing changes in the tons of trash 
produced in various cities, remembering the importance of the 
denominator by accounting for differences in the population 
growth of each community).</UL><P> 

To serve the needs of the audience probably will require the vast 
majority of journalists to become more skillful in using and 
analyzing the validity of statistical information and also to 
become more adept at translating the meaning of this information 
for audiences. <P> 

As educators and professionals, what can we do about it? Here are 
some suggestions:<P> 

<OL><LI>Journalism schools should assess how well statistical literacy 
is integrated into the professional curriculum at all levels. <P> 

If a good portion of journalists are having trouble dealing with 
statistics, as appears to be the case, much of the fault might 
lie in the traditional culture of the journalism academy. For 
decades, this culture has subtly written off journalism students 
as innumerate, often with encouragement from the students 
themselves, and has therefore failed to help them develop the 
necessary conceptual tools. <P> 

Journalism education, it seems, has been guided by what Lee 
Becker and Joseph Graf call "the myth [that] journalism is a 
career for those with math deficiencies" (<EM>Myths and Trends: What 
the Real Numbers Say About Journalism Education,</EM> The Freedom 
Forum, 1995, p. 11). This study shows that journalism students 
score well on the verbal portion of the Scholastic Aptitude Test. 
However, instead of being a bunch of math 
dummies, journalism students do, in fact, reflect the national 
average on the math portion of the SAT. So, they should be able 
to handle the basics of statistical methods and reasoning as 
applied to the work of journalism -- and probably have been able 
to do so for years.<P> 

The challenge to journalism education is to teach "numeracy" 
throughout the professional curriculum rather than just 
relegating statistics instruction to an isolated course the 
students might take over in the math or psychology department. (A 
stats course, however, does provide an essential base.) 
Statistical reasoning should be integrated thoroughly into 
reporting courses -- at least as well as law, ethics, and the 
other liberal arts drawn from the rest of the university -- so 
that students can learn how to apply it in the many everyday 
contexts of news reporting. <P> 

"It's time to let the secret out," as Paulos says in his book, <EM>A 
Mathematician Reads the Newspaper</EM> (p. 3). "Mathematics is not 
primarily a matter of plugging numbers into formulas and 
performing rote computations. It is a way of thinking and 
questioning that may be unfamiliar to many of us, but is 
available to almost all of us."<P> 

<LI>Journalists should consider refreshing their 
statistical reasoning skills and applying them more 
rigorously to the news.<P> 

Taking refresher courses in statistics, precision journalism, 
computer-assisted reporting and the like would be the fast track. 
There are, however, some other very good resources as well: 

<UL><LI>Read and keep nearby Victor Cohn's two books, <EM>News & 
Numbers</EM> (Iowa State University Press, 1989), and <EM>Reporting on 
Risk</EM> (The Media Institute, 1990), and also Philip Meyer's <EM>The New 
Precision Journalism</EM> (Indiana, 1991). Both Cohn and Meyer are 
former journalists (Cohn was a science writer) with a knack for 
statistics, clear writing, and good advice. 

<LI>For a quick read, try Arnold Barnett's article "How Numbers 
Can Trick You" in <EM>Technology Review</EM> (October 1994, pp. 38-45). 

<LI>For amplification, read John Allen Paulos' recent book <EM>A 
Mathematician Reads the Newspaper</EM> (Basic Books, 1995), his 
earlier <EM>Innumeracy</EM> (Vintage, 1988), and Cynthia Crossen's <EM>Tainted 
Truth: The Manipulation of Fact in America</EM> (Simon & Schuster, 
1994).  

<LI>To keep up-to-date, point your Internet web browser to the 
home page of math professor Laurie Snell's 
<A HREF="http://www.geom.umn.edu/locate/chance">"Chance" project</A> 
at Dartmouth College. The 
online <EM>Chance Newsletter,</EM> designed to help statistics 
instruction, contains a wealth of examples of the use of 
statistics in current news stories.</UL><P> 

In applying statistical reasoning skills, 
reporters should demand that statistical and other evidence 
presented in the news is enlightening, not misleading. Reporters 
also should insist that the evidence has been gathered 
in an ethical manner. These demands would apply to information 
provided by sources and that gathered by their own news 
organizations. That can be a big order, but there are some places 
to start.<P> 

Surveys are a very common -- and sometimes misused -- source of 
statistical information in the news. Various sources, such as 
Phil Meyer's <EM>The New Precision Journalism,</EM> provide guidelines for 
the kinds of information that reporters should gather about the 
method used in a survey to help them and their audiences assess 
its validity. <P> 

Similarly, journalists can also help audiences become more savvy 
about statistics and the scientific methods that generate them. 
The <EM>Minneapolis Star-Tribune,</EM> for example, ran an article by 
Sandra Y. Lee ("Untrue Facts," Nov. 28, 1994, p. 1E), reprinted 
from <EM>McCall's,</EM> about how people accept distorted statistics. The 
article included a guide with questions designed to help readers 
sort out what to believe in surveys and similar studies. 
Questions included: 

<UL><LI>Who was surveyed or studied?  

<LI>How many people were surveyed and how many responded?  

<LI>How were the questions worded? 

<LI>How was the problem defined?  

<LI>Who paid for the study?  

<LI>Was the study published in a peer-review journal such as the 
<EM>New England Journal of Medicine?</EM></UL><P> 

Answers to these and other essential questions (e.g., were the 
interviewees in a sample survey chosen in some random manner -- 
and, if so, what is the survey's margin of error?) should be 
readily available to reporters from the text of the study's 
report or from the organization which conducted the study. One 
very important way for reporters to apply statistical reasoning 
is to use a sample survey's margin of error directly to interpret 
the results for audiences (e.g., is the difference in support for 
the incumbent and the challenger greater than the sampling error 
would produce?) rather than simply reporting the margin of error 
at the end of the story and hoping audiences can figure out its 
application.<P> 

There are some unethical practices in survey research which 
reporters should be aware of. The most worrisome of these 
capitalize on others' innumeracy and borrow the scientific aura 
of good surveys to lend credibility to slipshod or self-serving 
efforts. Recently the Research Industry Coalition, which is 
comprised of 15 organizations including the American Association 
for Public Opinion Research (AAPOR) and the National Association 
of Broadcasters, took a stand against the most salient abuses: 

<UL><LI>Soliciting contributions or payments, selling products, 
or using survey participants as means of generating sales leads 
under the guise of conducting a survey; 

<LI>Revealing the 
identity of individual participants in a study (e.g., survey 
interviewees) without prior, informed consent;  

<LI>Depicting "call-in" polls as representative of the views of 
the general public.</UL><P> 

It might be disconcerting to see a reference to what is an all-
too-common media practice, the call-in poll, in this kind of 
rogues gallery. A call-in poll will, for example, ask audience 
members to initiate phone calls to a central number to indicate 
their stance on a particular issue in the news. The problem is 
that the call-in poll, like any kind of study based on self-
selection and individual cases, is not itself generalizable to 
the big picture. Call-in polls may yield some individual examples 
(e.g., some quotes) but they provide poor evidence of trends. <P> 

Compounding the problem is that call-in polls probably seem quite 
legitimate and representative to the public unless those who 
report these polls go out of their way to counteract that 
misperception. For example, the Research Industry Coalition 
recommends that the following disclaimer accompany the reports of 
call-in polls: "These 'polls' represent the opinions of only 
those people who have called or written in, and not the general 
public." <P> 

As the primary professional and scholarly association in public 
opinion research, AAPOR has developed an entire set of voluntary 
standards of good practice for conducting surveys -- standards 
which the organization is currently reviewing.<P> 

<LI>Since much of the evidence about journalists' encounters with 
statistics is itself anecdotal, we still have much to learn. 
Intelligence on the current state of the art is still quite 
tentative. We certainly need to get more systematic information, 
from the journalist's point of view, about their experiences with 
statistical information in the news (e.g., what are the most 
common or vexing problems they face when dealing with data?). We 
need to explore how journalism schools can do a better job 
of teaching statistical reasoning and the other intellectual 
software which should accompany the news-gathering power brought 
about by the newsroom computer. <P> 

There is no doubt, however, that the need to apply statistical 
reasoning to data and other forms of evidence can occur on just 
about any reporter's beat. Environmental reporters in particular 
play an increasingly important role as interpreters of 
complicated statistical and technical information to audiences, 
information which can help to enlighten debates over some of the 
most vexing public policy issues.</OL><P>

<EM>Robert J. Griffin, a member of SEJ, is associate professor of 
journalism at Marquette University in Milwaukee and director of 
the Center for Mass Media Research. He is also co-editor of the 
advanced reporting textbook </EM>Interpreting Public Issues <EM>(Iowa 
State University Press, 1991).</EM> <P> 



<H4><A NAME = "peer">Sidebar: Peer-Review Pitfalls: Learning from <EM>Time's</EM> Mistakes</A></H4>

By Robert J. Griffin<P>

Peer-review is the standard mechanism by which science strives to 
ensure the validity of research. A peer-reviewed study is one 
that has been examined for the scientific soundness of its 
methods and conclusions by an independent group of experts 
knowledgeable in those areas. Checking for appropriate 
peer-review is one way that reporters can reduce the likelihood of 
reporting poor research. <P> 

The "cyberporn" study upon which <EM>Time</EM> based a cover feature 
earlier this year was scheduled for publication in the <EM>Georgetown 
Law Review</EM> when <EM>Time</EM> was assembling its article. However, some 
critics later objected that the law review did not subject the 
study by Marty Rimm (who was an engineering undergrad at 
Carnegie-Mellon University when he conducted the study) to 
scrutiny by experts in social science methods. Law review 
journals, unlike scientific journals, typically are not peer-reviewed. 
In addition, the study's author made a pre-publication, 
"keep this under wraps" agreement with both <EM>Time</EM> and the law 
review. That agreement effectively prohibited both publications 
from conducting peer-review of the cyberporn study. That 
should have signalled to <EM>Time</EM> that something was amiss with 
the study itself. However, this agreement was not mentioned in 
the <EM>Time</EM> feature.<P> 

Although peer-reviewing helps to verify the legitimacy of 
scientific research, not all peer-review processes are equal. Studies reported at 
scholarly and scientific conventions have usually been 
peer-reviewed in some way, but this sort of review is not always as 
rigorous as that given to studies submitted for publication in 
refereed journals. <P> 

Reporters wanting help determining the soundness of a research 
study (including, for example, those conducted by 
their own news organizations) might consult 
university experts. Some have suggested that <EM>Time</EM> should have 
done just that.<P> 

<EM>Time</EM> later acknowledged some deficiencies with the reporting for 
its cyberporn feature. Elmer DeWitt, the author of the story, 
later published another <EM>Time</EM> article which included some 
discussion of the secrecy agreement. This article also discussed 
some "credibility problems" of Rimm's which surfaced after the 
feature was published -- although it was noted that Rimm failed 
to answer questions about his life during interviews (perhaps 
a warning about an undependable source that
DeWitt ignored).<P> 

In his second article, DeWitt stopped short of apologizing for a 
lack of "due dilligence" in his cyberporn reporting. Rather, he 
dodged this issue. "Some clearly believe that <EM>Time,</EM> by 
publicizing the Rimm study, was contributing to a mood of popular 
hysteria . . . that might lead to a crackdown," he wrote. "It 
would be a shame, however, if the damaging flaws in Rimm's study 
obscured the larger and more important debate about hardcore porn 
on the Internet," he wrote.<P> 

<EM>Robert J. Griffin, a member of SEJ, is associate professor of 
journalism at Marquette University in Milwaukee and director of 
the Center for Mass Media Research. He is also co-editor of the 
advanced reporting textbook</EM> Interpreting Public Issues <EM>(Iowa 
State University Press, 1991).</EM><P> 

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H3><A NAME="features">Features</A></H3>

<H4><A NAME="backlasher">Backlasher lashes out during Atlanta regional conference</A>
</H4>By Ken Edelstein<P>

Rep. Charles Taylor, R-N.C., let environmental journalists know 
exactly what he thought of them as he began a July 22 speech at 
SEJ's southeastern regional conference in Atlanta. <P> 

"You have the power to do something very positive," said Taylor, 
a leader in the environmental backlash now sweeping Washington. 
"You also have the power to continue to screw up, because most of 
what has been written is absolutely trash."<P> 

A steering committee of SEJ members focused the conference 
program on issues of particular concern in the South and on 
developing the skills of this region's environmental 
journalists.<P> 

The forums on skills included panels on covering company towns, 
getting news from state and regional agencies, and tapping into 
online resources such as the <EM>Green Disk Journal.</EM> Issue-oriented 
panels explored property rights, endangered species, suburban 
sprawl, and the region's proliferating water disputes.<P> 

This meeting -- SEJ's largest since the Republican sweep of 
congressional elections last November -- drilled home the point 
that today even the most local environmental controversies are 
tightly wound around the bitter struggle over environmental laws 
and funding in Washington.<P> 

A panel discussion on "Swamps, Species, and Property Rights," 
provided the sharpest exchanges. From Louisiana's bayous to 
Georgia's tree farms to the South Carolina coast (where a real 
estate developer named David Lucas won a Supreme Court case over 
his plans to develop his land), issues such as property rights, 
wetlands, and the Endangered Species Act have flashed across the 
region like lightning strikes in an old-growth forest.<P> 

When one questioner's request for "common ground" drew more 
disagreement, moderator Jay Bookman of the <EM>Atlanta Constitution</EM> 
quipped, "I didn't hear a lot.."<P> 

Lucas, now a leading property rights spokesman, sharpened the 
debate with the kind of populist one-liners that have helped 
gain publicity for his movement. He insisted that property 
advocates aren't aligned with big business and that they have no 
designs on destroying the nation's environmental laws.<P> 

"The only thing the property rights movement is interested in is 
protecting private property," he said. "... All of the sudden when 
I say I want just compensation, I'm being assailed as this devil 
(against) the environment."<P> 

Lucas said landowners face intimidating foes in overbearing 
agencies, because "people are still losing their property every 
day in this country."<P> 

"The federal government, the state governments, and the local 
governments own 67 percent of this country," he said. " ... They 
want to control it all. That's what the National Biological 
(Service) is about -- control of that land."<P> 

The Sierra Club's Sam Collier countered that facts and anecdotes 
paraded by the property rights movement often are exaggerated or 
wrong.<P> 

Dan Ashe, assistant director for external affairs at the U.S. 
Fish & Wildlife Service, said the Clinton administration has done 
"more than any administration has ever done before" to work with 
small property owners on incentive programs and exemptions to the 
Endangered Species Act. However, he argued that takings bills now 
before Congress would place a multibillion-dollar burden on the 
government to compensate landowners for speculative projects.<P> 

"Property is like everything else," Ashe said. "It comes with 
responsibility, and people have a responsibility to use the land 
wisely ... and conservation of wildlife is one of those things that 
we value in this society." <P> 

While the act should be flexible, it also should be tough, he 
argued, because it often provides nature's final stand.<P> 

Although Ashe and other administration officials (including 
Environmental Protection Agency regional administrator John 
Hankinson Jr. and Fish & Wildlife regional director Noreen 
Clough) were forced to ward off criticism from the right, the 
most blistering attack on the White House came from a former 
Clinton appointee.<P> 

Jim Baca, who was fired as director of the Bureau of Land 
Management, blasted President Clinton for giving in to Western 
senators on efforts to reduce subsidies for mining and grazing on 
public lands.<P> 

"You never get things done in Washington, if you need to fix 
them, through a policy of appeasement," Baca said. <P> 

Baca said he still doesn't understand why the administration 
agreed to the senators' demands. But he said the only way to 
change Congress' behavior would be through campaign finance 
reform, so that "dying" special interests, like foreign mining 
companies, would hold less sway in Washington.<P> 

Election victories and Clinton's cave-in emboldened Western 
fringe organizations to try to force their own land-use ideas and 
policies on the rest of the country, Baca said.<P> 

"What we ended up with was a lot of Wise Use groups really being 
able to push their way around, militia groups being able to push 
their way around in the Western states, and I have to say ... that 
after listening to Mr. Lucas here this afternoon, you've got the 
same problem out here," he said. (Lucas said earlier in the day 
that he knows nobody in the Wise Use movement.)<P> 

Baca, a former TV reporter, urged reporters to dig deeper and 
follow the money trail on land-use issues. Taylor, the North 
Carolina congressman, offered a far broader critique of the 
press.<P> 

The two-term Republican, who represents a mountainous district 
around Asheville, led this year's successful push to accelerate 
National Forest logging by allowing regulation-skirting timber 
salvages. A tree farmer himself, Taylor started his critique of 
environmental journalists even before he got the obligatory 
opening joke out of the way. Then, he explained why his briefcase 
was bulging.<P> 

"I have to travel with a lot of evidence," Taylor said, "because 
while you accept the environmental movement's words for gospel 
and print it over and over again, I have to prove it jot and 
tittle."<P> 

He argued that during the timber-salvage debate, reporters 
swallowed whole the arguments of environmentalists, who distorted 
biology or simply were ignorant. Taylor said his side has 
introduced "reality in science" to environmental debates.<P> 

When Randy Lee Loftis of the <EM>Dallas Morning News</EM> asked Taylor 
about the future of the National Biological Service, Taylor said, 
"I would classify it somewhat as dead because we took a lot of 
the money, and I think we'll probably take more of the money."<P> 

Taylor contended that this move wasn't part of an attempt to 
reduce scientific research. Rather, he said it was prompted by 
"bad blood" between conservatives and the service over 
biologists' attempts to survey on private property.<P> 

There was one hint at the conference of possible common ground 
between environmentalists and conservatives. Zoo Atlanta director 
Terry Maple, a noted conservationist, kicked off the meeting with 
a discussion of his friendship with House Speaker Newt Gingrich. 
<P> 

He's convinced Gingrich has a real interest in the environment, 
particularly in the Endangered Species Act. This high-level 
interest offers hope that Republicans will come up with their own 
sincere, market-oriented approaches to environmental protection, 
Maple said.<P> 

He also warned that environmentalists threaten their own agenda 
by siding consistently with Democrats.<P> 

The conference was co-sponsored by Emory University's Human and 
Natural Ecology Program, and also by CNN, Turner Broadcasting, 
the <EM>Atlanta Journal-Constitution,</EM> the <EM>News & Observer</EM> of Raleigh, 
and the New York Times Newspaper Group. CNN's Peter Dykstra 
chaired the meeting.<P> 

<EM>Ken Edelstein is the environmental reporter and Atlanta bureau 
chief for the</EM> Columbus <EM>(Ga.)</EM> Ledger-Examiner. <P> 


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="directory">Directory of environmental journalists being compiled by recently formed IFEJ
</A>
</H4>By Jim Detjen

<P>

The International Federation of Environmental Journalists (IFEJ) 
is creating an international directory of environmental 
journalists to link together reporters, writers, producers, and 
educators from around the world.<P> 

SEJ members who are interested in being listed in this directory 
should fill out the <A HREF="ifej_dir.htm">directory form</A>                                                                                            
and fax or mail it back to IFEJ's North 
American office at Michigan State University. Please make sure 
that you also list what languages you can speak and read.<P> 

Anyone listed in the directory will be able to obtain a copy when 
it is compiled. This directory will be sent to you for either a 
small fee or possibly for free, if sufficient funds can be raised 
to print it and to distribute it. <P> 

The hope is that the IFEJ directory will be of value in much the 
way that SEJ's membership directory helps SEJ members. If you are 
working on a story about Brazilian rainforests and need 
assistance, you could check the IFEJ directory for environmental 
journalists in Brazil. Once you've identified the journalist you 
can send a list of questions to the Brazilian reporter by e-mail, 
fax, or a letter. Or you could call up the journalist directly by 
telephone.<P> 

Similarly, if you are traveling overseas the IFEJ directory will 
give you a list of contacts in the countries you are visiting. 
Since they are also environmental journalists, the likelihood is 
great that they will be willing to assist you, if they possibly 
can.<P> 

The IFEJ directory also will list the areas of specialty of 
environmental journalists so that if you are interested in 
finding journalists who specialize in ocean pollution or fishing 
issues, you should be able to do so. <P> 

The IFEJ directory is being compiled by my assistant Barb Miller, 
and Melinda Arbaugh (a senior journalism major at Michigan State 
University). Our hope is that a rough draft may be available 
before the end of this year, so it's important that you mail or 
fax the enclosed form as soon as possible.<P> 

If you need extra copies of the <A HREF="ifej_dir.htm">directory form,</A> simply make a 
copy and use it. Or, if you need many extra copies, call Barb or 
Melinda at (517) 432-1415. <P> 

The costs of creating this directory are being partially 
underwritten by Michigan State University, the Knight Foundation 
and the United Nations Environment Programme.<P> 

<EM>Jim Detjen holds the Knight Chair of Environmental Journalism at 
Michigan State University. He is the founding president of SEJ 
and the current president of IFEJ. Please send the <A HREF="ifej_dir.htm">form</A> to him at 
341 Communication Arts Building, Michigan State University, East 
Lansing, MI 48824-1212 or by faxing it to him at (517) 355-7710. </EM>
<P> 


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="pressures">Pressures on business transcend regs</A></H4>

By Scott Fenn<P>

Recent news coverage of business and the environment is replete 
with stories about the assault on environmental regulation 
underway in Congress and the efforts of some within the business 
community to weaken environmental laws. <P> 

However, an interesting recent phenomenon calls into question the 
notion that environmental pressures on business are easing -- 
namely, growing private-sector and non-governmental pressures to 
improve environmental performance. Whether these forces can 
replace regulation as a mechanism for enforcing environmental 
accountability remains to be seen, but they are already 
influencing corporate behavior.<P> 

Enforcement activity by the EPA, the Department of Justice, and 
state regulators has been tightening since the Bush 
administration. Whether it will continue to do so is uncertain. 
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, for instance, recently blasted the 
EPA, saying it "may well be the biggest job-killing agency in the 
inner city in America today."<P> 

At the same time, however, the bipartisan U.S. Sentencing 
Commission has proposed new guidelines for environmental 
violations that include both stiffer penalties and a list of 
environmental management elements which will be used to determine 
penalties. Fines can be reduced if managers measure and monitor 
compliance; implement auditing, reporting, and tracking systems; 
and develop incentive programs for environmental excellence and 
processes for evaluating and improving performance.<P> 

Companies also face mounting pressure to improve environmental 
performance from shareholders and customers. During 1995's 
annual-meeting season, investors in 22 companies voted on 
shareholder proposals related to improving environmental 
performance and reporting. At a number of these companies, 
shareholder proposals requested companies to endorse a 10-point 
environmental code of conduct known as the CERES principles 
(CERES stands for the Coalition for Environmentally Responsible 
Economies). <P> 

The CERES effort, which is sponsored by a coalition of 
environment, religious and investment institutions, gained 
momentum over the last two years with the endorsement of its 
principles by several Fortune 500 companies (including Sun Co., 
General Motors Corp., Polaroid, Arizona Public Service Co., and 
H.B. Fuller).<P> 

Similarly, some institutional shareholders which supply capital 
for U.S. industry are displaying growing interest in corporate 
environmental performance. Several major financial institutions, 
including TIAA-CREF (the country's largest private pension fund 
with more than $120 billion in assets under management), have 
started investment funds which use environmental performance 
data, among other factors, as a criteria for selecting stocks. A 
survey by the Investor Responsibility Research Center of 
investment managers who use social criteria to screen portfolios 
found that the environment has become the single largest area of 
concern.<P> 

While most public institutions show no desire to see the 
environment become a political cause celebre, as disinvestment in 
South Africa became in the 1980s, some action is beginning to 
occur. In 1992, Dartmouth College divested its bond holdings in 
Hydro-Quebec, a major Canadian electric utility, following 
student protests and a petition drive on campus criticizing the 
environmental and social impacts of the utility's Great Whale 
hydroelectric project on native lands in northern Quebec. Tufts 
University and Williams College followed suit in 1994, each after 
enduring student pressure to divest for almost two years. 
Notably, the Quebec provincial government announced in late 1994 
that the project was being put "on ice for a good long while."<P> 

Even institutions with little interest in the social aspects of 
environmental performance are starting to pay attention to the 
issue for financial reasons. A survey published by the accounting 
firm Price Waterhouse in 1993 found that only 62 percent of 
companies with known environmental liabilities had reported them 
in their financial statements. Driven by concerns about such 
non-disclosure, the Securities and Exchange Commission, the Financial 
Accounting Standards Board, and the American Institute of 
Certified Public Accountants have issued new rules requiring 
companies to disclose more detailed cost estimates for waste site 
cleanups and other environmental liabilities. Corporate 
liabilities for the cleanup of abandoned Superfund hazardous 
waste sites alone are estimated to range from $42 billion to $120 
billion in present-worth dollars, according to the Congressional 
Budget Office.<P> 

Procurement regulations are yet another new source of pressure on 
companies to improve environmental management. Many federal 
contracts now contain clauses requiring contractors to 
investigate and monitor the environmental performance of 
subcontractors and vendors. Some companies have also adopted 
procurement programs designed to favor environmentally sound 
suppliers. AT&T was a leader in this area. Its Policy for 
Environmental Protection instructs employees to "include 
environmental considerations among the criteria by which 
projects, products, processes, and purchases are made." Many 
other large manufacturers have followed suit and are developing 
criteria for selecting environmentally responsible suppliers and 
standards to which they must adhere.<P> 

Perhaps the greatest pressure on companies to improve future 
environmental performance comes not from any external pressure, 
however, but rather from straightforward economics -- it is often 
cheaper to prevent pollution at the source rather than clean it 
up at the end of the pipe -- and then litigate with victims of 
environmental hazards. <P> 

The 3M Corporation, which initiated its Pollution Prevention Pays 
(3P) program in 1975, claims this program has saved a whopping 
$646 million over the last 18 years. Corporations increasingly 
are turning to such voluntary measures as a way to leapfrog ahead 
of government regulations which focus on pollution problems at 
the back end of the product cycle.<P> 

Do all these pressures insure that business activity is becoming 
ecologically sustainable? Well, not exactly. In fact, a strong 
case can be made that the world economy is less sustainable 
today, from a purely ecological perspective, than at any point in 
human history. Many critical global ecological indicators -- 
including worldwide emissions of sulfur, nitrogen, and carbon 
from the burning of fossil fuels -- are still heading in the 
wrong direction. Atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide and 
chlorine are rising, and tropical deforestation and species 
extinction also are continuing rapidly.<P> 

The environmental challenges to corporations and policy makers 
remain daunting. The business community's initial steps to treat 
pollution as an economic variable to be measured and managed are 
necessary, but not sufficient, to the task of achieving a 
sustainable world economy. Corporations must now move to close 
the loop in their production processes and product lifecycles, 
forming consortiums to turn wastes and used products into 
production inputs. <P> 

They also must integrate a much broader set of ecological 
indicators and goals (ranging from energy and water consumption 
to the impacts of their operations on biodiversity and the 
atmosphere) into business planning and corporate assessments of 
environmental performance. Meanwhile, investors -- whether in the 
private sector, at public institutions, or in multilateral 
lending institutions -- can play an important role by considering 
environmental sustainability as one criteria in selecting the 
projects and companies which they finance.<P> 

<EM>Scott A. Fenn is director of the environmental information 
program at the Investor Responsibility Research Center in 
Washington, D.C. <P> 
</EM>


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="aejmc">AEJMC panel calls for myth busters
</A>
</H4>By John Palen

<P>

Journalists' obligation to separate myths from facts was a 
persistent theme in an environmental reporting panel at the 
annual convention of the Association for Education in Journalism 
and Mass Communication, held in Washington in mid-August.<P> 

Much criticism of environmental regulation, for example, is 
misdirected at an U.S. Environmental Protection Agency that has 
moved off in new directions, according to EPA deputy associate 
administrator Denise Graveline, who is responsible for 
communication, education and public affairs with the EPA in 
Washington, D.C. <P> 

Environmental journalists have a role to play as "myth busters" 
in helping improve public understanding of the situation, she 
said.<P> 

Formed in 1970 at a time of crisis, the EPA made incredible  
progress, but was already moving away from a crisis mode when 
the elections of 1994 turned Congress on its ear, according to 
Graveline.<P> 

In the upheaval in Congress, some criticism of EPA doesn't take 
into account the changes in the agency, and journalists need to 
check facts and know sources to avoid being manipulated, she 
said.<P> 

The old EPA was built to deal with crisis, using a "command-and-control 
approach to administer drastic, expensive solutions to 
extreme problems," Graveline said. She cited statistics showing that a quarter century later, 
chemical emissions are down 90 percent, and sewage and 
carcinogens have been cleaned up. The new EPA stresses 
prevention and a single rule for every industry rather than 
separate regulations for air, land and water, she said.<P> 

Graveline spoke at a panel on "Ferment and the 
Future: Where is Environmental Journalism Heading?"<P> 

Other speakers were Kevin Carmody, environmental reporter for the 
<EM>Daily Southtown</EM> in Chicago and an SEJ board member; Carolyn 
Cline, faculty member at University of Southern California; James 
Detjen, Knight Chair of Environmental Journalism at Michigan 
State University; and Sharon Friedman, media coordinator of the 
National Campaign for Pesticide Policy Reform in Washington, and professor and
chairperson of the Department of Journalism and Communication at Lehigh University
in Pennsylvania.<P> 

The panel was sponsored by the Science Communication Interest 
Group and moderated by Sharon M. Friedman of Lehigh 
University.<P> 

Carmody cautioned that attacks on environmentalism are a current 
fad just as blindly pro-environment pieces were common a few 
years ago, but that anecdotes are promoted by anti-environment 
groups are taking on a new and troubling role.<P> 

Anecdotes which are supposed to illustrate the truth too often 
are being used by reporters as the arbiters of truth, he said. If 
a tale fits the current conventional wisdom, few reporters seem 
to go to the trouble of checking its accuracy.<P> 

"Hammer on the difference between fact, assumption and opinion," 
Carmody urged journalism educators. "Attribution makes a big 
difference. Who says it, is important."<P> 

Friedman said a media trend to make every story hang on conflict 
leads to "formulaic reporting" of extreme positions. "There are 
crazy people on both sides," she warned.<P> 

Public relations people are as guilty as reporters, she said, 
because they often use a polarized, good-guys-vs.-bad-guys 
approach to gain a purchase on a  controversy.<P> 

Coverage of Alar has been mythicized as an example of 
irresponsible environmental reporting, she said. However, the 
National Academy of Science agreed that Alar was a cumulatively 
dangerous chemical, and industry subsequently removed it from the market.<P> 

"We need 'responsible spinning' by public relations people," she 
said.<P> 

Detjen presented findings of a Times Mirror survey of public 
views on environmental issues and journalism. In an age of lost 
faith in large institutions, including mass media, environmental 
journalism gets barely a passing grade, he said. Nearly 80 
percent rated coverage only fair or poor.<P> 

More than a third of the 1,003 adults surveyed said reporters 
make environmental problems appear worse than they are, while  
younger readers think the media paint too rosy a picture.<P> 

"Overwhelmingly, the public wants more coverage," Detjen 
reported. His hunch is that the amount of environmental coverage 
will continue to increase.<P> 

As it increases, more and more of it relies on cyberspace as a 
source of information, yet the Internet is a "library with all 
the books on the floor," said Cline. One way to end the confusion 
would be to establish a central administration for the Internet, 
but Cline rejected that idea.<P> 

Instead, she said, computer scientists should devise better ways 
of managing information. "A meta-state, multi-disciplinary group should be 
formed and seek funding for an ongoing effort to keep 
information sites updated and get useful listings online," she said.<P> 

The panel was one of two environmental sessions sponsored by the 
Science Communication Interest Group. The other was a 
presentation of research on environmental issues.<P> 

Craig Trumbo, from the University of Wisconsin-Madison, said his study of 
global warming coverage found that scientists are often quoted at 
the beginnings of environmental controversies, but tend to get 
squeezed out as sources as debate becomes politicized.<P> 

Ethical concerns are high profile issues for environmental 
journalists, and Joanne Myer Valenti, Brigham Young University, 
surveyed SEJ members at last year's national conference to 
determine whether they score differently on standardized scales 
of ethical motivation. They don't.<P> 

Virginia Whitehouse, of the University of Missouri, reported on 
"SLAPP" suits -- strategic lawsuits against public participation. 
She said the suits, which are brought not to win a verdict but to 
shut off criticism, are a threat to environmental reporting as 
well as to citizens and citizen groups.<P> 

<EM>John Palen is chair of the journalism department at Central 
Michigan University, and is a member of both SEJ and AEJMC.<P> 
</EM>


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>


<H4><A NAME="farm">Farm bill's environmental side often overlooked by reporters</A></H4>

By Duncan Murrell

<P>

The committee room was full of those swaggering, corn-fed 
reporters who always show up for fetes with the House Agriculture 
Committee chairman, rattling off acronyms and slang that Farm 
Bill cognoscenti use to confuse and confound the rest of us every 
five years.<P> 

Rep. Pat Roberts, R-Kan., (Mr. Chairman, the Big Cheese, El Patron 
de Agricultura), rubbed his shiny head, shrugged, and seemed to 
look straight at me: "We've got no problem educating folks from 
the west, midwest, and the south about the Farm Bill," he sighed, 
"but those Northeast folks... well, let's just say they need a 
lot of work." Throaty heartland guffaws from everyone but me.<P> 

Guilty, I thought. Guilty of growing up in the Northeast. Guilty 
of covering the Farm Bill for the <EM>Great Falls</EM> (Mont.) <EM>Tribune</EM> on 
a sink-or-swim basis. Guilty of not knowing the difference 
between a sodbuster and a ghostbuster. A long summer stretched 
before me ...<P> 

In 1990, the last time the Food, Agriculture, Conservation, and 
Trade Act (that's the Farm Bill to the rest of us) was 
authorized, it was the single largest piece of legislation ever 
to pass out of Congress. A daunting study in turgidity, I thought 
-- until I noticed that one word in the title: "conservation." 
Now that was something I could handle.<P> 

By my count, nine of the 25 sections of the Farm Bill deal in 
varying degrees with environmental issues. Some, like the feed 
grain title, deal with loans, payments, and acreage reduction 
programs for grain crops -- each with indirect but significant 
effects on soil and wetland conservation. Other titles address 
forest preservation and stewardship, water quality research, 
farmland protection, pesticides, and sustainable agriculture.<P> 

The part most often considered "environmental," Title XIV, pulls 
together some of the most far-reaching and popular environmental 
programs authorized by Congress.<P> 

The Conservation Reserve Program, one part of Title XIV, pays 
farmers up to $50,000 per year for 10 years to stop growing crops 
on highly erodible land or land which contributes to water 
quality problems. Nationwide, more than 375,000 farmers have 
signed up for the program since 1985, enrolling about 36 million 
acres and pulling in a total of almost $20 billion.<P> 

That's a chunk of land about 17 times the size of Yellowstone 
National Park, or roughly the size of Illinois.<P> 

The Wetlands Reserve Program, another Title XIV program, was 
established to pay farmers up to $50,000 per year for 10 years to 
create a wetlands restoration program for a million acres of farm 
land. The Agricultural Water Quality Protection Program gives 
incentives to farmers to establish water quality programs on 
their land, with a goal of protecting 10 million acres 
nationwide. The Agricultural Conservation Program gives farmers a 
cost-sharing incentive to carry out conservation and 
environmental protection practices on their land. And on and 
on ...<P> 

Despite its obvious environmental impacts, the Farm Bill often is 
overlooked by news organizations. Often farm stories are all shot 
over to the agriculture reporter -- who is already drowning in 
the minutiae of deficiency payments, marketing loan programs, and 
export policy, not to mention covering local crop yields and the 
yearly 4-H show.<P> 

A quick survey of environmental news stories collected from 150 
news sources by the daily environmental news service <EM>Greenwire</EM> 
showed that only 22 environmental stories published since Jan. 1 
mentioned the Farm Bill. In contrast, 121 stories mentioned the 
Clean Water Act and 166 mentioned the Endangered Species Act.<P> 

What's more, said Clark Williams of the Washington-based 
Environmental Working Group, stories which deal with the 
environment and the Farm Bill routinely ignore the less-obvious 
but equally important environmental effects of farm programs.<P> 

"When environmental reporters have done such stories, they've 
focused on the Conservation Reserve Program (CRP) and the 
Wetlands Reserve Program (WRP), rather than on commodity price 
programs, loan rates, and other Farm Bill programs which control 
the amount of land farmers put in production," Williams said.<P> 

There have been times, including the mid-1970s, when the 
government has sent clear signals to "produce, produce, produce, 
by raising loan rates and other things," said Williams, "leading 
to what was clearly a massive conversion of wetlands and highly 
erodible land into farm land."<P> 

If environmental reporters are to give the Farm Bill more than a 
once-over, they'll have to learn to be comfortable with the 
alphabet soup of bedrock farm programs like the EEP (Export 
Enhancement Program), the MPP (the Market Promotion Program), 
deficiency payments, flex acres, base acreages, and crop 
insurance. Oh, my.<P> 

"We know it's hard for reporters trained in environmental issues 
to get their hand on the Farm Bill," Williams said. "But we need 
more open, public debate on these programs. We need to see if we 
can find a better way of redirecting even more farm money into 
conservation."<P> 

Regardless of whether you agree with Williams, keep this in mind: 
in the downsizing, cost-cutting and privatizing spirit that has 
swept Congress since Nov. 8, proposals to convert environmental 
programs like the Endangered Species Act from regulation-based to 
incentive-based plans have begun to float around Washington. Like 
the incentive-based programs at the heart of the Farm Bill, such 
measures rely on the good intentions of landowners. Can we trust 
'em?<P> 

"Farmers are pretty good conservationists, if not the best. They 
don't like to see their land blowing all over the place," said 
Norman Sullivan, president of the Montana Farmer's Union. "We as 
an organization are in favor of any type of conservation that is 
good for the country."<P> 

Perhaps. But talking to farmers in Montana and elsewhere gives 
the impression that they'd just as soon keep that annual $1.8 
billion CRP payment rolling in.<P> 

"The economics are the most important part of the popularity of 
programs like the CRP," Sullivan said. "If it came down to a 
choice between keeping the commodity price supports or keeping 
the conservation programs, our membership would most likely vote 
for the commodity supports. It's their livelihood."<P> 

<EM>Duncan Murrell is a former Marine and freshly minted graduate 
with a masters degree in journalism from the Medill School of 
Journalism. Though currently freelancing, Murrell isn't committed 
to sporadic projects and intermittent paychecks. Rescue attempts 
can be directed to <A HREF="mailto:dvm64@nwu.edu">dvm64@nwu.edu</A><P> 
</EM>

<H4><A NAME="resource">Sidebar: Resource guide for environmental farm reporting</A></H4>

By Duncan Murrell

<P>

Got a farm story to do? Here is a brief guide to reliable and 
knowledgeable sources.<P> 

<DL><DT>Government Experts<DD>These are the people who actually 
run farm programs, who know their history, who gets what and how 
much and have more information at their fingertips than anyone 
else. 

<DL><DT>Consolidated Farm Service Agency, U.S. Dept. of 
Agriculture: 

<DD>Tim Denley, director of the Conservation and Environmental 
Protection Division, (202) 720-6221

<DD>Leslie Devers, agriculture program specialist, Conservation 
Reserve Program, (202) 720-9563

<DD>Clayton Furukawa, Agriculture Conservation Program, (202) 
690-0571

<DD>Tim Drain, Emergency Conservation Program, (202) 720-
9562</DL> 

<DL><DT>Natural Resources Conservation Service, U.S. Department of 
Agriculture: 

<DD>Paul Johnson, chief, (202) 720-4525

<DD>Bob Misso, Wetlands Reserve Program, (202) 690-0848

<DD>Travis Stevens, Forestry Incentives Program, (202) 720-1845

<DD>Dan Smith, Water Bank Program, (202) 720-3524

<DD>Dave Sawyer, Colorado River Salinity Control Program, (202) 
7720-1845</DL> 

<DL><DT>Farm Bill Web Site: <DD>The USDA publishes a wide range of 
information online. The USDA home page on the Web can be found at 
<A HREF="http://www.usda.gov/welcome.html">(http://www.usda.gov/welcome.html.)</A> 
Farm bill information can be found at <A HREF="gopher://gopher.nalusda.gov:70/11/ag_pubs/frmbl95">(gopher://gopher.nalusda.gov:70/11/ag_pubs/frmbl95).</A> 
</DL> 
</DL>
<DL><DT>Congressional Sources: <DD>These are the key legislative 
staffers who can tell you where the Farm Bill stands in the 104th 
Congress: 

<DL>
<DT>Senate: 
<DD>Chuck Connor, staff director, Senate Agriculture, 
Nutrition and Forestry Committee. Connor has spent his Hill 
career working for Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., chairman of the 
committee. Before becoming staff director, Connor was the 
committee's specialist in conservation, research and pesticides. 
(202) 224-2035; 

<DD>James Cubie, minority chief counsel, Senate 
Agriculture, Nutrition, and Forestry Committee. A veteran of Hill 
conservation wars, Cubie has gone toe-to-toe with Reagan-era 
figures like James Watt and Anne Burford. Former lobbyist for 
Congress Watch and the Union of Concerned Scientists. (202) 224-6901. 

<DT>House: 

<DD>Gary Mitchell, chief of staff, House Agriculture 
Committee. Associated with Chairman Pat Roberts, R-Kan., for more 
than 14 years, Mitchell is a free-market enthusiast, which may 
explain the free-market spin of Roberts' "Freedom to Farm Act," a 
proposal to overhaul farm commodity programs. (202) 225-2171; 

<DD>Doug Benevento, staff director, Resource Conservation, Research 
and Forestry Subcommittee. (202) 225-2342.
</DL> 
</DL>
<DL><DT>Non-Government Sources: <DD>There are many good 
non-government sources, but one of the best is the Environmental 
Working Group (EWG), in Washington, D.C. A nonprofit 
environmental research organization, the EWG develops exhaustive 
databases on everything from city dwellers drawing farm subsidies 
to PAC contributions from the pesticide industry. Though 
generally skeptical of current farm programs, the EWG approaches 
farm issues in a rigorously objective manner. The Group's policy 
analysts are Andrew Art and Clark Williams; the president is Ken 
Cook. (202) 667-6982. (Sources: U.S. Department of Agriculture, 
Congressional Quarterly, National Journal)</DL></DL><P> 


<EM>Duncan Murrell is a former Marine and freshly minted graduate 
with a masters degree in journalism from the Medill School of 
Journalism. Though currently freelancing, Murrell isn't committed 
to sporadic projects and intermittent paychecks. Rescue attempts 
can be directed to <A HREF="mailto:dvm64@nwu.edu">dvm64@nwu.edu</A><P> 
</EM>


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H3><A NAME="sej">SEJ News</A></H3>
<H4><A NAME="report">Report from the society's president: Strike sparks thoughts on 
journalism
</A>
</H4>By Emilia Askari

<P>

There's nothing like an old-fashioned newspaper strike to shake 
up an ink-stained environment reporter like me. One day, I was 
scrambling to write a masterpiece on nuclear waste. The next, I 
was packing up my Rolodex and walking away from my desk at the 
<EM>Detroit Free Press.</EM> My last glimpse of the building was from the 
middle of a crowd of thousands of angry Teamsters. Jimmy Hoffa 
Jr. was rasping into a megaphone, leading a chorus of union 
chants. A large truck driver peered down on me as I stood quietly 
listening to the people shouting around me. "I guess they didn't 
teach you the words in journalism school," he said.<P> 

No, they didn't.<P> 

In the months since mid-July, when six unions struck <EM>The Detroit 
News</EM> and <EM>Free Press,</EM> I have had some time to think about this 
profession we all have chosen. Despite the pain and disruption of 
this strike, I have not considered permanently seeking another 
career. On the contrary, I have concluded that as environmental 
journalists, we are doubly blessed.<P> 

The end of the 20th Century is unquestionably the age of 
information. With our fellow reporters and editors we are the 
gatherers, shapers and interpreters of the most important 
commodity of our time.<P> 

As environmental journalists, we have the added pleasure of 
specializing in some of the most interesting, complicated and 
explosive issues of the day.<P> 

My parents are of the World War II generation. They grew up in a 
time when technology was king and industrial growth was always 
considered to be a good thing. This growth was accomplished with 
little thought to impacts on the environment.<P> 

That time has passed. Assessing, containing and reducing the 
environmental impact of "progress" is now a billion dollar 
business. The effort touches every American  --  in factories, in 
schools, in offices and at home (where within the past five 
years, curbside recycling has become common practice).<P> 

As developing countries build economies more similar to ours, 
environmental issues can only become more important and 
contentious. That is why, during this strike, I have not followed 
some of my <EM>Free Press</EM> colleagues into temporary waitressing jobs. 
Instead, I have decided to practice my trade from home, 
freelancing environment news.<P> 

I am heartened by the results of a recent national survey by 
Roper-Starch. It found that 52 percent of the American public 
wants to hear more news of the environment. Only eight percent 
wants less. The demand for environmental news is particularly 
high among people 18 to 34, the survey showed. More than six in 10 
people in Generation X want the media to tell them more about 
environmental issues.<P> 

Our challenge as environmental journalists is to convince power 
brokers in our newsrooms to allocate precious time and space to 
trend-oriented environment news. One of SEJ's goals is to lead 
this campaign.<P> 

To that end, the first story I wrote after going on strike was 
for <EM>The American Editor,</EM> a publication of the American Society of 
Newspaper Editors. The article recaps recent poll results and 
quotes several newspaper marketing consultants, including Tim 
Holbein of the Dallas-based firm Belden and Associates. 
Environment news, he says, "warrants consistent, daily attention. 
It's where subjects like health, medicine and nutrition were 10, 
15 years ago."<P> 

Since then, many news organizations have added regular features 
on those topics. Others simply are devoting more attention to 
them.<P> 

Expect more poll results  --  and potential ammunition in the 
battle for more and better quality environment news  --  at the 
SEJ national conference during the last weekend in October in 
Cambridge, Massachusetts. As I look to the future, trying to 
picture the job of an environmental journalist 30 years from now, 
I realize how important such conferences are. They give us not 
only insights into a wide range of topics we are covering, not 
just access to top experts in many fields, but also a chance to 
learn how our colleagues in different media approach the same 
material.<P> 

I am certain that by the time I am nearing the end of my career, 
many professional journalists will not be pigeon-holed as print 
journalists or broadcast journalists. We will all have to know 
something about simultaneously using writtten and spoken words, 
sounds, images and computer technology to get our points across.<P> 

In the near future, those of us in the newspaper end of the 
business face especially tough times with a shrinking job market 
and ever-decreasing space in which to tell our stories. Still, I 
would not choose to be anything other than an environmental 
journalist.<P> 

Thanks to all of you who have shown support by calling or writing 
to me during the strike. Special thanks as well to the following 
funders who have generously given SEJ grants or other support 
since the last edition of the <EM>SEJournal:</EM><STRONG> The Charles Stewart Mott 
Foundation,</STRONG> for a new two-year challenge grant totalling 
$100,000; <STRONG>The Turner Family Foundation,</STRONG> for a $20,000 grant; the 
<STRONG>Henry P. Kendall Foundation</STRONG> for a $5,000 grant in support of the 
1995 national conference; the <STRONG>Bureau of National Affairs, Inc. </STRONG>
for a $2,500 conference grant; and the <STRONG>Swan Fund for the 
Environment</STRONG> for a $2500 conference grant.<P> 

Until I return to my desk at the <EM>Detroit Free Press,</EM> you can 
reach me via the internet at <A HREF="mailto:EmiliaA@aol.com">EmiliaA@aol.com</A> or through the SEJ 
office. <P> 


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="media">Media on the move</A></H4>

By George Homsy<P>

If you noticed environmental coverage slacking off this summer, 
there's a darn good reason. For two weeks, <STRONG>Frank Allen,</STRONG> dean of 
the University of Montana School of Journalism had 16 of the 
nation's enviro reporters tooling around Montana. The High 
Country Institute literally was "a moving institute," according 
to Allen. The first session was conducted on a bus -- stops 
included an experimental forest and a working ranch. Allen says 
he wanted his students to learn more about the economics and 
science of western issues.<P> 

"It put a face on the people and the landscape of something I 
cover from my desk" reported <STRONG>Peter Thomson,</STRONG> producer of the 
National Public Radio program, <EM>Living On Earth</EM> and one of Allen's 
16 fellows. <STRONG>Rocky Barker</STRONG> of the <EM>Post-Register</EM> in Idaho Falls 
echoed those sentiments and added that "the power of this session 
was bringing together colleagues." <STRONG>Jennifer Schmidt</STRONG> of KPLU-FM in 
Tacoma, Washington was glad to be out from behind her desk. She 
said the Institute was hard work, but admitted to some relaxing 
nights in the hot tub.<P> 

The other graduates of the Institute's kickoff season were: 
<STRONG>William Allen,</STRONG> <EM>St. Louis Post-Dispatch;</EM> <STRONG>Teresa Bell,</STRONG> KPAX-TV in 
Missoula, Montana; <STRONG>Jonathan Brinckman,</STRONG> <EM>Idaho Statesman;</EM> <STRONG>Frank 
Clifford,</STRONG> <EM>Los Angeles Times;</EM> <STRONG>Linda Kanamine,</STRONG> <EM>USA Today;</EM> <STRONG>Woodrow 
Kipp,</STRONG> <EM>The Missoula</EM> (Montana) <EM>Independent;</EM> <STRONG>Joan Laatz,</STRONG> <EM>The 
Oregonian;</EM> <STRONG>Betsy Marston,</STRONG> <EM>High Country News;</EM> <STRONG>Scott McMillion,</STRONG> 
<EM>Bozeman</EM> (Montana) <EM>Daily Chronicle;</EM> <STRONG>Tom Meersman,</STRONG> <EM>Minneapolis 
Star-Tribune;</EM> <STRONG>Jim Morris,</STRONG> CNN; <STRONG>Natalie Pawelski,</STRONG> CNN; <STRONG>Nancy 
Vogel,</STRONG> <EM>The Sacramento</EM> (California) <EM>Bee.</EM><P> 

The role of a reporter is to learn and then pass on that 
information to others. Teaching is "reporting in another form" 
says <STRONG>Deborah Potter,</STRONG> who has joined the staff of the Poynter 
Institute in St. Petersburg, Florida. Potter, who spent last year 
teaching journalism at the American University in Washington, 
D.C., has 22 years of journalism experience to draw on for her 
classes. The veteran CNN reporter already has taught reporting, 
producing, ethics, and investigative techniques. <P> 

<EM>Greenwire,</EM> the on-line news service, has a new editor. The 
publishers predict <STRONG>Catherine Cooney</STRONG> will be a "steadying hand" at 
the daily electronic periodical. Cooney has almost a decade of 
experience on the environment in Washington, D.C. Her most recent 
post was as managing editor of <EM>Environment Today.</EM><P> 

<STRONG>Whitman Bassow</STRONG> has added a line to his already impressive CV. He 
is a new columnist for <EM>Tomorrow,</EM> the Swedish quarterly covering 
global environment management issues and business. Bassow's 
career in international environmental affairs spans more than two 
decades. He covered Moscow and Paris for <EM>Newsweek</EM> and UPI. In 
fact, budding foreign journalists should read his book, <EM>The 
Moscow Correspondents.</EM> It is a fascinating history of Western 
reporters in the Soviet Union. In honor of his achievements as a 
journalist, the Overseas Press Club in 1993 added a new category 
to its awards: The Whitman Bassow Award for Best Reporting on 
Environmental Issues. <P> 

"I'd had it with New York." Those simple and direct words 
describe the main reason <STRONG>Catherine Dold</STRONG> packed her bags and 
headed west to Boulder, Colorado. The move brings the full time 
freelancer closer to the wild flora and fauna she enjoys writing 
about for clients including <EM>Audubon</EM> magazine and the <EM>New York 
Times.</EM> Editors, don't fret if she doesn't return your calls right 
away. Most likely she's out hiking, perhaps with (SEJ board 
member) Amy Gahran, also a new Boulder resident.<P> 

For now, anchor/reporter <STRONG>David DeWitt</STRONG> works a general assignment 
beat for WUTR-TV in Uttica, New York. He came east from Salinas, 
California, but soon heads west again. Next year, he'll be at a 
new station in Green Bay, Wisconsin. <P> 

<STRONG>Rich Santalesa</STRONG> has moved on to take the Executive Editor office 
at <EM>NetGuide,</EM> a monthly magazine published in print as well as on 
the Internet. The environment is very much a part of <EM>NetGuide's</EM>
fare. The magazine's <A HREF="http://techweb.cmo.com/ng/current">web site</A> contains a roundup of 
environmental information resources. Rich is interested in 
hearing from SEJ members who know where good environmental 
information can be found online. E-mail him at <A HREF="mailto:rsantale@cmp.com">rsantale@cmp.com</A> 
to pass on your tips. <P> 

An awards addendum: <STRONG>National Public Radio's <EM>Living On Earth</EM></STRONG> took 
two awards since the last issue of the <EM>SEJournal.</EM> Reporter <STRONG>Bob 
Carty</STRONG> won an Edward R. Murrow Award for his news documentary "Who 
Owns Life?" about the patenting of human genes. As a series, 
<EM>Living On Earth</EM> was also a New York Radio Festival finalist in 
the environmental information category. The top award, a silver 
medal, went to <STRONG>Nancy Wilson</STRONG> of N.W. Bell, Inc. for "Big Blue 
Planet: Wetlands History/Egrets/ Wolves/Owls." No gold was 
given.<P> 

Finally (and he admits being a little embarassed at appearing in 
this space once again) <STRONG>Scott Bronstein</STRONG> is heading back to France 
as an associate producer in CBS' Sixty Minutes Paris bureau. 
Covering Europe, Asia, and Africa, Bronstein will report and 
field produce for veteran correspondent Mike Wallace. The job 
offer was "a total shocker" to Bronstein, who was happily 
settling in at CNN. "It reaffirms my idea that you never know 
when the seeds you sow will sprout," says Bronstein who met his 
future boss last year while on a fellowship. Bronstein sighs 
happily. "It's been a long-term dream of mine to work overseas. I 
always wanted to live in Paris." Bonne chance, Scott.<P> 

<STRONG>WHERE ARE YOU?</STRONG> Change jobs? Win an award? Start a fellowship? Let 
us know. Send any professional news about you or your colleagues 
to: George Homsy, Living On Earth, PO Box 380639, Cambridge, 
MA., 02238-0639; tel: (617) 868-8810; fax: (617) 868-8659. Email: 
<A HREF="mailto:loe@npr.org">loe@npr.org</A><P> 


