<H3><A NAME="online">Online Bits & Bytes: </A></H3>
<H4><A NAME="access">Access: Rifling the NRC's online database</A></H4>

By Dave Davis

<P>

Imagine having unlimited access to the file cabinets of the U.S. 
Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC). Imagine having the ability to 
peruse millions of documents kept in offices across the country 
-- everything from technical reports, to Congressional testimony, 
to licensee violation notices -- all without a bureaucrat 
standing over your shoulder.<P> 

That's exactly what you'll get if you get connected to NUDOCS, 
the NRC's online database of nearly 3 million records dating to 
1978. NUDOCS is agency lingo for Nuclear Document System.<P> 

This searchable database is an invaluable source of information 
for reporters who cover the environment, or who occasionally 
write about hospitals, universities, nuclear power, radioactive 
waste, or other related topics. <P> 

Within about a week of issuing inspection reports, technical 
studies, fines, and conducting special investigations, NRC 
officials have the information summarized and entered on the 
NUDOCS system. NUDOCS also is an excellent source for 
correspondence, reports, and  records generated by other federal 
and state agencies, as well as outsiders such as environmental 
groups, concerned citizens, and reporters.<P> 

For example, a search for records which mention "Ohio" brings up 
2,010 hits. Plug "death" or "killed" into the NUDOCS search menu 
and 426 records appear. NUDOCS has 10,141 records generated by 
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, 46 by the Federal 
Bureau of Investigation, and 19 by Vice President Al Gore.<P> 

I am listed as the author of 21 documents, all Freedom of 
Information Act requests. This may sound inconsequential. But if 
my FOIA happens to hit on something that interests you, you can 
get copies of everything I got by calling the NRC's Public 
Document Room (PDR) (202-634-3273) and giving them the FOIA 
response number listed in NUDOCS.<P> 

It was in this way that I happened across the worst-known 
radiation accident in medicine, the overexposure of hundreds 
patients undergoing cancer treatment at Riverside Methodist 
Hospitals in Columbus, Ohio, in the mid-1970s.<P> 

I had heard about the incident, caused when a hospital 
technologist used the wrong type of graph paper in calculating 
patient exposure times to a cobalt source, but I couldn't get any 
details about victims. NRC officials said they weren't sure who, 
or even how many, people died as a result of the mistake.<P> 

Then I came across a FOIA in NUDOCS. It was filed by a lawyer who 
represented an 11-year-old boy who had died from the radiation 
overdose. Among other things, he requested medical reports and 
autopsies for others known to have died.<P> 

The letter was dated 1978. I called the PDR, and, to my surprise, 
they had the hundreds of pages of records that were sent to the 
lawyer in response to his FOIA. In a series of stories that 
followed, we published the names of all 40 people known to have 
died in the Riverside mishap, along with interviews with families 
members who said they had been kept in the dark about what 
happened.<P> 

We've also used NUDOCS to track radioactive contamination in the 
nation's sewage treatment systems and the multi-million-dollar 
cleanups which follow. We've also used the system for daily 
stories, mostly about the Perry and Davis-Bessie nuclear power 
plants.<P> 

Because NUDOCS offers only summaries of documents -- ranging from 
a few sentences to dozens of pages in length -- it must be used 
in conjunction with the NRC's PDR, which holds the actual 
records. With the document accession number retrieved from 
NUDOCS, you can call the PDR and get the records by fax or by 
mail. The cost is just a few cents a page.<P> 

<EM>Dave Davis is an investigative reporter with</EM> The Plain Dealer <EM>in 
Cleveland, Ohio.<P> </EM>

<H4><A NAME="how">Sidebar: How to use NUDOCS</A></H4>

<P>

NUDOCS is not available on the Internet; rather, it is a 
searchable database accessible through a toll-fee 800 number. The 
system is menu-driven. To utilize it, you simply need a computer, 
a modem, and any basic communications software (such as Procomm 
or ZTerm).<P> 

There is no cost for searching NUDOCS. The NRC doesn't charge for 
time on the system, and there are no phone charges thanks to the 
toll-fee access number.<P> 

Although NUDOCS was created for use by NRC officials and the 
libraries which serve as NRC repositories, you can get access. 
However, you must first request a password by writing to: <P> 

<STRONG>Gerald F. Cranford, Director
<BR>Office of Information and Resource Management
<BR>U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission
<BR>MNBB6219
<BR>Washington, D.C. 20555
</STRONG><P>

Be sure to include your mailing address. A password and a manual 
will be mailed out to you when your request has been processed. 
This manual will include information for both Macintosh and IBM-
compatible computer users. If you need help, online and phone 
support for NUDOCS is excellent.<P> 

<EM>Dave Davis is an investigative reporter with</EM> The Plain Dealer <EM>in 
Cleveland, Ohio.<P> </EM>


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="newspapers">Newspapers launch Great Lakes Internet mag</A></H4>

By David Poulson

<P>

The woman was frustrated, angry, and obviously not buying the 
point I was making as a speaker at a retreat for the Michigan 
chapter of the Sierra Club.<P> 

"I don't care," she said, after I explained that the environment 
is getting less coverage due to shrinking newshole and a 
perception that it is lower on the public agenda than in the 
past.<P> 

"You are not giving me what I want as a reader," she insisted. The 
group quickly agreed.<P> 

I left feeling more than a little guilty about their gripe. But 
that experience and a series of lucky opportunities have led to 
an experiment on the Internet with tremendous potential for 
specialty reporting.<P> 

I cover the environment for a state capital bureau serving eight 
Michigan dailies owned by Booth Newspapers, a division of the 
Newhouse Newspaper Group.<P> 

Last March we launched the <A HREF="http://www.great-lakes.net/~glew">Great 
Lakes Environmental Wire (GLEW)</A>, 
an Internet publication that is, in my opinion, the single 
greatest source of Great Lakes environmental news and 
opinions.<P> 

The stories come from our eight papers, and our bureaus in 
Washington, Detroit, and Lansing.<P> 

These stories get decent play in the papers which generate them. 
But they may be considered too local or too special interest-oriented 
to get much play (or any play) elsewhere. Yet they are 
of profound interest to people concerned about the Great Lakes 
environment who are scattered across the region and the country. <P>

GLEW creates special reports which stitch together news 
stories, opinion columns, and other information on the Internet. 
Recently we covered the reorganization of Michigan's Department 
of Natural Resources with a news story, an analysis, two opinion 
columns, five editorials, and the actual executive orders which 
created a new agency.<P> 

A searchable archive quickly provides background on many 
environmental issues. Great Lakes policymakers who may get spotty 
coverage in general-interest newspapers are given electronic 
column space. We hope to soon provide forums for readers to 
discuss the issues they raise. <P> 

GLEW's greatest value is its use as a front door for the Great 
Lakes Information Network, a virtual crossroads of information 
provided by U.S., Canadian, and state governments, as well as by 
academic, environmental, and industrial organizations. <P> 

This network increases tremendously the value of stories which 
our newspapers already have produced. <P> 

For instance, the <EM>Muskegon Chronicle</EM> recently ran a story about 
the ruffe, a non-native fish which threatens the Great Lakes 
perch fishery with its voracious appetite. By tapping GLEW's 
other resources, this story was linked to a map of the ruffe's 
spread, strategies to control it, a scientific assessment of the 
threat, and an image of the fish. Each of these "cyber-sidebars" 
required more space than a general-interest newspaper would have 
been able to give to this issue. <P> 

Instead of becoming yesterday's fishwrap, the story will always 
be in our archive for anyone searching for information about the 
ruffe, or exotic species in general.<P> 

I am a different reporter now. I have to be aware of potential 
Internet links on my beat. I urge information providers to get 
their stuff online on the chance that someday I might want to 
read or link to it.<P> 

There are hurdles. I worry about overwhelming readers with too 
much information, too many choices. And there is a very real 
concern about creating revenue to support such a service. 
Currently, we don't charge users or support advertising.<P> 

But any reporter who has had a story killed or chopped (because 
of space constraints or its lack of widespread appeal) can't help 
but get excited about this stuff.<P> 

The cyberspace newshole is limitless.<P> 

<EM>David Poulson writes for Booth Newspapers. You can e-mail David 
Poulson at <A HREF="mailto:dpoulson@great-lakes.net">dpoulson@great-lakes.net</A> 
and read the Great Lakes 
Environmental Wire at http://www.great-lakes.net/~glew<P> 
</EM>


<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H3><A NAME="book">The Book Shelf:</A></H3>

<H4><A NAME="green">The Green Right: <EM>"The Making of A Conservative Environmentalist"</EM></A></H4>

By Gordon Durnil
<BR>
Indiana University Press
<P>
<EM>Reviewed by George Homsy</EM>

<P>

Republicans always have been well-represented in the 
environmental movement. Some very strong conservationists in 
Congress today are members of America's conservative party. They 
usually believe smaller government is better, but often have no 
qualms backing strict environmental laws and regulations. <P> 

Gordon Durnil is trying to set a different course. In his book, 
<EM>The Making of A Conservative Environmentalist,</EM> Durnil tries to 
sketch out a framework for conservative environmental activism. 
The author, a leader of the Republican Party in Indiana, is 
pushing an agenda of education and cooperation over legislation 
and regulation. <P> 

Durnil, who served during the Bush Administration as U.S. 
Chairman of the International Joint Commission (IJC), uses the 
cleanup efforts of the Great Lakes as an example of what's wrong 
with environmental regulation, environmental groups, and 
especially industrial lobbying. Durnil abhors the 
irresponsibility of some industrial leaders who pollute and also 
that of the government regulators who issue the licenses to emit 
deadly chemicals. <P> 

Durnil, who admits to having thought little about the environment 
before his tenure at the IJC, is on a crusade to eliminate 
chlorine. Chlorinated chemicals (such as dioxin, DDT and many 
pesticide compounds in use today) may be responsible for a 
drastic decrease in human male sperm counts, increased incidents 
of endometriosis in women and other devastating reproductive 
disorders. <P> 

However, being a conservative, Durnil doesn't want to regulate 
such a ubiquitous chemical as chlorine. Instead, he advocates a 
more cooperative approach. Once industrial leaders are educated 
about the dangers of persistent toxics, he believes they will 
phase out the pollution. He says many high-level executives are 
blinded by their own lobbying organizations and don't know the 
truth about the damage they are causing. His comparison of 
chemical industry actions to the smoke-and-mirrors of tobacco PR 
flacks is especially hard-hitting today. <P> 

Durnil also does a commendable job outlining the debate over the 
issue of scientific certainty. How much evidence of danger is 
needed to act? In the case of chlorine, Durnil clearly thinks 
there is enough. <P> 

Sorely missing from the book is a solid argument in favor of the 
conservative way of doing things. There is no discussion of how 
free market mechanisms can reduce pollution. Durnil's analysis of 
burdensome regulations is nothing new. There is no sense of how a 
small-government, lower-taxes philosophy can translate into 
environmental protection. <P> 

Whether educated industrial leaders will stop their polluting 
ways, as Durnil predicts, is an open question. Unfortunately, his 
prediction has little bearing on how conservatives can become 
environmental leaders. That's too bad, because a reasoned, 
well-written discussion about conservative philosophy in the 
environmental movement would be invaluable -- especially given 
today's political climate.<P> 

<EM>George Homsy is a producer for</EM> Living On Earth, <EM>an environmental 
news program broadcast on National Public Radio.<P> </EM>


<H4><A NAME="wise">Wise Use Wars: <EM>"Let the People Judge"</EM></A></H4>

John Echeverria and Raymond Booth Eby, editors
<BR>
Island Press ($49.95 hardcover, $27.50 paperback)
<P>
<EM>Reviewed by Nancy Riggs</EM>

<P>

Readers of <EM>Let the People Judge</EM> will come away with a distinctly 
disturbed feeling, the kind that comes after sitting in on a 
volatile debate where emotions run high. In their preface, 
Echeverria and Eby lure us into the debate on Wise Use and 
private property rights movements with the benign statement that, 
as editors, they have attempted to "collect a wide range of 
different and sometimes sharply divergent thinking." This promise 
of different and divergent thinking is carried out.<P> 

Laid out in six sections, each containing essays representing the 
promised divergent viewpoints, the 369-page <EM>Let the People Judge</EM> 
informs the uninformed and stirs the unstirred. Jon Rouch 
explains the Wise Use movement in his introduction. "Because we 
live by incompatible values, we have created institutions that 
invite conflict." Expanding on this point, Rouch writes, ". . . 
love for the earth is not exclusive to any class, occupation, or 
political persuasion. The difficulties lie elsewhere."<P> 

The essays, which provide background on events and responses 
related to the Wise Use and private property rights, offer sound 
reasoning on both sides. Sometimes they are immediately 
identifiable as favoring or opposing the Wise Use movement, and 
sometimes they espouse less identifiable positions. We are told 
that the Wise Use movement is "a volatile mix of traditional 
conservative ideology blended with some revolutionary proposals 
to open public lands to greater private exploitation." We learn 
that the "takings," or property rights, movement, initially came, 
not out of the wide-open, rugged western states, but from the 
Heartland via a law professor at the University of Chicago.<P> 

Armed with an overview of the conflict, we listen to the debate, 
from Thomas Lewis' explanation in "Cloaked in a Wise Disguise," 
to Grant Ferrier's "Strategic Overview of the Environmental 
Industry." In an essay in the closing section entitled "Message 
and the Media", Sharon Collins notes, " ... you're dealing with 
emotion, and you're dealing with a right ... In trying to be fair 
to both sides, you sometimes get caught up in a lot of emotion." 
Keith Schneider sums up the key point of the Wise Use movement 
that journalists are concerned with: " ... it is one of the most 
compelling stories that I could cover."<P> 

Whether or not <EM>Let the People Judge</EM> will help the general public 
make decisions about Wise Use and property rights movements, this 
work of Echeverria and Eby, (both affiliated with the National 
Audubon Society) reminds journalists that both sides approach 
this debate with high emotions, and both are armed with strong 
arguments. Journalists new to this beat will be 
forewarned that artillery on both sides 
is aimed at managing media relations. The Appendices which describe various 
organizations, are excellent 
resources.<P> 

<EM>Nancy Riggs is editor for</EM> The HELM, <EM>published by llinois-Indiana 
Sea Grant, University of Illinois and Purdue University.<P> </EM>


<H4><A NAME="ad">Ad lib regulations: <EM>Tankers Full of Trouble</EM></A></H4>

Eric Nalder
<BR>
Grove Press, ($24 hardcover)
<BR>
<P><EM>Reviewed by Chris Rigel</EM>

<P>

<EM>Tankers Full of Trouble</EM> is a log of the sea-time Eric Nalder 
spent aboard the <EM>SS Arco Anchorage,</EM> traveling from Valdez, 
Alaska, where it takes on about 35 million gallons of cargo oil, 
to its drop-off point in Cherry Point, Washington, and back. A 
journalistic appraisal of the issues with all sides covered, 
<EM>Tankers</EM> explores such facets of the troubled oil-shipping 
industry as: 

<UL><LI>The human factor: as the profits go, so goes the crew. 
Now that the oil shipping industry doesn't carry the huge profits 
it once did, the size of the crew is shrinking, downsized from 45 
to 22 on an average U.S.-flagged ship over the past 30 years. The 
math is simple: the same amount of work, fewer people to do it. 
Repairs and maintenance jobs are sometimes left undone, and sleep 
is lost. It isn't unusual for captains and their crew to work two 
or even three days on six or seven hours of sleep.  

<LI>Safety regulations: with nobody in charge, safety has been 
nearly impossible to regulate. A ship may be captained by someone 
whose crew speaks a different language. It may be registered with 
a "flag state," (the nautical division of the world) of 
conspicuously low safety standards (cheaper). The ship may be 
owned by a Kansas City lawyer who is unknown to any of the above. 
The safety of the ship and crew seem dependent upon the goodwill 
of the owner (i.e., the year's profits) since there is no global 
maritime organization to enforce standards. Some precautions have 
been developed, like the IGS (inert gas system) which decreases 
the possibility of explosion when the cargo tank is at its most 
volatile. Industry, however, has been slow to respond; once the 
system was developed and proven effective, it became mandatory on 
all tankers, but it took fifteen years. 

<LI>The steel factor: tankers have mushroomed in size from 3,500 
tons to 50,000-70,000 tons with a vast increase in cargo 
capacity. Hull thickness, however, has <EM>decreased</EM> from one and 
three-eighths inch  to seven-eighths inch in a money-saving 
maneuver, with owners offering firm resistance to the proven 
safety measure of double hull design.</UL> 

Tankers Full of Trouble is written from the strategic location of 
the rolling deck, elbow to elbow with the <EM>Anchorage</EM> crew and 
officers. It's a quick read, peppered with anecdotes that break 
down the cliche image of the seaman who's had one too many, 
steering into icebergs. Tankers conveys a clear picture of the 
hazards, of profit's tendency to determine the future  and the ad 
lib regulations that follow catastrophe. The extensive 
bibliography and an index that allows for logical search is an 
added plus.<P> 

<EM>Chris Rigel is SEJ's systems manager and design 
editor of the</EM> SEJournal.<P>

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="letter">Letter</A> </H4>

<EM>To the Editor, SEJ:</EM>

<P>

I salute the <EM>SEJournal</EM> for its recent articles on opportunities 
for environmental journalists in fellowship programs at MIT and 
Harvard. Because the environmental field is so complex (and 
because those who cover it need not only current information but 
also some historical, philosophical, and scientific background) a 
fellowship experience can be truly enriching. A number of SEJ 
members have come to Stanford as Knight Fellows. Their 
opportunity to study and conduct research at a place with strong 
environmental programs, and the chance to come into direct 
contact with faculty members like Paul Ehrlich and Steve 
Schneider, have had a major impact on their lives and their 
careers. It's good to see a forward-thinking organization like 
SEJ extolling the virtues of fellowship programs at a time when 
so many employers, in a downsizing, cost-cutting mood, are 
discouraging employees from taking leave to better themselves. 
<P> 

Sincerely,<BR>
<EM>James V. Risser<BR>
Director<BR>
John S. Knight Fellowships<BR>
Stanford University<BR>
</EM><P>

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>

<H4><A NAME="corrections">Correction:</A></H4>
<P>

Kathy Sagan and the editors of the <EM>SEJournal</EM> would like to 
acknowledge the following errors in Sagan's review of Gregg 
Easterbrook's book <EM>A Moment on the Earth,</EM> which appeared in the 
Summer 1995 issue:

<UL><LI>The review criticized Easterbrook for 
suggesting that areas downwind of Chernobyl received a radiation 
dose of one-fifth of a chest X-ray. Easterbrook's passage 
referred to a 1992 accident at a "Chernobyl-type reactor" near 
Saint Petersburg. 

<LI>The review referenced a <EM>Newsweek</EM> article by 
Easterbrook which according to Sagan was "called 'Rachel Carson 
Was Wrong.'" The article actually was headlined "Averting a Death 
Foretold" and ran with the subhead, "Environment: Rachel Carson 
warned that man was poisoning the earth. Because we listened, 
writes Gregg Easterbrook, the birds are still here."</UL> <P> 

