<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>



<H3><A NAME="beat">The Green Beat</A></H3>
<P>

<DL>CALIFORNIA
<P>


<DD><EM>San Francisco Examiner</EM> Outdoors Writer Tom Stienstra took a close 
look at Lake Tahoe in a three-part series Aug 20-22. Stienstra 
found one of the greatest lakes on Earth glutted with new housing 
and the tracks of 4 million tourists a year who flock to South 
Shore gambling caissons, golf courses and Squaw Valley skiing. 
Erosion, sewage and golf course fertilizers are turning blue 
water to green: clarity has drooped from 103 feet in 1968 to 67 
feet today. And the real threat of fire from dead trees drives a 
push for salvage logging of fir forests. Stienstra's number is 
(415) 777-6405. The <EM>Examiner</EM> can be found on Dialog. <P> 


<DT>COLORADO<P>


<DD>Increasingly frustrated with what they believed was a media 
blackout on the political right's "war on the environment," some 
Colorado environmental leaders considered in April targeting 
Denver metro area dailies for political demonstrations. The issue 
came to a head on April 17 when about 25 activists and two state 
legislators held an hour long rally on the steps of U.S. Post 
Office to protest pending "takings" legislation and were ignored 
by Denver newspapers. About two weeks earlier, 45 people picketed 
the Denver office of Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell after he 
changed his vote on a measure that would have made the salvage 
timber legislation comply with federal laws, which allowed the 
measure to fail.  Again they were ignored. Boulder 
environmentalists were also angered when a <EM>Daily Camera</EM> editor 
"wasn't willing to listen" when they made a plea for better 
coverage. But they were particularly angry at the <EM>Rocky Mountain 
News</EM> after an editor reportedly told one man "we've written one 
story about takings, and that's all we intend to write. The 
managing editor at the <EM>Post</EM> apologized and promised better 
coverage, and the executive editor at the <EM>Daily Camera</EM> offered to 
meet with the activists. The <EM>Rocky Mountain News</EM> never responded 
to the threats and did not return calls to the <EM>Colorado Daily, </EM>
which was writing a story. Since then, all three papers have 
improved their coverage of the issues with the <EM>Post</EM> leading the 
way with strong editorials opposing the anti-environment 
proposals in pending legislation and featuring front page news 
stories on the Republican proposals. However, when protesters 
recently created a mock "toxic waste spill" in front of the 
Denver mining company that owned the Omai mine in Guyana, which 
flushed nearly a million gallons of cyanide tainted water into 
the Essequibo River, there was no coverage, despite extensive 
publicity before hand. For more information, contact Ron Baird at 
the <EM>Colorado Daily,</EM> 839 Pearl St., Boulder, Colo. 80302, or phone 
(303) 443-6272, ext 126. <P> 


<DT>CONNECTICUT
<P>


<DD>For more than two decades a solid waste landfill in Canterbury 
was operated in violated repeatedly of numerous state 
environmental guidelines. A former state environmental commission 
wrote in disgust that the company's past conduct reflected "a 
thorough disregard for legal requirements as well as the welfare" 
of the dump's neighbors. Yet for two decades the state allowed 
the landfill to remain open. The reason? Connecticut had so few 
other options available for getting rid of waste that the state 
felt compelled to keep the facility open. A May 29 story by 
<EM>Hartford Courant</EM> writer Dan Jones examines the costs that dump 
neighbors had to pay for society's inability to find options for 
getting rid of its waste. Further, the story show how governments 
can be unwilling or unable to enforce their own laws. For more 
information, Jones is at (203) 246-6520. <P> 


<DT>DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA
<P>


<DD>Companies increasingly are conducting environmental audits to 
asses their compliance with regulations and to check on the 
environmental efficiency of their operations. Business groups are 
lobbying state lawmakers to protect the results of these audits 
from public disclosure--and 34 states considered such legislation 
this year. So far, 14 states have adopted these laws, known as 
audit privilege statues. Many of these laws also provide immunity 
to any company that finds violations through an audit then 
voluntarily corrects them and reports them to state authorities. 
Public interest groups and press associations have fought against 
these bills, which run counter to the right-to know movement. 
Cheryl Hogue, a reporter for the Bureau of National Affairs Inc., 
examined the 1995 state legislation and prospects for these bill 
in 19996. Her work appeared in the Aug. 29 edition of <EM>Daily 
Environment Report</EM> and in other BNA publications dated Aug. 30 
and Sept. 1. These are available on LEXIS. Hogue can be contacted 
at (202) 452-4625. <P> 


<DD>George Washington University in the District pledged in a 
voluntary deal with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency to 
become a model "green" university. GWU is holding contests to see 
which dormitory can recycle the greatest portion of its trash and 
its administration is trying to cut down on paper use. Meanwhile, 
faculty members are urged to incorporate environmental issues in 
their classes. Colleen Bradford, a summer inter from Iowa State 
University at the <EM>Washington Post's</EM> Metro section, outlined the 
steps that the university is taking to "green" nearly all part of 
campus life. Her story is available on NEXIS. <P> 


<DT>FLORIDA
<P>


<DD>The <EM>Tampa Tribune</EM> in August published a five-part series entitled 
"the Cost of Superfund" that outline the mismanagement, 
contractor abuse, inefficiency and scandal that plagued the early 
years of the hazardous waste cleanup program. The series showed 
how the early history set the stage for the massive problems 
later on. The <EM>Tribune</EM> detailed how thousands of small business 
are forced to pay for cleanups when, in many cases, they did 
little or nothing to cause the pollution. In Florida, for 
instances, businesses sent waste oil, car batteries and other 
wastes to recyclers- which was the right thing to do- only to 
discover later that sloppy recyclers had left toxic waste 
littering the landscape. The businesses that sent the waste in 
many cases were shared in expensive lawsuits that consume up to 
one third of all money spent on Superfund. <P> 


<DT>ILLINOIS
<P>


<DD>The increasingly high cost of recyclable commodities made the 
front page of the <EM>Sunday Sun-Times</EM> (August 27, 1995). Business 
writer Janet Kidd Stewart profiled how rising demand is putting a 
premium on commodities such as paper and glass. The story's 
placement is significant since the Chicago Board of Trade 
commodities exchange is finalizing details on an electronic 
exchange for recyclable--the first in the country. <P> 


<DD>The <EM>Chicago Tribune,</EM> meanwhile, has been linking environmental 
with development issues in a series on the Chicago River "The 
River Reborn" (Aug. 27-30). <EM>Tribune</EM> writers charted the 
development of the property adjacent to the river and highlighted 
future growth as industrial properties are being converted into 
housing, recreation and retail projects. Although the water 
quality of the once-filthy river is improving marginally, the 
fight on the riverbanks is over whether residential real estate 
growth will supplant long industrial corridors that linked Chicago's 
commercial hub with the Mississippi River basin and 
beyond. <P> 


<DT>KANSAS
<P>


<DD>In Labette County, within a few miles of one of the nation's few 
commercial hazardous waste incinerators licensed to burn dioxin, 
two cement kilns and a large oil refiner, state officials have 
found an increased risk of childhood leukemia. Now, they are 
expanding their study to 10 counties in southeast Kansas. Contact 
Stephen Pickard at the Kansas Department of Health and 
Environment at (913) 296-8039. <P> 


<DD>The Kansas City metropolitan area, including Johnson County and 
Wyandotte counties in Kansas, once claimed to have the cleanest 
big-city air in the nation. But July 1995 has changed all that. 
Like Detroit and San Francisco, which recently had been 
designated in attainment with federal Clean Air Act provision, 
Kansas City recorded excess readings for ozone. Now, the city 
long untroubled by air pollution control programs. For more 
information contact Voris Williams at the Mid-America 
Regional Council in Kansas City, MO (816) 474-4240. <P> 


<DD>Across America by Boat. In Sundance, Utah, author William Least 
Heat-Moon told SEJ's national conference attendees that he would 
travel from New York City to Astoria, Ore. this year for his next 
book by boat. On Aug. 1, the author of blue Highways and 
PrairyEarth completed his four-month journey, crossing the 
hazardous Columbia Bar with the help of U.S. Coast Guard 
auxiliary. Along the way he passed on the Hudson, Allegheny, 
Ohio, Mississippi, Missouri, Kaw, Beaverhead, Jefferson, Salmon, 
Snake and Columbia rivers. He also was on the Erie Canal and Lake 
Erie. Along much of the way was <EM>Kansas City Star</EM> writer Mike 
Mansur, who wrote about Heat-Moon's journey and the 
environmentally endangered rivers on which he passed. Contact 
Mansur at (816) 234-4433. <P> 


<DT>MAINE
<P>

<DD>The Northern Forest Forum took an exhaustive look in its Mid-
Summer issue at the planned Kenetech windpower project-639 
turbines on 26 miles of mountain peaks in western Maine that 
would generate 210 megawatts of power. The project won 
preliminary approval in August from Maine's Land Use Regulation 
commissions. But a stir arose when it appeared staffers of Maine 
Gov. Angus King pressured LURC for the approval. In two articles, 
accompanied by a project Q&A and excerpts from a LURC report, it 
appears the project has divided environmentalists. Conservation 
Law Foundation Senior Attorney Dan Sosland defended it as a 
clean, fully studied alternative to nuclear, coal and oil in 
meeting the region's energy needs. National Audubon Society 
activist Sam Hands detailed the alleged involvement of King's 
staffers, and criticized the project as unnecessary, inadequately 
studied and damaging, both to the environment and the credibility 
of renewable energy. Contact Jamie Sayen, The Northern Forest 
Forum, (603) 636-2952. <P> 


<DT>MASSACHUSETTS
<P>

<DD>Media up and down the Eastern Seaboard spent the summer tracking 
Chessie, a manatee that left his home at Florida's Merritt Island 
National Wildlife Refuge on June 13 and headed north, swimming 
further than any manatee had ever traveled. Along the way, the 
federally protected endangered species showed a predelection for 
tight spots, cruising New York Harbor and the Narrows to get to 
Long Island Sound, stopping at the mouth of Connecticut's 
Quinnepiac River to stock up on marsh grass, and surfing in and 
out of coastal coves in Rhode Island. At one point, federal 
biologists monitoring him by satellite telemetry feared he might 
shoot the Cape Cod Canal, at the height of tourist season. But he 
only made it as far as Rhode Island, and by late August, appeared 
to be headed home; the researchers lost him when his radio tag 
became loose in New Haven. No one knows why Chessie traveled over 
1,000 miles north of his range. But some say the warmer oceans 
this summer may have made the trek possible. Contact Robert 
Braile, <EM>The Boston Globe,</EM> (603) 772-6380. <P> 


<DD>State environmental regulators spend too much time and effort 
watching companies that rarely cause problems. further, thriving 
companies are often burdened with a seemingly endless stream of 
paperwork in order to meet state environmental regulations. That 
is the viewpoint of Massachusetts Environmental Affairs Secretary 
Trudy Coxe, who in July announced a regulatory reprieve for 
thousands of Massachusetts companies. By the end of 1996, 10,000 
companies, 60 percent of the total in the state, will be freed 
from the need to obtain detailed permits which limit the amount 
of pollution the companies can release into the environment. The 
firms must still comply with state pollution guidelines, but they 
will operate more on an honor system than in the past. Meanwhile, 
regulators will concentrate on the other 40 percent who have 
shown a greater history of problems. Massachusetts officials, in 
announcing this new policy, touted as one of the first in the 
nation to truly streamline environmental regulations and cut 
costs to both industry and taxpayers. The Massachusetts 
Environmental Affairs office can be reached at (617) 727-9800. A 
public relations spokesman is John Rodman. <P> 


<DT>PENNSYLVANIA
<P>


<DD>In April the <EM>Erie Times-News</EM> published a special report on the 
Great Lakes titled "Saving the Sweet Sea." The nine-page report 
covered a wide range of topics, including  a historical overview 
of the environmental assaults on the lakes, development of the 
Great Lakes initiative, Erie's Presque Isle Bay Area of Concern, 
the Great Lakes fishery and the politics and economics of clean-
up efforts. Erie is Pennsylvania's only Great Lakes city. For 
copies call John Bartlett at (814) 437-6397. <P> 


<DD>Governor Tom Ridge quickly followed through with his campaign 
promise to split Pennsylvania's Department of Environmental 
Resources into two agencies, one for environmental protection and 
the other to manage state lands and resources. Legislation 
approving the split and creating a Department of Environmental 
Protection and a Department of Conservation and Natural Resources 
passed the state legislature and was signed by the governor in 
June. John Oliver, Governor Tom Ridge's nominee to head the 
newly-created Department of Conservation and Natural Resources, 
has run into opposition in rural northwestern and northcentral 
Pennsylvania, according to reports in the <EM>Erie Times-News</EM> and 
<EM>Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.</EM> Oliver, former head of the Western 
Pennsylvania Conservancy, has come under attack by property 
rights organizations and others for the conservancy's land 
purchases, its handling of home and cottage leases on property it 
has purchased and timbering practices on land it owns. Most land 
purchased by the conservancy is eventually transferred to 
government entities. State Senator John Peterson, R-25, a 
statewide spokesman for rural interests, said he has never known 
of a state cabinet nominee to attract so much opposition from his 
constituents. The Senate was expected to vote on the Oliver 
nomination in late September. <P> 


<DD>Don Hopey, environmental beat reporter for the <EM>Pittsburgh Post-
Gazette,</EM> is one of a dozen writers and photographers from five 
newspapers, that hiked the Appalachian Trail. Hopey completed his 
453-mile section from Shenandoah National Park in Virginia 
through Maryland to the Delaware Water Gap on July 11. He later 
joined the writers and photographers from the other participating 
papers for a triumphant collective finish climbing to the top of 
Maine's Mount Katahdin. Hopey termed it "a wonderful assignment." 
<P> 


<DT>RHODE ISLAND
<P>


<DD>The major energy issue in Rhode Island, in other New England 
states, as well as some states around the nation, this year has 
become the drive to restructure how electricity sold. Rhode 
Island wants to bring new competition to the sale of electricity, 
the way telephone customers can choose from several long distance 
companies. In the process, environmental issues have emerged as 
key issues, including: how does one continue energy conservation 
programs; encourage renewable energy; and close down dirty old 
plants that produce electricity so cheap that market forces may 
keep them open longer than planned. In Rhode Island, a 
collaborative of utility, consumer, environmental and 
governmental officials have been working on this issue. A Feb., 
1996. For more information, contact Bob Wyss, <EM>Providence Journal-
Bulletin,</EM> (401) 277-7000. <P> 


<DT>TENNESSEE 
<P> 


<DD>In June, <EM>Nashville Tennessean</EM> reporter Anne Paine examined the 
nature of public-private partnerships, chronicling the efforts of 
hiking enthusiast Paul Miller to acquire for public use a 15,000-
acre tract of forest about 110 miles east of Nashville. 
Bridgestone-Firestone owns the property and is asking $12 million 
for it. Miller is trying to mobilize all available resources to 
get the land into public hands. For information, call Anne Paine 
at (615) 259-8071. <P> 


<DD>Tom Charlier of <EM>The Commercial Appeal</EM> also looked at cooperation 
between government agencies and nonprofit groups, with tow 
articles about wetlands preservation. The first, published July 
17, told of a "mitigation bank" being established in Middle 
Tennessee. Developers, to compensate for wetlands they destroyed 
during construction projects elsewhere in the state, will be able 
to pay a fee for restoring wetlands on this 1,600-acre site. And 
on Aug. 14, Charlier reported on a proposed $4 million project to 
enhance 161,000 acres of wetlands along the Mississippi River in 
West Tennessee, State and federal governments, environmental 
groups, farmers, and the timber company Anderson-Tully would all 
be involved in the project. Call Charlier at (901) 529-2572. <P> 


<DT>UTAH
<P>


<DD>A new risk-assessment prepared by a Toronto-based firm for Atlas 
Corporation says leaving 10-5 million tons of uranium mine 
tailings in place would be safer for public health than hauling 
them 19-miles away for burial. The report is the latest effort by 
Atlas to convince the Nuclear Regulatory Commission that it's $16 
million capping plan is the best alternative for dealing with the 
tailings. The state of Utah and residents of nearby Moab, Utah, 
want the tailings removed and buried from an abandoned mine site. 
The report says removal could cost upwards of $114 million 
dollars and would put workers and the public in general at five-
times the risk of capping project. Further information: Rod 
Jackson, KTVX-TV (801) 975-4418. <P> 


<DD>The Utah Geological Survey says previous estimates of the 
potential for coal-bed methane gas extraction in central Utah's 
"Ferron Fairway'" have been dramatically understate. In a report 
issued in late August UGS says the 80-mile by 10-mile long strip 
has the potential of becoming the third largest coal-bed methane 
gas field in the nation. UGS says as many as 34-hundred 
production wells, spaced at one-half mile intervals, could be 
developed in the region. The news stunned the Bureau of Land 
Management, which has since issued a moratorium on new drilling 
permit applications. The agency says it will have to conduct new 
EIS assessments for an existing resource management plan that 
calls for a fraction of that number of wells. Further 
information: John Hollenhorst, KSL-TV (801) 575-5500. <P> 


<DD>Operators of the new USPCI-Laidlaw hazardous-waste incinerator 
are asking Utah's Department of Environmental Quality to reduce 
operating standards for emissions of the plant form 99.9999 
percent to 99.99 percent destruction.The company says the 
reduction in standards would make them competitive with nearby 
incinerators. Environmental groups say the request is a direct 
violation of existing Utah Division of Solid and Hazardous waste 
permits. Further information: Jim Woolf, <EM>Salt Lake Tribune</EM> (801) 
237-2045. <P> 


<DT>VERMONT
<P>


<DD>Vermont eco-icon Ben and Jerry's Ice Cream took a hit in a Sept. 
11 <EM>New Republic</EM> cover story, "The Evil Empire, " by associate 
editor Hannah Rosin. In a stinging critique, Rosin sheared away 
the social mission mandate of the $140 million company by 
detailing its "little white lies, mutual delusions that keep 
everyone happy." Among them: B&J announced on Feb. 1 that it had 
hired a new CEO, Bob Holland, who purportedly won the "Yo, I'm 
your CEO contest, explaining better than 20,000 others in a 100 
word piece why he is the best person for the job. Turns out 
Holland is a 13 year veteran at Mckinsey & Company and a 
consultant to several Fortune 100 companies who wrote his piece 
after B&J hired him having been discovered through a New York 
executive search firm, Rosin writes. Other such "lies" involve 
B&J's rainforest Crunch and Cherry Garcia ice creams, its capture 
of the Boston superpremium ice cream market, and its involvement 
in inner city initiatives, she writes. Yet B&J's followers remain 
loyal. "it's this kind of awestruck reverence, willfully ignorant 
of details, that fuels the Ben and Jerry's juggernaut, " she 
writes. Contact <EM>The New Republic,</EM> (202) 331-7494. <P> 


<DT>WASHINGTON
<P>


<DD>Bill Dietrich authored a five-part series on ecosystem management 
in <EM>The Seattle Times,</EM> March 26  through 30, The wide-ranging 
essays talked of the need for complexity and disturbance in 
natural systems, and the folly trying to sustain a specific 
pattern in a dynamic world. Dietrich is at (206) 464-2216.<P> 

<DD>Also in the <EM>Times</EM> July 16 through 18 was a series on 
human/endangered species conflicts by Eric Pryne, Marla Williams 
and Katherine Long. They looked at the recovery of the peregrine 
falcon and turmoil caused by protection of Bruneau Hotspringsnail 
in Idaho farmland and the golden cheeked warbler in Texas 
suburbs. Pryne is at (206) 464-2231. Mailing address: Seattle 
Times, Box 70, Seattle, WA  98111. <P> 


<DT>WISCONSIN
<P>


<DD>A Wisconsin media consortium teamed up in late July for a series 
of stories on Land use issues. Reporters for the Wisconsin state 
journal. Wisconsin public television, Wisconsin public radio and 
WISC-TV in Madison took looks at environmental problems triggered 
by urban sprawl. The 'we the people' series culminated with a 
two-hour live 'town hall' program on the state TV network. For 
more information, contact public TV's Dave Iverson at (608) 263-
2121. <P> 


<DD>On August 15, <EM>Milwaukee Journal/Sentinel</EM> environment writer Don 
Behm published a lengthy article on how congressional attempts to 
redefine a wetland could lead to a large loss of swampland in 
Wisconsin. Later that week, conservative radio talk show host 
Charles Sykes took the piece and Behm to task. Sykes claimed that 
article endoresed government efforts to protect small acreages 
that are only under water during heavy rains. Sykes works for one 
of the <EM>Journal/Sentinel's</EM> corporate brethren, WTMJ-AM in 
Milwaukee. <P> 

<DD>The takings controversy has hit Wisconsin. A Madison weekly 
newspaper, Isthmus, gave the issue front cover play in late 
August, with a story on takings legislation pending in the state 
and in congress. For more information, contact Isthmus freelancer 
Erik Ness at (608) 251-5627. <P> 

<DT>WYOMING
<P>

<DD>The Wyoming transportation department says the Chief Joseph 
Scenic Highway can't handle heavy traffic that could bring 
tailings from the proposed Crown Butte mine under one 
alternative. District maintance engineers say the 46-mile road is 
built to recreational standards, and that another two-inch 
overlay would have to be added every five years to withsand truck 
traffic. That would cost $2.5 million for each application. Crown 
Butte wants to mine gold near Cooke City, MT, and developers want 
to impound mine waste in a nearby fragile alpine area. For 
further information: Michael Milstein, Cody Bureau, <EM>Billings 
Gazette</EM> (307) 527-7250. 
</DL>
<HR>

