<H1>Environmental Groups<br>on the World Wide Web</H1>

<FONT SIZE=+2>W</FONT>hile we work on our own listings, check these other 
collections of activist sites. And scroll down for some alternative views
from the political right.

<HR>
<P><P><P>

<DL>

<DT><A HREF="http://www.essential.org">Essential Information</A>
<P>

<DT><A HREF = "http://www.yahoo.com/Business_and_Economy/Organizations/Public_Interest_Groups/Environ
ment/">Yahoo</A>
<P>

<DT><A HREF = "http://envirolink.org/orgs/">Enviroweb</A>
<P>

<DT><A HREF = "http://www.igc.org:80/igc/members/index.html">EcoNet</a>
<P>

<DT><A HREF = "gopher://gopher.igc.apc.org:70/11/environment/organizations">EcoNet Gopher</A>
<P>


<DT><A HREF="http://www.cei.org">Competitive Enterprise Instititute</A>
<DD>The Competitive Enterprise Institute "is a pro-market, public policy 
group committed to advancing the principles of free enterprise and limited 
government."
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.reason.org">Reason Foundation</A>
<DD>Founded in 1978 and based in Los Angeles,  the Reason Foundation 
is "a national public-policy research organization with a practical, 
market-based approach and an outside-Washington perspective."
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.heartland.org">Heartland Institute</A>
<DD>Headquartered outside Chicago, Heartland produces research that "has 
been used by concerned citizens across the country to cut taxes and 
reduce spending."
<P>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.rff.org">Resources for the Future</A>
<DD>"An independent nonprofit organization engaged in research and public 
education on natural resource and environmental issues."
</DL>

<P>

