<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<p><font size=5><strong><u>Business &amp; Industry</u></strong><strong> </strong></font>&#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font><br>
</p>
<table width=100%>
<tr><td valign=top><img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16> <a href="labourforce.html"><strong>Labour Force</strong></a> <img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16> <a href="industrial_development.html"><strong>Industrial Development</strong></a><br>
<br>
<img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16> <a href="municipal_services.html"><strong>Municipal Services</strong></a> <img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16> <a href="business_development.html"><strong>Business Development</strong></a><br>
</td><td align=right><img src="business_main.gif" align=bottom width=125 height=80></td></tr>
</table>
<p><font size=3><b>Open for Business</b></font><font size=4> </font><font size=3><strong><i><br>
<br>
The Early '90s</i></strong></font><font size=4> </font><font size=3><br>
During the early 1990s focus was on the CS-1 (Service Commercial) zones with emphasis on the auto-oriented 
stripmalls located on the Lougheed Highway and Dewdney Trunk Road. These services experienced a boom from 
1992-1993, while the town centre development made only a slight increase. During 1993 and 1994, however, 
concentration increased in the town centre area while the service commercial zone remained stable. </font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong><i>The Picture Today</i></strong></font><font size=4><strong> <br>
</strong></font><font size=3>The town centre area continues to see demand for retail space, particularly in the east end of Maple Ridge, between 
224th and 228th Streets. This may be due to the virtually fully leased area of 207th Street and Lougheed Highway, and 
the forecast of future residential growth in the east end of the District.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Recent developments in this area include a 6,300 square foot Red Robin Restaurant built in front of the Valley Fair 
Mall. Another development on the corner of 216th Street and Lougheed Highway is presently being leased by 
Blockbuster Video. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Two projects which have recently experienced significant leasing activity are Maple Ridge Square and Valley Fair Mall. 
Maple Ridge Square has several new additions including a Pharmasave outlet, an expansion of the Saan store, and Only 
Women's Fitness, leasing approximately 9,000 square feet. Valley Fair Mall has undergone significant renovations, 
bringing an up-to-date, attractive appearance to the mall. Additions include major retail outlets such as London Drugs, 
The Sony Store, Starbucks Coffee, and Bata Shoes / Athletes World. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Haney Place Mall, another mall within the district, has also undergone recent renovations. The addition of a food fair, 
offering a variety of foods to shoppers, and increased leasing activity have helped to enhance the shopping experience. </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Zoning</b></font><font size=4> <br>
</font><font size=3>All commercial property in Maple Ridge falls into one of the following zoning designations</font><font size=4>:</font> </p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Core Commercial A - Concentration of retail, cultural, institutional, office, recreational, and entertainment uses in 
the downtown core creates a strong town centre.</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Village, Community, and Neighbourhood Commercial Centres - Centres ranging from a single small store to a 
small commercial centre provide day-to-day needs to the immediate area. Most of this zoning is concentrated in 
west Maple Ridge.</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Tourist Commercial - Two areas adjacent to the downtown core are intended to encourage hotel and motel 
facilities, which can take advantage of the town centre facilities.</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Service Commercial Areas - These areas are geared to auto-oriented commercial uses, such as car sales and 
service, and other commercial uses that are heavily dependent on automobile access. </font></li>
</ul>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>Figure 1 - Percentage of Commercial Land Available in Each Zone Category</b></font><font size=4> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table border=1>
<tr><td width=197></td><td width=197><font size=2><b>Total Lands Available</b></font> </td><td width=197></td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2><b>Zone Category</b></font> </td><td width=197><font size=2><b>Hectares</b></font> </td><td width=197><font size=2><b>% Distribution</b></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Core Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>19.32 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>45.64</font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Service Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>10.69 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>25.25</font></td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Community Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>4.45 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>10.51</font></td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Local Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>4.34 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>10.25</font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Tourist Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>1.93 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>4.56</font></td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Heritage Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>0.67</font></td><td width=197><font size=2>1.58</font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Rural Commercial </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>0.93 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>2.20</font></td></tr>
<tr><td width=197><font size=2>Total </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>42.33 </font></td><td width=197><font size=2>100.00</font> </td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=3><b>Commercial Land Requirements / Forecasts</b></font><font size=4> <br>
</font><font size=3>Future commercial land requirements can be forecast on the basis of expected population growth multiplied by the 
current commercial-space-per-capita figure. At a moderate population growth rate of 3 percent we can determine that 
the remaining service commercial (CS-1) zoned lands may be quickly absorbed. Figure 2 illustrates this point. This will 
increase pressure for some additional (CS-1) zoning, and provide more shopping centre development both east and 
west of the town centre.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>Figure 2 - Commercial Land Requirements/Forecasts - 1996-2021</b></font><font size=4> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table border=1 width=550>
<tr><td width=278><font size=2><b>Total Commercial Land Requirements (hectares)</b></font> </td><td width=70></td><td width=70></td><td width=70></td><td width=70></td><td width=70></td><td width=70></td></tr>
