<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>District of Maple Ridge - Attractions</title>
<meta name="description" content="Maple Ridge, British Columbia,
             Your source for information on Maple Ridge!  Check out what Maple Ridge has to offer!">
<meta name="keywords" content="Maple Ridge, District of Maple Ridge,
             Pitt Meadows, Haney, British Columbia, Tourism, Business,
             Vacation, Holiday, Fraser Valley, Maple Ridge, Government,
             Lower Mainland, Mountains, Alouette, Golden Ears, Park, 
             Parks">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=5><strong><u>Attractions</u></strong><strong> </strong></font>&#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font><br>
<br>
L<font size=3>akes, forests, and mountains abound as natural attractions 
for recreation and outdoor activities. The magnificent Golden 
Ears mountains and their snow-capped peaks overlook this 
vibrant Fraser Valley Community. Come and discover a 
network of more than two dozen parks, a national 
award-winning leisure centre and recreation complex, golf 
courses, an art gallery, historical landmarks, and an excellent 
array of restaurants and shops.</font></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="attractions_main.gif" align=bottom width=180 height=181></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=2>Either select one of the pictures below for a larger version...<br>
or <img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16> </font><a href="scenes.html"><font size=2>click here</font></a><font size=2> for all of them at once. (heavy load)<br>
</font><font size=3><strong><br>
Golden Ears Provincial Park </strong><br>
</font><a href="golden_ears_park.html"><font size=3><img src="golden_ears_park_small.gif" align=right border=0 hspace=0 width=100 height=69></font></a><font size=3>55,626 hectares of playground for nature enthusiasts, hikers, mountain 
climbers, and horseback riders. This is a family recreation haven. Numerous 
tributaries, creeks, and connecting lakes are yours to explore. There are boat 
launching facilities and more than 350 camping sites. An extensive trail system 
for hikers and horseback riders makes travel easy in this naturally beautiful area.<br>
<br>
<strong>Kanaka Creek Park</strong> <br>
400 hectares of wilderness park along 12 kilometres of Kanaka Creek. The focal point of the 
park is Kanaka Falls. This spectacular canyon carved by the turbulent water is ideal for picnics 
and quiet enjoyment.<br>
<br>
</font><a href="ubc_research_forest.html"><font size=3><strong><img src="ubc_research_forest_small.gif" align=right border=0 hspace=0 width=62 height=100></strong></font></a><font size=3><strong>University of British Columbia Research Forest</strong> <br>
6,250 hectares of carefully planted and tended forest is located just west of Golden 
Ears Provincial Park. During the summer months, professional foresters conduct free 
guided tours through the demonstration wood lots, ecological, and silviculture areas 
within the forest. The many trails throughout the forest are open seven days a week 
throughout the year.<br>
<br>
<strong>Whonnock Lake Park</strong> <br>
</font><a href="whonnock_lake.html"><font size=3><strong><img src="whonnock_lake_small.gif" align=right border=0 hspace=0 width=100 height=67></strong></font></a><font size=3>Discover this year-round playground offering swimming, hiking, canoeing, and 
nature study. Facilities include barbecue pits, concession stand, covered picnic 
areas, picnic tables, play equipment, play field, washrooms, canoe rentals, and 
a sandy beach.<br>
<br>
<strong>Maple Ridge Park</strong> <br>
The gateway to Golden Ears Provincial Park, this park is on the banks of the South Alouette 
River and contains a ball diamond, picnic area, horseshoe pitch, camping sites, spraypool, and 
washrooms; this is also an excellent spot to watch the salmon moving upstream to spawn in 
mid-winter.<br>
<br>
<strong>Haney House</strong> <br>
</font><a href="haney_house.html"><font size=3><img src="haney_house_small.gif" align=right border=0 hspace=0 width=100 height=70></font></a><font size=3>An historic site built in 1878 for Thomas and Anne Haney, this home remained 
the residence of Haney descendants until 1979 when it was willed to the 
Municipality by Thomas Haney's daughter, Elizabeth Hawley and three 
grandchildren, Mary Hawley-Issac, Joseph, and Bernard Hawley. In 1979, 
with a grant from the B.C. Heritage Trust, the house was restored for the display of the many 
furnishings and artifacts of three generations of the Haney family, to be maintained in perpetuity 
for the interest of visitors and future generations.<br>
<br>
<strong>Maple Ridge Museum </strong><br>
After being inadequately housed for ten years in the Haney Library, the Maple Ridge Museum 
was opened in August of 1984 in the Port Haney Brick Company Manager's home which had 
been constructed in 1907. This historic setting overlooks the Fraser River and the CPR main 
line near the original waterfront heart of Port Haney. Displays reflect the local history and 
geography of Maple Ridge, beginning with the stone tools and cedar baskets of the Katzie and 
Whonnock Indians. Pioneer artifacts show some of the occupations of our early settlers such as 
logging, farming, fishing, and brick-making. Household articles, period clothing, and handicrafts 
are another feature of the museum, along with Finnish and Japanese items from the varied ethnic 
groups that settled in Maple Ridge. An extensive photographic archive and historic books and 
papers are available to the public for study.<br>
<br>
<strong>Canadian Pacific Rail Diorama</strong><br>
The Dewdney-Alouette Railway Society is constructing a display on the lower floor of the 
Maple Ridge Museum showing the CPR lines along the Fraser River from Ruskin to Hammond 
in the 1920 era. With painstaking detail, using plaster rock casts to produce lifelike cliffs, and 
trees devised from a variety of materials, the modellers are shaping their miniature landscape. 
The 1920s were the heyday of the Abernethy and Lougheed Lumber Company, the largest 
logging outfit in British Columbia at the time. Their extensive network of regular gauge railway, 
with its spidery trestle bridges, is shown in the diorama. The only place in Canada where a 
logging train crossed the CPR main line, brought the huge logs to the booming grounds at the 
mouth of Kanaka Creek, with log dumps for high or low water on the Fraser River.<br>
<br>
<strong>Leisure Centre</strong> <br>
</font><a href="leisure_centre.html"><font size=3><img src="leisurecentre_small.gif" align=right border=0 hspace=0 width=100 height=66></font></a><font size=3>Visit this modern facility which includes a 25-metre competition pool, 
free-form pool, toddlers' pool, two saunas, jacuzzi, four racquetball courts, 
fitness area, youth centre, and other amenities such as a waterfall and 
restaurant. The Centre is located on Haney Place Mall and is physically 
connected to the Recreation Complex.<br>
Address: 11995 Haney Place<br>
Phone: 467-7322<br>
</font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td width=480><font size=3><strong>&#147;The Beast&#148;</strong> <br>
</font><a href="beast.html"><font size=2><em><img src="beast_small.gif" align=left border=0 hspace=5 vspace=5 width=52 height=80></em></font></a><font size=3>Come, see, and enjoy this indescribable town clock located in front 
of Municipal Hall. The complete &#147;Legend of The Beast&#148; is written on 
a plaque beneath the clock.<br>
</font><br>
<br>
E<font size=3>xcerpt:<br>
</font><font size=2><em>&#147;In the valley of the Golden Ears Mountains in Maple Ridge, 'The Beast' ran and 
frolicked from the beginning of time in perfect harmony with the environment. Mother 
Nature took many hours of pleasure just watching the beauty of the 'Beast's' movement 
and the sheer joy of living that the 'Beast' projected as it ran and jumped in play with the 
other animals in the valley, without a mean bone in its body. . .&#148;</em></font> </td><td align=center><img src="anihorse.gif" align=bottom width=95 height=71><br>
<img src="clckbody.gif" align=bottom width=58 height=76><br>
<img src="pendulum.gif" align=bottom width=58 height=52></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=3><b>Maple Ridge Historical Society</b><em><b><br>
</b></em></font><a href="river_boat.html"><font size=3><img src="river_boat_small.gif" align=right border=0 hspace=0 width=100 height=67></font></a><font size=3>The Historical Society operates the Maple Ridge Museum, St. Andrew's 
Heritage Church, and the Old Post Office building. The mandate of the Society 
is to collect and preserve the history of Maple Ridge for future generations. 
Other activities include the recording of oral histories on videotape, research 
into early families, and conducting guided tours through historic parts of town. </font></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
