<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>District of Maple Ridge - Our Heritage</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=5><strong><u>Our Heritage</u></strong><strong> </strong></font>&#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font><br>
<br>
<font size=3>Maple Ridge looks back with pride on a rich heritage beginning 
with our First Nations peoples and continuing to the present. 
Symbols and images of the past allow us to learn, remember, and 
reflect. Scroll down to find some of the highlights of our past.</font></td><td align=right><img src="ourheritage_main.gif" align=bottom width=150 height=101></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=3><b>Haney House</b></font><font size=4> <br>
</font><font size=3>Built in 1878 for Thomas and Anne Haney, this home remained the residence of Haney 
descendants until 1979, when it was willed to the Municipality by Thomas Haney's 
daughter, Elizabeth Hawley. With a grant from the B.C. Heritage Trust, the house was 
restored and now displays many furnishings and artifacts from three generations of the 
Haney family. Haney House is located at 11612-224th Street. Open hours are 1:00 p.m. to 
4:00 p.m. on Wednesdays and Sundays. Admission is $2 for adults and $1 for children and 
seniors. Guided group and school tours can be arranged by calling 463-1377.<br>
<br>
<b>Maple Ridge Museum</b><em><b><br>
</b></em>Housed in the historic home of the manager of the Haney Brick &amp; Tile Co.[1907 - 1974], 
the Maple Ridge Museum displays objects from our First Nations' heritage, our pioneer 
past and the history of local industry. In addition, the Museum also houses the Maple Ridge 
Community Archives which include several thousand photographs and primary documents 
relating to local people, organizations, and businesses.<br>
<br>
On the Museum's lower level, the Dewdney-Alouette Railway Society has created a 
diorama which shows Canadian Pacific Railway trains and tracks in the setting of circa 
1926 Port Haney. Outside the Museum, the Railway Society maintains a 1940's wooden 
Canadian Pacific Railway caboose which is open to the public.<br>
<br>
The Museum is located at 22520-116th Ave and is open to the general public for drop-in 
tours from 1:00 p.m. to 4:00 p.m. on Wednesdays and Sundays. Admission is $2 for adults 
and $1 for children and seniors. On the last Sunday of every month, members of the 
Dewdney-Alouette Railway Society are present to &quot;talk trains&quot; and operate the Diorama. <br>
<br>
Tours for groups and school classes and appointments for research purposes can be 
arranged by calling the Museum at 463-5311 or by e-mail at vcp@mindlink.bc.ca.<br>
<br>
<b>St. Andrew's Heritage Church</b><em><b><br>
</b></em>Built as a Presbyterian Church in 1888 on land donated by Thomas Haney, St. Andrew's 
became a United Church in 1926 and continued to serve a congregation until 1956. In 
1984, with a grant from the B.C. Heritage Trust and the efforts of many Maple Ridge 
Historical Society volunteers, the exterior of the Church was restored.<br>
<br>
The heritage church is now used as a small community hall, operated by the Maple Ridge 
Historical Society. The premises are an excellent venue for meetings, musical events, and 
small weddings. For more information on renting the hall, please call Alice Clayton at 
467-4015.<br>
<br>
<b>Fraser River Heritage Walk<br>
</b>Follow a paved footpath from the Maple Ridge Museum to historic Haney House and on to 
Port Haney Wharf. The historic buildings of Port Haney, St. Andrew's Heritage Church, the 
Masonic Hall, the 1911 Bank of Montreal, and a 1930 Japanese kindergarten, identified by 
plaques and interpretive material, help bring history alive on this walk through the past.<br>
<br>
<b>Heritage Advisory Committee<br>
</b>This Committee advises the Municipal Council on matters relating to the heritage of Maple 
Ridge. Past and current projects include the Heritage Plaque program, Heritage 
&#147;Walkabouts,&#148; and the restoration of the Wharfingers' Office at Port Haney (in cooperation 
with the Historical Society). The Committee is appointed by Council and is composed of 
seven members who serve one or two-year terms.<br>
<br>
<b>Maple Ridge Historical Society</b><em><b><br>
</b></em>The Historical Society operates the Maple Ridge Museum, St. Andrew's Heritage Church, 
and the Old Post Office building. The mandate of the Society is to collect and preserve the 
history of Maple Ridge for future generations. Other activities include the recording of oral 
histories on videotape, research into early families, and conducting guided tours through 
historic parts of town. For more information or to join the Society, please call the Maple 
Ridge Museum at 463-5311 or e-mail to </font><a href="mailto:vcp@mindlink.bc.ca">vcp@mindlink.bc.ca</a> <font size=3><br>
</font></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
</body>

</html>

