<html>

<head>
<title>District of Maple Ridge - The Arts in Maple Ridge</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top width=400><p align=left><font size=5><strong><u>Arts in Maple Ridge</u></strong><strong> </strong></font>&#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font> </p>
<p><font size=3>Music in the park on a soft summer evening. A dynamic exhibition 
or poetry reading at the local art gallery. Whether your enjoyment 
of the Arts is by participation or by admiration, you'll find lots of 
inspiration in Maple Ridge.</font> </p>
</td><td align=right valign=top><img src="thearts_main.jpg" align=bottom width=102 height=150></td></tr>
</table>
<p></p>
</center></div>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td width=370><font size=3><b>Ridge Meadows Arts Council<br>
</b><em>Bringing Arts to the Heart of our Community</em><b><br>
</b>The Maple Ridge Arts Council, which represents 28 member 
groups, serves as an information base and resource centre for 
arts and culture in Maple Ridge and Pitt Meadows. This 
group develops interest and support for the area's artistic 
community and cultural heritage, as well as acting as a liaison 
between the Arts community, the public, government, and 
other organizations. The Arts Council offers Poetry Readings, 
Candlelight Concert Series, Arts and Crafts programs, and 
Art Exhibitions. For more information call 467-3825.</font></td><td><font size=3><b><img src="arts_in_mall.jpg" align=bottom width=153 height=87></b></font></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=3><b>Maple Ridge Art Gallery<br>
</b>This volunteer-run gallery in the heart of downtown Maple Ridge offers 13 different shows 
each year, with works by professional and amateur artists from Maple Ridge and beyond. 
The gallery strives to present excellence and diversity, with annual highlights including a 
special ethnic exhibit each Christmas and a display of the artwork of talented students from 
local schools. The gallery also sponsors workshops in Arts education, and holds a number 
of special events throughout the year.<br>
<br>
</font><b>The Peace Memorial Park Bandstand<br>
</b>The Maple Ridge Concert Band started discussing the bandstand project through the winter 
of 1991-1992. The Bandstand design work began in April of 1992 and through the course 
of the following year was refined and presented to the Parks and Recreation Commission 
before being presented to Council. By May of 1993 all the necessary approvals had been 
granted and Tom Walker, President of the Concert Band, had been introduced to the 
President of Legion Branch 88 (George Price) by Mayor Belle Morse. <br>
<br>
George was kind enough to offer his considerable talents for fund-raising. The Maple Ridge 
Concert Band had already approached many service groups, businesses, and individuals, 
so George immediately followed up the first contacts with a personal visit. He rapidly 
collected substantial donations and convinced the Legion to donate $20,000. Mrs. 
Sparrow heard of his efforts and gave $10,000 on the condition of anonymity. (She later 
agreed to let her name be known as she wished her donation to be a memorial to her late 
husband). <br>
<br>
As the preliminary budget goal started to come into view, the Maple Ridge Concert Band 
began the necessary pre-construction work. This included ordering the decorative columns 
from Oregon, letting the contracts for the structural steel work, renting a large warehouse 
for the assembly of the acoustically-engineered ceiling (the acoustic design was completed 
by the same firm that designed the acoustics for the Orpheum Theatre), painting the 
decorative railings and ironwork, painting the ceiling panels, and countless meetings with 
George Neeson, the general contractor. <br>
<br>
On-site construction began in March, 1994, and took a remarkably short 8-1/2 weeks to 
substantial completion.<br>
<br>
In the end, the final costs of the project (including donated materials) amounted to 
$192,000. This did not include more than 1,300 hours of volunteer time (176 person-days) 
and the value of the land donated by the Municipality. The Provincial Government donated 
$50,650 in the form of a BC21 Grant.<br>
<br>
The Concert Band presented the Bandstand as a gift to the people of Maple Ridge on May 
7, 1994.</p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</body>

</html>

