<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>District of Maple Ridge - Transportation</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=5><strong><u>Transportation</u></strong><strong> </strong></font>&#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="transportation_main.gif" align=bottom width=144 height=136></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p align=left><font size=3>In the past, community growth has been restricted by ground transportation bottlenecks; 
however, these transportation problems are now receiving high priority attention from the 
Provincial Government. A counter-flow lane on the Pitt River Bridge is near completion; a 
third commuter lane has been added to the Lougheed Highway; and the widening of the 
Mary Hill bypass is also complete. Further, a high-speed commuter train to downtown 
Vancouver started operations in November of 1995.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>B.C. Transit operates regular bus services throughout Maple Ridge, and provides a 
transportation link to other Lower Mainland communities. HandyDart is available for 
commuters requiring additional support or wheelchair bus services. Travelers also have 
direct access to the south side of the Fraser River with the Albion Ferry. The CP rail line 
runs through the District, and air traffic is accommodated by the Pitt Meadows Municipal 
Airport. </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>West Coast Express</b></font><font size=4> <br>
</font><font size=3>The West Coast Express made its inaugural run on November 1, 1995 along 65 kilometers 
of track linking North Fraser Valley communities with downtown Vancouver.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Five trains depart every 20 to 25 minutes during peak traffic periods, running westbound 
from Mission in the morning and eastbound from downtown Vancouver in the afternoon.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Each bi-level train consists of five roomy rail cars, designed to accommodate 148 seated 
and 155 standing riders, and a state-of-the-art locomotive. The cars are wheelchair 
accessible and are equipped with bicycle racks, computer plug-ins, cellular phones, work 
stations, and washrooms. The train also features tinted windows, air conditioning, and 
on-board cappuccino service.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>The Express runs on existing Canadian Pacific Rail Systems' track, which has been 
upgraded to accommodate passenger rail traffic, and provides significant time savings over 
traveling by car.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Passengers can purchase tickets from automated vending machines. Tickets are fully 
integrated with bus, SeaBus, and SkyTrain.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Annual ridership is projected to reach 2.4 to 2.9 million within 18 months of opening.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Public Transit</b></font><font size=4> <br>
</font><font size=3>In December 1991, Maple Ridge was integrated into the B.C. Transit System, providing 
efficient transportation on a scheduled basis to most areas within the Greater Vancouver 
Regional District. Fares paid locally are valid for boarding any bus, SkyTrain, or SeaBus 
for 90 minutes from the time issued. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Link is a community-oriented service. With a 24-passenger capacity the Link buses serve 
most of the local routes in Maple Ridge and Pitt Meadows.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Dial-a-Bus is a service providing flexible transit to rural areas, upon request.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>HandyDart Custom Transit<br>
</b>Equipped with two large and four small vans, HandyDart provides a door-to-door service 
for people who have difficulty using regular buses, particularly those with special needs. 
HandyDart now serves approximately 900 people.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>River Transport<br>
</b>Fort Langley and other municipalities south of the Fraser River are only a five minute ferry 
trip from Maple Ridge. The Albion Ferry, located on River Road at 240th Street, shuttles 
vehicles and walk-on passengers across the river seven days a week, from *5:00 a.m. to 
1:00 a.m., at no charge to its passengers. During daytime hours, two 24-vehicle ferries 
travel back and forth every 15 minutes; after 8:00 p.m. the ferries run every half hour.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>*Schedules are subject to change</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Railway Service<br>
</b>The main line of the Canadian Pacific Railway parallels the Fraser River through the District. 
This dual-track facility accommodates an average of 25 trains per day. The CPR is 
currently relocating its intermodal service yard from Port Coquitlam to the nearby District of 
Pitt Meadows. The new intermodal yard, under construction since October 1995, will 
occupy 200 acres of land between the airport and the Lougheed Highway.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Air Service<br>
</b>The Pitt Meadows Airport, located in the District of Pitt Meadows, is the only Fraser 
Valley aerodrome located on the Fraser River's north side. It is located 2.5 km east of the 
junction of the Pitt and Fraser Rivers, and serves the area north of the Fraser River from 
Mission up to and including Vancouver. The principal communities served by the airport are 
the TriCities (Coquitlam, Port Coquitlam &amp; Port Moody), Pitt Meadows, and Maple 
Ridge. The total population of these communities exceeds 220,000.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>The airport consists of one 1,310-metre and two 762-metre paved runways and a staffed 
control tower. It is the home base for three major rotary wing operations, provides a float 
aircraft dock and ramp, and serves approximately 225 locally based float and regular 
aircraft.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Businesses at the airport offer a variety of both aviation and non-aviation services. Aviation 
services include:</font> </p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>aviation support services: fuel sales, hangarage, and engineering</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>flight training</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>scheduled passenger service</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>charter service</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>avionics sales and service</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>aircraft painting</font><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><font size=3>aircraft sales and repair </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size=3>Non-aviation commerce includes a large horticulture nursery, a custom roof-truss 
manufacturer, a restaurant, and log storage. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>The last Pitt Meadows Airport Economic Activity Study, dated 1990, showed the airport 
as contributing $10.6 million dollars in total revenue with direct employment for 141 
persons and a total of 160 jobs sustained. With a new published instrument approach, and 
the completion of a key navigational aid project, Pitt Meadows Airport is in a strong 
position to compete for commercial aviation activity.</font><font size=2><br>
</font></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
</body>

</html>

