<html>

<head>
<title>District of Maple Ridge - You &amp; Your Pet</title>
<meta name="description" content="Maple Ridge, British Columbia,
             Your source for information on Maple Ridge!  Check out what Maple Ridge has to offer!">
<meta name="keywords" content="Maple Ridge, District of Maple Ridge,
             Pitt Meadows, Haney, British Columbia, Tourism, Business,
             Vacation, Holiday, Fraser Valley, Maple Ridge, Government,
             Lower Mainland, Mountains, Alouette, Golden Ears, Park, 
             Parks">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=5><strong><u>You &amp; Your Pet</u></strong></font> &#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font><br>
<br>
<font color="#000000"><font size=3><strong>The Responsibilities of Pet Ownership<br>
</strong></font></font><font size=3><strong>in the District of Maple Ridge</strong><br>
</font><font color="#000000"><img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16></font><font size=3> </font><a href="spca.html"><font size=3>The SPCA in Maple Ridge</font></a></td><td align=right><img src="your_pet.jpg" align=bottom width=136 height=120></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p align=left><font color="#000000"><font size=3><b>Mayor's </b></font></font><font size=3><b>Message</b></font><font size=4><b><br>
</b></font>Many families living in Maple Ridge have house pets. Most have dogs and cats, but many also have birds, 
rabbits, mice, fish, and others. A pet can add a great deal of joy to our lives, but it can also become a 
nuisance to neighbours. The following information has been designed to help you bring up well-behaved 
pets and to understand the laws that govern them. Here you will learn how many dogs you may keep at 
home, how to licence a dog, and other facts, such as the leash law.<br>
<br>
We have also included information which may be helpful to you, such as when to vaccinate your cat or 
dog. We will describe some of the more common injuries that can be sustained by your pet and how to 
avoid these injuries. We will tell you about the S.P.C.A. Spay/Neuter Program and what it means to be a 
responsible pet owner. <br>
<br>
A pet is only as responsible as its owner and I urge you to avail yourself of the services provided by the 
Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals and the following information. By making sure our pets are 
<b>well behaved</b>, we help to make Maple Ridge a very pleasant place for all of us. </p>
<p align=right><strong><i>Carl Durksen</i></strong><i>, Mayor</i> </p>
<p align=left><font color="#000000"><font size=3><b>Responsible Pet Ownership </b></font><font size=4><b><br>
</b></font>There are laws governing dog ownership in the District of Maple Ridge, and there are common sense 
rules to keep your pet safe, happy and a welcome member of our community. <br>
</font></p>
<p><b>Your Dog Must be Licensed</b> <br>
All pets should wear identification at all times. If your pet is injured or lost, an ID tag will ensure that your 
pet gets immediate attention.<br>
<br>
All dogs are required by Municipal law to be licensed every year, regardless of age.<i> (Bylaw No. 
5468-1996)</i> </p>
<div align=left>
<table width=550>
<tr><td width=319>Yearly fee for licences</td><td width=319>$52</td></tr>
<tr><td width=319>Discount before March 1</td><td width=319>$15 </td></tr>
<tr><td width=319>Discount for Spay/Neuter</td><td width=319>$24</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<p>Dogs must wear their tags on their collars at all times. If you lose the tag, a replacement is required for a 
fee of $5.00. There is no charge for a &quot;Seeing Eye&quot; or &quot;Hearing Assistance Dog&quot; with satisfactory proof.<br>
</p>
<p><b>Tattooing<br>
</b>Tattooing is a relatively painless procedure which can be done any time using an mild tranquilizer or at the 
time your pet is spayed or neutered. It is permanent and cannot be lost or removed. A tattoo makes your 
pet readily identifiable and provides for quick, positive proof of ownership when your pet is lost or stolen. <br>
</p>
<p><b>How Many Pets Can You Have?<br>
</b>You cannot have more than three dogs over the age of four months unless a Kennel Permit has been 
issued. There is no law governing the number of cats you may own.<br>
</p>
<p><font color="#000000"><b>Control of Pets - The &quot;Leash Law&quot;</b><b><i><br>
</i></b></font>Dogs on public property must be restrained by a leash or harness. Your dog must be confined to private 
property by cord, chain, or by fencing that is high enough and strong enough to prevent your dog from 
escaping. It is strongly recommended that cats be kept indoors for their own safety and to prevent them 
from becoming a nuisance to your neighbours.<br>
</p>
<p><b>Dogs in Automobiles<br>
</b><em>Your car is a death trap for your pet!</em> Temperatures inside parked cars can reach up to 175&#176;F 
(79.44&#176;C) on a hot summer day. Cars parked in shaded areas with open windows help, but even at 
125&#176;F (51.66&#176;C) <em>your pet can die in 10 minutes</em>. It is against the law to transport a dog in a pickup 
truck or car without proper restraint. They could be severely injured or killed from being tossed around or 
thrown out of the vehicle. </p>
<p><b>Cleaning Up After Your Dog<br>
</b>Any fecal matter (stool) must be immediately cleaned up and removed from any public park and/or 
Municipal property. Remember, excrement carries diseases and is a health hazard, especially where 
people play, walk, sit or lie. Pet stores carry disposable scoops or you can simply take a plastic bag, 
insert your hand in the bag, pick up the feces and then close the bag over them. (<i>Poop and Scoop</i>)<br>
</p>
<p><b>Animal Abandonment<br>
</b>It is against the law in Maple Ridge to abandon your pet. If you are not able to find it a home on your 
own, please bring it in to the S.P.C.A. Shelter.<br>
</p>
<p><font color="#000000"><b>Common Sense<br>
</b></font>Bath your pet frequently to prevent odours and control fleas. If you start when they are little, even your 
cat will enjoy a good shampooing.<br>
</p>
<p><b>Lost Animals - Found Animals<br>
</b>If your pet becomes lost, you should immediately call the S.P.C.A.. and all local animal hospitals. It is a 
good idea to keep a record handy of your pet's licence number, rabies tag number, tattoo number, and 
even a current photograph so that staff are able to recognize your pet. If you have found an animal, please 
contact the S.P.C.A. and all local animal hospitals for instructions. <br>
</p>
<p><b>Vicious, Dangerous or Guard Dogs<br>
</b>Your dog is not allowed to harm, injure, or kill another animal or a human being. A dangerous or vicious 
dog must be effectively muzzled to prevent it from biting another animal or human. Guard dogs must be 
kept in an enclosed area that they cannot escape from or be under the absolute control of a handler at all 
times. <br>
</p>
<p><b>Noise Control<br>
</b>No person shall allow any animal or bird in their control or possession which, by its calls, cries, barks or 
other noise, disturbs or tends to disturb the quiet, peace, rest, enjoyment, comfort, or convenience of the 
neighbourhood or of persons in the vicinity.<i> (Bylaw No. 5122-1994)<br>
</i></p>
<p><b>When Your Pet is Dying or Dies<br>
</b>Your Veterinarian or the S.P.C.A. will put your pet to sleep, using an injection which is gentle and 
painless. They can then arrange for cremation and disposal for a fee. There are also private crematoriums 
and pet cemeteries listed in the telephone book. Check with the District of Maple Ridge on burial laws. <br>
</p>
<p align=center><font color="#000000"><font size=4><b>Vaccination &amp; Worming: </b></font></font><font size=4><b>A Longer, Healthier Life for All Dogs and Cats</b></font> </p>
<p align=left>As a pet owner, you want to do all you can to give your dog or cat a long and healthy life. Proper nutrition 
and sanitation combined with regular visits to your Veterinarian are, of course, important elements of 
responsible pet health care. If you haven't had your dog or cat vaccinated against infectious diseases, you 
could be leaving your pet vulnerable to a number of serious illnesses. <br>
<b><br>
Your puppy</b> will require a combination vaccination at 8 &amp; 12 weeks of age which consists of Distemper, 
Hepatitis, Parainfluenza, Leptospirosis, Parvovirus, Coronavirus, and Adenovirus. At 16 weeks of age 
your puppy will require another Parvovirus booster as well as a Rabies vaccination. If you are boarding or 
showing your dog, you must vaccinate against Kennel Cough. </p>
<p><b>Your kitten</b> will require vaccinations at 8 &amp; 12 weeks of age for Distemper (Panleukopenia), 
Rhinotracheitis, Calicivirus, Chlamydia and Feline Leukemia Virus. A Rabies vaccination should also be 
given at 16 weeks of age.<br>
<br>
Vaccinations need to be repeated on a yearly basis, with the exception of the Rabies vaccination which 
only needs to be repeated every three years (after the first year).<br>
<br>
You should bring a fecal (stool) sample with you on each visit. Your Veterinarian will test for worms and 
prescribe any medication that might be needed. Heartworm medication should be given to dogs from May 
to October. A blood test is required. <br>
<br>
Check with your local Veterinarian for more information on vaccinations and worming and the costs. They 
can advise you on travel requirements for your pet as well.<br>
</p>
<p align=center><font color="#000000"><font size=4><b>Common Injuries/Poison Substances: </b></font></font><font size=4><b>Prevention &amp; Treatment<br>
</b></font></p>
<p>Your Veterinarian is the most important person in your pet's life when an accident or illness occurs. By 
keeping a first aid kit handy, you can help your pet until you get to the Animal Hospital. Some common 
items are a thermometer, hydrogen peroxide, gauze bandages, adhesive tape, cotton swabs and tweezers.<br>
<br>
Only buy toys for pets that they cannot destroy. For dogs, a Nylabone is an excellent choice. Swallowed 
pieces of a toy or tinsel, especially for cats, can be fatal.<br>
<br>
Do not leave socks, children's toys, nails, staples, pins, or other sharp objects lying around and don't let 
your pet play with plastic bags which could suffocate him. Unplug, remove, or cover any electrical cords 
or wires that your pet might chew. <em>They could be electrocuted!<br>
</em><br>
If you must tie your dog up, do not tie him up with a choke chain. <em>They could strangle!<br>
</em><br>
A trip to the Veterinarian might be necessary if your pet has any of the following symptoms: loss of 
appetite, diarrhea, vomiting, dull eyes, or a high temperature. It is recommended that you take your pet's 
temperature at the first sign of illness. Using a rectal thermometer, lubricate it with vaseline and carefully 
insert it into the rectum, holding firmly in place for at least two minutes. The normal temperature for your 
cat or dog is between 101&#176;F and 102.5&#176;F (38&#176;C - 39&#176;C).<br>
<br>
Wounds should be cleaned gently with warm water and lightly bandaged before your trip to the 
Veterinarian. <br>
<font color="#000000"><br>
Beware of sharp objects where your pet may walk or play. Walking or running on a cut pad prevents the 
cut from healing.<br>
</font></p>
<p><b>A poisoned animal must be treated instantly.</b> <b>Phone your Veterinarian Immediately!<br>
</b>There are many household products that can kill your pet. These include rat poison, slug bait, boric acid, 
hand soap, detergents, insecticides, mothballs, household cleaners, bleaches, de-icers, polishes and 
disinfectants, paints and varnish removers, acetone, turpentine and even some health and beauty aids if 
swallowed in large enough quantities. Antifreeze is a deadly drink; one teaspoon is enough to kill your 
companion. Tylenol (Acetaminophen), Nicotine, Drugs, and even Chocolate can kill! <br>
<em>If you lock it away from your child - do the same for your pet!<br>
</em><br>
Many household and garden plants can cause serious illness or death. Among them are Peach and Cherry 
Tree Bark, Cyclamen, Lily of the Valley, Rhododendrons, Tulip Bulbs, Azalea, Wisteria, Mistletoe, 
Daffodils, Delphiniums, Foxglove, Dumcane, English Ivy, Morning Glory, Oleander, Philodendrons, and 
Poinsettia. Rhubarb Leaves, raw or cooked, can cause death. <br>
</p>
<p align=center><font color="#000000"><font size=4><b>Spay/Neuter</b></font></font>: <font size=4><b>Stop Unwanted Pets<br>
</b></font></p>
<p>Maple Ridge, like many other communities, has a pet overpopulation problem. Because of the 
indiscriminate overbreeding of domestic pets, the S.P.C.A. handles over 1,550 homeless animals a year. 
Since homes cannot be found for all these pets, few dogs, but many cats must be destroyed.<br>
<b><br>
What are the benefits of spaying or neutering your pet?</b> </p>
<ul>
<li>Your pet will remain more healthy and less likely to fight. Spaying eliminates a female's risk of 
developing uterine infections and reduces the chance of developing mammary cancer. The male 
usually becomes less aggressive and is less likely to roam, thus reducing the chance of injury in 
fights or automobile accidents and the risk of prostate and testicle cancer is virtually eliminated. </li>
<li>There are not enough homes for all the animals. By preventing the birth of unwanted pets, you will 
prevent the destruction of thousands of animals. <em>Quite Simply - It Is A Matter of Life and Death! </em></li>
<li>You will not have to chase off all the male suitors. </li>
<li>You will not have to put up with blood stains on your carpets, floors, and furniture. If your pet is a 
male cat, there usually will be no more strong smelling urine sprayed onto furniture and drapes. </li>
<li>Your female cat will not wail, rub or dart out the door. </li>
<li>Dog licences are purchased at a discounted rate. </li>
</ul>
<p>It is recommended that you spay or neuter your pet at the age of six months.<br>
</p>
<p>The S.P.C.A. provides a certificate at the time of adoption to be used toward reducing the cost of spaying 
or neutering your pet. This certificate may be redeemed with your local Veterinarian or at the S.P.C.A. 
Clinic in Vancouver.<br>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>Some Alarming Statistics from the </b></font><font color="#000000"><img src="bulletleaf.gif" align=bottom width=17 height=16></font><font size=4><b> </b></font><a href="spca.html"><font size=4><b>S.P.C.A.</b></font></a><font size=4><b> </b><b><u><br>
</u></b></font></p>
