<DOCHDR>
http://district.maple-ridge.bc.ca:80/budget_memo.html 207.81.211.55 19970118232323 text/html 10688
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 18 Jan 1997 23:23:22 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=widener15169853629802979; path=/
Content-length: 10463
Last-modified: Wed, 11 Dec 1996 19:54:42 GMT
</DOCHDR>


<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>District of Maple Ridge - Municipal Services</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#800000" vlink="#808080" alink="#FFFF00" topmargin="0" leftmargin="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="government/../home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="government/../tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government/../government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="government/../busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="government/../localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="government/../Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=5><strong><u>Budget Memo </u></strong></font>&#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge<br>
<br>
</u></font><font size=3>The following is the text of the memorandum that went to Council with the 
proposed 1997 Provisional Budget:</font><p><sub><font size=3>It is my pleasure to present the proposed 1997 Provisional Budget. This 
Budget will provide the legal authority for expenditures, as set out in Section 
263(3) of the Municipal Act, for the General Revenue Fund, Waterworks 
Revenue Fund, and the Sanitary Sewer Revenue Fund. This Budget as 
submitted or as amended must be adopted by resolution by Monday, 
January 20, 1997. I recommend that it be adopted as the &quot;Annual Budget in 
Principle.&quot;</font></sub></p>
</td><td align=center valign=top><img src="anihorse.gif" align=bottom width=95 height=71><br>
<img src="clckbody.gif" align=bottom width=58 height=76><br>
<img src="pendulum.gif" align=bottom width=58 height=52></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=3>Highlights of the Proposed Annual Operating Budget totaling $43,502,394 are:<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Financial Summary</b> </font></p>
<table>
<tr><td width=216><font size=3><br>
</font><p><font size=3>General Revenue Fund </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Waterworks Utility Fund </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Sanitary Sewer Utility Fund </font></p>
</td><td width=95><p align=right><font size=3>1997<br>
Revenues<br>
</font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3>$33,706,545 </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3>4,223,867 </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3><u>5,571,982</u> </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3><u>$43,502,394</u> </font></p>
</td><td width=99><p align=right><font size=3>1997<br>
Expenditures<br>
</font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3>$33,706,545 </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3>3,840,810 </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3><u>4,894,889</u> </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3><u>$42,442,244</u> </font></p>
</td><td width=88><p align=right><font size=3>Surplus<br>
(Deficit)<br>
</font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3>$ 0 </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3>383,057 </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3><u>677,093</u> </font></p>
<p align=right><font size=3><u>$1,060,150</u> </font></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
<p><font size=3><b>Real Growth<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>The real growth estimate included in the Budget for 1997 is 3.0%. Real growth is the new 
construction and land development that was not taxed in the previous year. These 
assessments cover the period November&#160;1,&#160;1995 - October 31, 1996 and are based on 
the market values that existed on July&#160;1, 1996. The actual real growth will be confirmed by 
the British Columbia Assessment Authority in early 1997. <br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Property Taxation<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>a) Council has set a guideline of no tax increase for the 1997 taxation year. Therefore;<br>
</font></p>
<blockquote>
<p><font size=3>i) There is no increase in the General Purpose Tax proposed, however 
there are incremental packages which Council may wish to consider. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>ii) There are no local levy increases for the Waterworks or Sanitary 
Sewer Utilities.<br>
</font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><font size=3>b) Council has for the past two years, approved a tax shift which decreases Major and 
Light Industrial taxation up to 6% at the expense of a &#189;% increase in Residential and 
Seasonal Recreational taxation. This shift has been used to demonstrate our encouragement 
to business to relocate or expand here in order to create employment and growth benefits. 
Council must determine if they wish a further tax shift in 1997. <br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3>c) Debt Levy </font></p>
<p><font size=3>There will be a small reduction in the debt levy due to an increase in real growth and 
negligible change in our debt charges. <b><br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>d) Waterworks Utility </font></p>
<p><font size=3>This Budget contains a $10.00 user fee increase to provide for the phasing of the rate 
increases that are required for the system and safety improvement being undertaken by the 
Greater Vancouver Water District. These improvement programs will continue to increase 
water supply fees in the future. <br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3>e) Sanitary Sewer Utility </font></p>
<p><font size=3>The Greater Vancouver Sewage and Drainage District has commenced major treatment 
plant modernizing and upgrading from primary treatment to secondary treatment that will 
notably reduce the pollution entering the Fraser River. This is a multi-million dollar 
undertaking which will result in future user fee increases. Due to a slower construction pace 
and the implementation of Regional Development Cost Charges the anticipated 1997 user 
fee increase is deferred. <br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3>f) Recycling Levy </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Due to public demand and the Regional mandate to reduce solid waste, this proposed 
budget includes the provision for recycling plastics at the Recycling Depot. A parcel charge 
increase of $2.00 is required to cover the cost of this service.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Provincial Government Unconditional Grants<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>Provincial Government Unconditional Grants represent Local Government access to sales 
tax and resource revenues which the local levels are restricted from taxing directly. The 
Unconditional Grant for 1996 was $2,188,837 which is equal to 11.6% of property 
taxation. Property taxation is considered the most regressive form of taxation and therefore, 
these grants are a very important component of our revenue base. Due to the economic 
conditions faced by the Provincial Government we can expect to have major reductions in 
the Unconditional Grants over the next three years. This proposed budget includes a 50% 
reduction for 1997 (total grant of 1.1 million); and it is very important to recognize that 
further reductions in this area appear likely in subsequent years.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Railway Taxation<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>The Provincial Government Bill 55 reduced assessments for railways and imposed taxing 
caps on tax rates. While we are not affected by the cap, the assessment reductions result in 
a $60,000 revenue loss.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Investment Income<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>The sharp fall in interest rates required that we cut our investment income expectations by 
$325,000 to more reflect the likely longer term interest rates. The expected interest rates in 
1997 are lower than this level and therefore in line with our stabilization policy, this budget 
includes a $200,000 appropriation of surplus to cover the 1997 shortfall.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Manpower Increases<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>Due to the uncertainty of Provincial Government Grants over the next several years and the 
pressures for no tax increase there are no new positions in this budget. We have eliminated 
four previously budgeted positions and several temporary labour hours. A program of 
attrition management to assess vacant positions has been implemented.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Collective Employment Agreement<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>The current three year union employment contract expires March 31, 1997.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Capital Program<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>We have previously targeted 12% of property tax revenue to be allocated to capital 
improvements from the General Revenue Fund. We have reduced this allocation to 10% for 
1997 and future years. <br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>Development Activity<br>
</b></font></p>
<p><font size=3>The revenue generated from land development and building was down in 1996 from our 
previous highs. We expect a slight improvement in 1997, but we have significantly revised 
our revenue projections downward, especially in Engineering subdivision inspections.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3>This document translates policy into specific levels of service. It also is a communication 
document on how tax dollars and user fees are allocated for our fiscal year that ends 
December 31, 1997. To more actively prepare for financial uncertainty in the future a 
formal business planning approach will be brought forward to Council in the first quarter of 
1997. The purpose of the business plan is to establish a process to systematically review all 
programs, assess service levels in detail, review partnership or other service delivery 
options that may be available, and develop performance measures to ensure the 
effectiveness and efficiency of expenditures. In the interim, the proposed budget meets the 
guidelines of Council and is recommended for adoption by Council.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3>Respectfully submitted,<br>
<br>
<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=3>Robert W. Robertson, A.I.C.P., M.C.I.P.<br>
Chief Administrative Officer </font></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
</body>

</html>


