<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td><p align=center><a href="home.html"><font size=2><img src="home.gif" alt="Home" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="tourism.html"><font size=2><img src="tourism_icon.gif" alt="Tourism" align=bottom width=88 height=20></font></a><a href="government.html"><font size=2><img src="government_icon.gif" alt="Government" align=bottom width=100 height=20></font></a><a href="business.html"><font size=2><img src="busines_icon.gif" alt="Business" align=bottom width=80 height=20></font></a><a href="localnews.html"><font size=2><img src="localnews_icon.gif" alt="Local News" align=bottom width=93 height=20></font></a><a href="contact.html"><font size=2><img src="Contact_icon.gif" alt="Contact" align=bottom width=79 height=20></font></a><font size=2> </font></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=550>
<tr><td valign=top><font size=5><strong><u>Finance</u></strong></font> &#149; <font size=4><u>District of Maple Ridge</u></font><br>
<br>
</td><td align=right><img src="finance.gif" align=bottom width=117 height=97></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=3><b>District Financial Results Show Prudence, Careful Planning<br>
</b>At a time when people want more value for their tax dollar, the District of Maple Ridge is 
meeting the challenge. Property taxes for general operating services have remained frozen at 
1993 levels and the District has taken a creative and strong approach to improving service 
while reducing expenses. The District has achieved numerous successes through innovation, 
business process improvements and technological advances.<br>
<br>
These innovations and improvements include adopting a more flexible, customer service 
driven model, more efficient software and computer support, and streamlining of staff time 
and work methods. These achievements come at a time when all governments are facing 
pressure to develop a revenue structure that meets demands for new or enhanced services, 
and to accommodate the escalating cost of existing services.<br>
<br>
Municipalities face special challenges in trying to meet both the need for more services and 
less taxation. There is a fundamental difference between the impact of a 0% increase for a 
municipality compared to the federal or provincial governments. For senior governments, a 
0% change in the tax rates has a built in inflationary increase. Their revenues rise as the 
economy grows. <br>
<br>
At the municipal level, however, a 0% property tax change, provides no additional revenues 
to offset inflationary costs of service delivery. For example, in 1995 our tax revenue 
increased by $829,000 or 3.8% due only to favourable growth - more new residents 
buying properties. However, growth brings with it cost increases and pressures to provide 
more services. Fire and police service costs for example, increased 8.7% during the same 
period as the 3.8% increase in tax revenues. Says Jake Sorba, municipal Director of 
Finance, &quot;Even if we had no growth, we would still have service costs and inflation. 
Residents are getting very good value for their money.&quot;<br>
<br>
Most of the consolidated surplus for 1995 was a result of the treatment of capital and 
reserve funds. Operating funds, on which taxation and fees are based showed only a 
moderate surplus; the Waterworks Utility Fund had an operating deficit, and the Sanitary 
Sewer Utility Fund an operating surplus.<br>
<br>
The District's Sewer and Water Funds are run like separate companies, and like any 
business, they must pay for themselves. Significant cost increases have occurred over the 
years to pay for new mains, treatment plants and other infrastructure. As Maple Ridge 
grows, and environmental concerns become ever more of a priority, cost increases for 
efficient infrastructure will continue. Like private business, in order for sewer and water 
services to continue to be reliable and to be poised to meet future demand, they must show 
a profit. <br>
<br>
Revenue sources for Maple Ridge include tax money from senior governments, grants, user 
fees and licence and permit fees. However, the major source of revenue for Maple Ridge is 
property taxes and the largest tax class is Residential. Interestingly, actual tax revenue, 
adjusted for inflation and growth, has remained flat or declined since 1986! In fact, Maple 
Ridge residents enjoy one of the lowest general municipal taxes in the province. The District 
intends to remain vigilant in regard to Residential taxes, and to encourage a competitive cost 
structure for growth in the Business and Industrial sectors.<br>
<br>
As a part of the Official Community Plan review conducted last year, the District undertook 
a comprehensive public opinion poll. The Angus Reid results reported that &quot;Surprisingly , in 
this period of tax protests, and criticism of government expenditure, most Maple Ridge 
residents are satisfied with the municipal services they receive and the value for their tax 
dollars paid.&quot; In 1995, Maple Ridge received the prestigious Canadian Award for Financial 
Reporting (CAnFR) based on financial reporting and the Distinguished Budget Presentation 
Award for budgeting. These awards recognized the District's commitment to quality and the 
highest standards.<br>
<br>
In order to meet the challenges of the future Maple Ridge must remain cognizant of factors 
such as declining federal transfer payments to provinces that may result in downloading of 
costs to local governments, aging infrastructure requiring increased maintenance and the 
increasing pressures of growth to provide increasing services. The District is poised to meet 
those challenges. Residents can obtain a copy of the 1995 Comprehensive Annual Report 
from the Finance Department at Municipal Hall.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><br>
</font></p>
</td></tr>
</table>
