<head>
<TITLE>Career Development Information For Prospective Students</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<H2>Career Development Information For Prospective Students</H2>
The Career Development Office (CDO) provides a full range of services to support the career decision-making process.  Students, graduates, and prospective employers are served through a wide variety of programs including:  job vacancy announcements; newsletters on current career information; individual and group counseling on resume preparation, self-assessment, interviewing skills development, and job-search strategy; a career development resource library; an alumni career network; and seminars and panel presentations covering legal career topics as well as alternative career options.  Students are further served through significant employer-support programs such as fall campus interviewing, off-campus regional interviewing, and a resume referral system in the Spring.
<p>
The CDO's priority is to serve the career needs of all students and alumni.  With that in mind, it is important that you know, no matter what your status - prospective student, present student, experienced alumna/us - that the job market of 1996-97 is an incredibly competitive field.  According to the most recent employment statistics reported to the National Association for Law Placement, for the class of 1995 39,305, law students graduated from the 177 ABA-accredited law schools across the nation.  
<P>
We at the CDO believe it is imperative that you investigate your decision to become a lawyer thoroughly and research not only your law institution of choice, but also the nature of the job market today and predictions for employment in the future.
<P>
Attending law school is a serious consideration.  We hope that you will consider The George Washington University Law School.   

<H3>GENERAL SUPPORT ACTIVITIES</H3>

The Career Development Office commits considerable financial and personnel resources to a variety of support activities.  These activities are geared toward in-depth job seeking support for the general student body, especially those whose interests are not served through job fair- type interviewing programs.


	<H3>1.  Job Vacancy Advertising</H3>

During the 1995 calendar year, the Career Development Office processed and advertised approximately 3,500 legal job vacancies to which students and alumni could directly apply.  These opportunities included summer positions, part-time jobs during the academic year, experienced lawyer positions, full-time positions for evening division students, entry-level attorney positions, judicial clerkships, internships, and opportunities to teach.

	<H3>2.  Individual and Group Counseling</H3>

An integral component of office services is individual and group counseling.  Professional staff members meet personally with hundreds of students and alumni each year to provide valuable guidance in the job-search process.  Counseling takes many forms and includes "basic tools" preparation (resumes, cover letters, application procedures, etc.), employment market insight (career options, interpreting organizational research, and job-search strategy), and personal career counseling (self-assessment, and skills recognition and development).  Between July, 1995 and February, 1996 the office staff spent over 650 hours providing individual counseling assistance to students and alumni.


	<H3>3.  Career Development Resource Library and Reference Files</H3>

Through the Career Development Office Resource Library, students and graduates gain access to a wealth of materials supporting the legal job search.  The library collection includes over 350 books and directories providing information on legal career planning, employment trends and statistics, employer profiles, prospective employer contact information, alternative careers, state bar exam application information, review courses, standard application procedures to government agencies, educational opportunities in the U.S. and abroad, subscriptions to legal periodicals including magazines, newsletters, bulletins and newspapers, and handout materials on job-search basics such as resume writing, interviewing, and cover letter preparation.

	<H3>4.  Skill Development Workshops</H3>

Frequently during the academic year, the Career Development Office sponsors informational seminars and workshops to which the student body is invited.  Workshop topics cover such items as effective resume writing, networking, preparing standard federal government employment application forms, and successful interviewing skills.

	<H3>5.  Bi-Weekly Newsletter, the Career Development Office Student Handbook, and Informational Handouts</H3>

The Noteworthy newsletter is published twice monthly and distributed to students in an attempt to keep them informed of upcoming programs, general career news, trends in hiring, changes in bar examination rules, deadlines, and other pertinent information.  To facilitate student job-search preparation, the Career Development Office has composed a number of 
valuable resource handouts on preparing resumes, interviewing, selecting references, federal application forms completion, and cover letter writing.  Students may secure these materials at any time by visiting the Career Development Office.  The Career Development Office Student Handbook provides students with insight into office services, policies and practices.


	<H3>6.  Graduate Career Opportunities Newsletter</H3>

The Graduate Career Opportunities Newsletter is published bi-weekly and is distributed free of charge to alumni at their individual request.  The Newsletter announces vacant positions that require law school graduation and legal experience.  Positions are advertised for many locations across the country, and include all those brought to the attention of the Career Development Office.


	<H3>7.  Specialized Recruiting Efforts for Particular Populations</H3>

Within the law school exist several student populations facing unique considerations in the job-search process.  They include such groups as foreign students, minority students, evening students, LL.M. students, and students with a specialized legal career focus.  The Career Development Office provides support in the form most suited to the particular student group.  Minority students are served through the Minority Clerkship Student Internship Program and the Minority Mock Interview Program.  Foreign students receive individual assistance resulting in targeted letters to specific employers.  Evening students are served through the Evening Express, a series of programs that addresses the special concerns of evening students.


	<H3>8.  Mock Interview Program</H3>

The purpose of mock interviews is to aid students in developing sharp interviewing skills by placing them in a simulated interview situation.  The 20-minute videotaped interviews are conducted by local attorneys (usually GW law school alumni) and legal recruiters who are proficient in this practice.  Students, under the guidance of a career consultant, review their taped session in order to gain insight into personal style and interview strengths or weaknesses, and develop new strategies for improving individual interview techniques.  This past semester, the CDO conducted four days of mock interviewing with seventy-two students participating in the program.


	<H3>9.  Legal Career Panels/Brown Bag Lunches</H3>

The Career Development Office offers a series of presentations geared for first-year law students.  Alumni employed in different areas of legal practice (large firm, small firm, corporations, Capitol Hill/associations, alternative careers, public interest, and federal government/judicial) share their experiences and offer information about their practices as well as specific practice areas.  


	<H3>10.  Alumni Career Network</H3>

The George Washington University Law School Alumni Career Network is a resource that facilitates alumni and student career exploration.  The Network, national in scope, is comprised of law school graduates who have agreed to be a contact for students and fellow alumni in need of career information and advice.  Networkers conduct informational interviews with alumni in order to investigate practice areas, geographic areas, employers, employment trends and alternative career options.  Over 1,000 alumni are members of the Network.

	<H3>13.  Pro Bono Students America</H3>

Pro Bono Students America (PBSA) is a national network of pro bono and public interest programs.  Its mission is to help match law students and public interest organizations seeking student assistance on pro bono or public interest projects.  In conducting a search with PBSA, students specify the issues they want to work on, the kind of experience they're looking for, the hours they want to work, etc.  After students select their top three choices, the PBSA Coordinator forwards their resume to the organizations in order of preference.  Students are asked to commit at least five hours a week and a total of 50 hours a semester.


	<H3>12.  Small Firm Initiatives</H3>

Small law firms traditionally recruit as the need arises rather than participate in organized interview programs.  In order to assist small firm employers, the Career Development Office posts job announcements and/or collects resumes upon request.  In the spring, the Career Development Office targets GW alumni in small DC area law firms, collecting resumes from students seeking small firm employment and matching students and firms by practice area.   


	<H3>13.  Alternative</H3>

In recent years students and alumni have increasingly been interested in exploring careers which are not traditional.  The CDO attempts to provide information and programming to those interested in exploring this career option.  Panel presentations by alumni in legal and non-legal positions including corporations, non-profit organizations, higher education and publishing are offered.  Resources housed in the CDO Resource Library further assist students investigating alternative careers.  The Alumni Network is a wonderful resource for identifying examples of such types of careers.


<H3>INTERVIEWING PROGRAMS OFFERED BY THE CAREER DEVELOPMENT OFFICE</H3>

In addition to the general support activities, the Career Development Office administers campus, regional, and cooperative interviewing programs which provide actual job interviewing opportunities to a wide segment of the student population.  In 1995-96 approximately 620 employers participated in at least one of the five interviewing programs which are outlined in detail below.


	<H3>1.  Fall Interviewing Program</H3>

The Career Development Office organizes a strong fall interviewing program.  Over 250 participating employers represented 24 states and the District of Columbia.  Interviewing organizations primarily included law firms.  Legal services offices, corporations, government agencies, accounting firms, and District Attorneys' offices also participate to a lesser degree.  Approximately 74 employers unable to interview through the formal Fall Interviewing Program requested that the Career Development Office collect resumes for their review and follow-up.  Other employers requested that students contact them directly.  Through this direct-write process approximately 100 summer positions and permanent positions for students were listed.

	<H3>2.  Regional Interviewing Programs</H3>

Regional interviewing programs provide opportunities for students to interview with prospective employers in selected or targeted geographic locations across the country.  During Fall 1995, the Career Development Office conducted regional off-campus interviewing programs in Chicago, Los Angeles, New York City and Philadelphia.  In 1996, we are adding two programs in Atlanta and San Francisco.  
<P>
Regional programs supplemented the campus interviewing process by providing students exposure to 65 firms and organizations that did not otherwise interview through Fall Interviewing Program.  Employers likewise benefitted from this effort by seeing qualified candidates who might have been overlooked as a result of the organization's limited campus recruitment program.  Students participating in "regionals" cover their own travel and other personal expenses.

</font>

<p>
