<html>
<head>
<TITLE>Student Activities</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<H2>Student Organizations</H2>

<H3>The Advocate</H3>

The Advocate is the student-run news-paper of the Law School. Published bi-weekly in fourteen issues annually, The Advocate provides students and faculty with news about and of interest to the school, and allows members of the Law School community to voice their opinions and engage in dialogue through commentaries and editorials. Each year The Advocate has a staff of about 50 students, and all are welcome to make contributions for publication.

<H3>Amnesty International Legal Support Group</H3>
The Amnesty International Legal Support Group of the Law School was founded in 1987. It is affiliated with the Amnesty International Legal Support Network, which includes law students, lawyers, and judges. The Legal Support Group s activities include working for the release of imprisoned lawyers and other prisoners of conscience with legal concerns. This involves distributing human rights information at the law school and coordinating student letter-writing to government officials for the release of prisoners of conscience and to members of Congress for passage of laws supporting human rights. The Legal Support Group also presents lectures and panel discussions on human rights by lawyers and other experts in the field.

<H3>Asian/Pacific American Law Students Association (APALSA)</H3>
APALSA is a national organization for Asian/Pacific American and other interested law students. Its goals are to provide academic and social support for incoming as well as continuing students, to assist members in job searches, and to increase Asian/Pacific American enrollment at the Law School. APALSA holds various workshops throughout the semester to help students better orient themselves in this new environment and has instituted a "buddy system," whereby second- and third-year students act as friend/adviser/confidant to first-year students. APALSA fosters a sense of community among Asian/Pacific American students by hosting various social events within the Law School itself or with other APALSA chapters in the region and participating in the yearly National APALSA convention.

<H3>Black Law Students Association (BLSA)</H3>

BLSA, with a membership of over 100 students of African descent, sponsors academic, career-oriented, social, and community activities and services. BLSA is an official chapter of the National Black Law Student Association, and provides academic support and encouragement to minority students through programs that include exam writing workshops, brief writing seminars, and oral argument practice sessions. BLSA's career-oriented activities include job fairs at national and regional conventions, networking forums with the Black Law Alumni Association, and seminars on networking skills. BLSA's involvement in community service, which includes the group s Adopt-A-School program and annual clothes drive for the homeless, is aimed at educating minorities in Washington, D.C., area schools about opportunities in the field of law and 
providing legal and non-legal services to the D.C. community. In order to help promote and support a diverse student body at the law school, BLSA members participate in the recruitment of minority students and provide information to the Law School community about the contributions of members of the African-American community to the field of law. BLSA also sponsors extracurricular activities through its Buddy program and social functions with other area law school BLSA chapters.

<H3>Christian Law Association (CLA)</H3>
CLA brings Christian students together both socially and intellectually, sponsoring weekly fellowship hours and Bible study. The organization also has sponsored Christmas and Easter fellowships with the University s Ecumenical Christian Ministry. CLA is a member of the Christian Legal Society, a national organization of jurists, lawyers, and students, with law school chapters throughout the country. This year, CLA will co-sponsor speakers and activities with similar groups at other law schools and with the Christian Legal Society. During the Law School's first-year orientation program, CLA sponsors a new members outreach. All students who are interested in Christian and church-state issues are encouraged to join CLA.

<H3>Environmental Law Association (ELA)</H3>
ELA's most visible activity is the publication of The Environmental Voice -- an environmental law news-letter written and edited each term by the organization's members. In the fall, ELA sponsors an Environmental Law Career Day. Other activities include camping trips, the sponsoring of speakers from various government and private environmental organizations, on-campus Earth Day activities, and promoting recycling. Members are also encouraged to participate in a yearly national meeting of environmental law associations.

<H3>Evening Law Students Association (ELSA)</H3>
ELSA's membership, consisting of students in the Law School s evening division, reflects a broad diversity of experiences and viewpoints.  Many ELSA members began law school after enjoying successful careers, and a large number continue to work while they attend school.  Because many student organization meetings, clinic responsibilities, and law school events occur during times when evening students are unable to attend, ELSA was formed to give these students an opportunity to participate more fully in campus activities.  ELSA has sponsored many of 
its own events, including a symposium on how to publish written works, a networking event with alumni in the Washington area, visits of of prominent speakers such as Law School evening graduate and former Attorney General William Barr, and a number of social events.  ELSA also serves as an advocate for evening students with the law school administration, seeking to ensure equality of treatment and an understanding of the special circumstances of evening students.

<H3>The Federalist Society</H3>
The Federalist Society for Law and Public Policy Studies is a group of conservatives and libertarians interested in the current state of the legal order.  It is founded on the principles that the state exists to preserve freedom, that the separation of government powers is central to our Constitution, and that it is emphatically the province and duty of the judiciary to say what the law is, not what it should be.  The Society seeks both to promote an awareness of these principles and 
to further their application through it activities.  This entails reordering priorities within the legal system to place a premium on individual liberty, tradition-al values, and the rule of law.  
It also requires restoring the recognition of the importance of these norms among lawyers, judges, and law professors. In working to achieve these goals,the Society has created a conservative intellectual network that extends to all levels of the legal community.

<H3>George Washington Entertainment and Sports Law Association (GWESLA)</H3>
GWESLA provides students interested in entertainment and sports law with a forum for expanding their knowledge in the field.  The organization sponsors workshops, lectures, and panel discussions featuring prominent figures in the entertainment and sports industries.  These programs focus on the basic mechanics of entertainment and sports law by addressing areas such as copyrights, trademarks, contract negotiations, athlete and artist representation, licensing, and endorsements.  GWESLA also provides students with information regarding legal career opportunities, assists with research and networking and informs students of any conferences, forums, and competitions regarding entertainment and sports law.

<H3>Hispanic Law Student Association (HLSA)</H3>
HLSA provides support and educational services to Hispanic and other students at the Law School while fostering an appreciation for Hispanic language and culture. HLSA also encourages its members to become involved in public interest organizations in the D.C. area, particularly the D.C. Law Students in Court program and Ayuda. HLSA activities have included hosting speakers to discuss career and legal topics, and holding meetings to provide support and assistance to first-year students with summer job searches, moot court competitions, and final examinations. HLSA also sponsors several social events each year. All students are welcome to participate in HLSA, especially those who have an interest in Latin American cultures or the Spanish language. 

<H3>International Law Society (ILS)</H3>
ILS is one of the largest and most active student organizations at the Law School. Throughout the year, ILS presents guest speakers, sponsors social functions, and promotes career development activities such as resume drops.  Each year ILS co-hosts the International Law Weekend with Georgetown University Law Center. This two-day event offers professional and social activities including visits to D.C. law firms for discussions with partners and associates in international practice, a career fair of international public agencies, a keynote address, panel discussions, and an embassy reception.  Last year s panels addressed Bosnia, NAFTA, the environment, and human rights.  ILS invites all students interested in international law to become active members.
<H3>
Jewish Law Students Association (JLSA)</H3>
JLSA brings Jewish law students together both socially and intellectually. JLSA sponsor a number of happy hours in conjunction with other area law schools, including Georgetown and American Universities, and arranges for speakers to come to the Law School to discuss Jewish/American legal concerns on current political issues. JLSA also provides Jewish law students with  information regarding the celebration of Jewish holidays in D.C. and Jewish events around town. JLSA works with the GW Hillel, which provides many resources, activities, and programming ideas. The Hillel is also the location of the only Kosher restaurant in the District and functions as a food co-op for kosher meat and other products. JLSA is a member of the National Law Students Network, which links Jewish law students throughout the nation and promotes Jewish awareness and education. 

<H3>Lambda Law </H3>
Lambda Law is an organization of law students interested in gay and lesbian legal issues, employment concerns, and the fostering of tolerance and awareness on campus. The organization provides a network for professional and social interaction between students with similar interests. Since its foundation in 1989, Lambda Law has become a visible and active force at the Law School. Lambda Law's dual commitment to providing a tolerant social climate for gay and lesbian students and fostering policy changes within the University is evident from the diversity of the group s activities. Recent activities include: successfully working to include "sexual orientation" 
in GW's anti-discrimination policy, organizing a panel discussion on hate crimes legislation, successfully protesting military policy against gays and lesbians so that the DOD's recruiting activities are now conducted off campus, developing and implementing Career Development Office procedures to deal with the needs of gay and lesbian students, attending national gay and lesbian legal conferences, participating in the mentor program with gay and lesbian attorneys in Washington, and holding various social events with Washington area gay and lesbian students and 
attorneys. All students are welcome and encouraged to join Lambda Law in an effort to increase awareness of diversity and acceptance at the Law School.

<H3>Law Association for Women (LAW)</H3>
All students at the Law School with an interest in women's issues are encouraged to join LAW, which has a membership of over 100 students. LAW's goals are to increase awareness of women's issues and to build a supportive community for women in law school 
and beyond. Each year LAW sponsors a number of programs, including brown-bag lunches with faculty members, a student/faculty reception, and career and issue-related forums. Recent speakers at the Law School sponsored by LAW have included Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for Women; Robin West, professor and scholar of feminist jurisprudence; Eleanor Smeal, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority;  and Sarah Weddington, the attorney who argued Roe v. Wade. LAW welcomes initiatives from its members and strives to express a broad range of women s interests.Law RevueThe annual Law Revue show allows GW Law students to display their "hidden" talents as singers, dancers, musicians, choreographers, song and script writers, and stage hands. The Law Revue players spoof, among other things, law school, their professors, the legal profession, current events, and their fellow students for the benefit of their audience -- the rest of the law school community. 
<H3>
Phi Alpha Delta (PAD)</H3>
PAD, a coed service fraternity, was founded in 1902 in order to promote professional competency and achievement within the legal profession. PAD is located in over 50 countries, and has over 100,000 members. Benefits to student members include the availability of PAD student loans, the opportunity to participate in social programs, and the establishment of alumni contacts. PAD offers students leadership development opportunities and practical legal education through its service to both students and the community. In 1991, the GW chapter of PAD established a Legal Related Education program, where members visit local elementary and middle schools to teach students about important legal principles.

<H3>Phi Delta Phi (PDP)</H3>
Founded in 1869 to promote a higher standard of professional ethics and culture, PDP is the oldest national or international association in the legal profession. Since 1869, over 158,000 
men and women have been initiated as members, including Supreme Court Justices Rehnquist, O Connor, Scalia, and Kennedy.  PDP offers members numerous opportunities to develop leadership skills and participate in community service activities.  Benefits to members include scholarships, an outline file, a student loan program, the opportunity to make alumni connections, and discounts on bar review courses.  PDP sponsors a number of annual events at the law school, including the "Ambulance Chase" race and "Canned Immunity."

<H3>Republican Student Lawyers Association (RSLA)</H3>
The Republican Student Lawyers Association consists of a core group of students who seek to educate the Law School community about the ideals and policies of the Republican party.  The RSLA sponsors activities, ranging from speakers and area conferences to social events, designed to heighten awareness of conservative approaches to current issues in law and politics.  The RSLA also publishes a newsletter each semester, The Right Stuff, designed to provide a written forum for conservative opinion within the Law School.  The RSLA seeks to assist students pursuing internships and employment with the federal government, and encourages interaction with practicing Republican lawyers within the community at-large.

<H3>Student Bar Association (SBA)</H3>
All students of the Law School are members of the SBA, the law school's student government. Through its elected officers and representatives, the SBA acts as an advocate of the student body; oversees the funding of student organizations; and sponsors a number of social, professional, and community service programs and events. Students take an active role in the academic and institutional development of the school through the SBA s participation on the faculty-student committees dealing with faculty tenure and appointments, curriculum development, student recruitment, incidents of discrimination and harassment, and public interest involvement. All students are encouraged to participate in SBA elections and to take advantage of the programs 
and activities that the SBA sponsors throughout the year, including resume writing and interviewing workshops; the Barrister's Ball; "Kegs on the Quad"; and annual blood, food, and clothing drives.

<H3>Student Health Law Association (SHLA)</H3>
SHLA was established to increase student interest in the growing field of health law, based on the premise that as health care grows, so too does the demand for excellent health lawyers. The SHLA informs students about local seminars on health law and sponsors programs that introduce students to attorneys practicing in diverse areas of this field.

<H3><A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/sipla/">Student Intellectual Property Law Association (SIPLA)</A></H3>
SIPLA offers intellectual property (IP) programs geared towards the needs and interests of its members. The Law School has the largest number of intellectual property alumni of any law school in the country (currently numbering well over 700). To our knowledge, SIPLA is the oldest and largest intellectual property student group in the nation. SIPLA members have interests in a variety of IP areas including patents, trademarks, copyrights, unfair trade practices, antitrust, technology licensing, entertainment, and communications law. SIPLA accommodates these interests by sponsoring speakers expert in these and other subject areas throughout the year. SIPLA works to promote contact between its members and leaders in the intellectual property field, many of whom are alumni.
<A NAME="skills"></A>
<H2>Student Skills Boards</H2>

<H3>Moot Court Board </H3>
The Moot Court Board is a student-managed honorary society that plays a vital role at the Law School by prom-oting the development of oral and written advocacy skills. Particular attention is given to fostering excellence in oral advocacy. Membership on the Board is offered in one of two ways: to first-year law students who achieve exceptional performance in the first-year moot court competition, or to upper-class students who achieve distinguished performance in one of the intrascholastic competitions. Each year the Board sponsors the Van Vleck Appellate Moot Court Competition in constitutional law, the Jessup Competition in international law, and the Giles S. Rich Competition in intellectual property law. During the 1996 97 year, the Board will host the sixth annual interscholastic National Security Law Competition.

<H3>Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) Board</H3>
The ADR Board, an honorary society, promotes student interest and the development of skills in the growing field of dispute resolution.  Over the course of the year, the Board sponsors in-house competitions in negotiations, mediation, and client counseling.  The Board also prepares students to compete inter-scholastically at the regional and national level.  Students gain membership on the Board by excelling in ADR competitions.  In addition, the Board hosts speakers from government agencies, the judicial system, and local practitioners to expose the Law School community to a wide range of ADR topics.  By raising student awareness about ADR, the Board endeavors to maintain the Law School s position in the vanguard of developing legal arenas.
<H3>
Trial Court Board </H3>
The Trial Court Board is open to all students and is dedicated to the pursuit of excellence in trial advocacy.  The Trial Court Board conducts intrascholastic trial competitions in both the fall and spring semesters. These competitions are held under realistic conditions at D.C. Superior Court and are judged by practicing litigators. Based upon performance in these competitions, top student litigators are selected for membership on the Trial Court Board. In the spring semester, members of the Trial Court Board represent the Law School at interscholastic competitions across the nation. The Law School has achieved national recognition based on the success of Trial Court Board members in these competitions.

<A NAME="pubs"></A>
<H2>Student Publications</H2>

<H3>The George Washington Law Review</H3>
Founded in 1931, The George Washington Law Review is issued five times a year and is edited and managed entirely by its student members. The Law Review is internationally known for 
its emphasis on federal and public law, and annually devotes an issue to a major symposium. Law Review staff members are selected based on a combination of applicants  grades and the results of a writing competition.

<H3>The George Washington Journal of International Law and Economics</H3>
The George Washington Journal of International Law and Economics was founded in 1966 and is also edited and managed by law students. In its three annual issues the Journal presents articles and commentaries on public and private international financial development, comparative law, and public international law. Journal staff members are selected based on criteria identical to those used by the Law Review.

<H3>The Environmental Lawyer</H3>
The Environmental Lawyer was founded in 1994 as a joint venture between the Law School and the American Bar Association s Section on Natural Resources, Energy and Environmental Law. The Environmental Lawyer is issued three times year., and one issue is devoted to a symposium on a selected topic. J.D. staff members are also selected based on a combination of grades and the results of a writing competition.

<H3>The American Intellectual Property Law Association Quarterly Journal</H3>
The American Intellectual Property Law Association Quarterly Journal, a publication of the AIPLA, is housed at the Law School and is edited and managed by law students under the direction of the editor-in-chief, Professor Joan Schaffner.  The journal is dedicated to presenting materials relating to intellectual property matters and is published four times per year.  AIPLA Journal student staff members are selected based on the results of a national writing competition.

<H3>The Public Contract Law Journal </H3>
The Public Contract Law Journal, which is produced jointly by the Law School and the Public Contract Law Section of the American Bar Association, is the premier journal read by ractitioners 
in the field of government procurement law.  The journal is published quarterly and is edited and managed by J.D. and LL.M. students. The selection criteria for J.D. staff members is the same at those used by the Law Review.




</font>

