<html>
<head>
<title>The Career Development Office</title>
</head>


<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL">

<h3>Pro Bono Students America</h3>
     Want to acquire some client-intake experience?  Do you have
five hours a week to donate to a community organization but don't
know where to find volunteer opportunities?  Still looking for a
public interest job this summer?   A new program is available at
the Career Development Office to facilitate your job search.
<p>
     What is it?  Pro Bono Students America (PBSA) is a national
network of law school pro bono and public interest programs, and
its mission is to help law students find valuable and manageable
volunteer projects during the school year and the summer. 
Georgetown University Law Center recently became the
administrative
center for the Capital States region of PBSA, which serves law
school and organizations in DC, Maryland, Virginia, Delaware,
West
Virginia, Kentucky, and North Carolina.
<p>
     The PBSA computer database uses specific criteria to match
students with organizations--government agencies, legal aid
societies, non-profits, judges and private firms--seeking student
assistance on pro bono or public interest projects.  You can
specify the issues you want to work on, the kind of experience
you're looking for, the number of hours you want to work,  whether
you want flexible hours, and a number of other options designed
to
ensure that you get the volunteer position that is right for you.

So, if you want a position in a public defender's office but can
only spare a few hours a week, PBSA will help you find one.  Or,
if
you're interested in working on women's issues in Chicago for the
summer, PBSA will generate a list for you of Chicago-based
women's
groups seeking summer interns.
<p>
     The computer generates a list of groups that meet  some, if
not all, of the student's criteria.  Students select their top
three choices from the list and the PBSA Coordinator faxes the
student's resume to the organizations in order of preference. 
The
organizations are asked to contact the student within 3-5 days. 
Students are asked to commit at least five hours a week and a
total
of 50 hours a semester.
<p>
     Any GW Law student interested in PBSA should contact Laura Lane at <A HREF="mailto:laura@cdo.nlc.gwu.edu">laura@cdo.nlc.gwu.edu</A> or
(202) 994-7340.
<p>
     Employers interested in becoming part of PBSA should contact
Barbara Moulton at Georgetown University Law Center, 111 F
Street,
N.W., Washington, D.C.  20001-2095, (202) 662-9654.
<p>
</body>
</html>
