<head>
<TITLE>Admission</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>

<A NAME="FAQ">
<H2>Frequently Asked Questions</H2>

<STRONG>What are the entrance requirements for the J.D. degree?</STRONG>
<P>
An applicant must have a bachelor's degree awarded by a regionally accredited college or university and must have taken the <A HREF="http://www.lsac.org/">Law School Admission Test</A> (LSAT) within the past three years.
<P>
<STRONG>What is the J.D. program application deadline?</STRONG>
<P>
March 1.  Applicants are strongly urged to submit their applications as soon as possible after October 1.  Those who wait until March 1 to submit their application may not have a completed file for several more weeks, or when we receive your LSDAS report (see below).
<P>
<STRONG>What is the application fee?</STRONG>
<P>
$55
<P>
<STRONG>How do I apply for the J.D. program?</STRONG>
<P>
The process begins when you submit a completed application form, which may be either the form available from the Admissions Office or the version generated by <A HREF="http://www.ot.com/multi-app/">LAW MULTI-App</A> software.  The application form should be accompanied by a $55 application fee.
<P>
Every applicant must register with the <A HREF="http://www.lsac.org/">Law School Data Assembly Service</A> (LSDAS).  This service provides a report that standardizes undergraduate grades and lists the applicant's LSAT score.  The report also includes a copy of the writing sample of the LSAT and copies of all transcripts.  The Law School orders a copy of the LSDAS report once a completed application is received.
<P>
<STRONG>When does the admission process begin?</STRONG>
<P>
Once an applicant's file is complete, i.e., once a completed application and LSDAS report have been received.
<P>

<STRONG>Can the application fee be waived?</STRONG>
<P>
The application fee may be waived in cases of extreme financial need.  The number of fee waivers granted each year is limited to five percent of the previous year's applicant volume, and waivers are awarded on a first come, first served basis.  An application for such a waiver may be obtained from the Admissions Office.
<P>

<STRONG>Can I begin the J.D. program in the spring?</STRONG>
<P>
No.  Beginning J.D. students may begin in the fall semester only.
<P>
<STRONG>Are letters of recommendation required as part of the application?</STRONG>
<P>
Letters of recommendation are not required, but we encourage applicants to submit two recommendations.  Letters of recommendation should be included, in sealed envelopes, with the application materials.  If the applicant's undergraduate school maintains a packet of recommendations on file, he or she should arrange to have the packet sent directly to the Admissions Office.
<P>

<STRONG>Can I visit the Law School?</STRONG>
<P>
Yes!  Prospective students are invited to visit the Law School, Monday through Friday, between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m.  Admission counselors are available on a walk-in basis to answer questions about the admission process.
<P>
<STRONG>Does the Admissions Office conduct personal interviews?</STRONG>
<P>
No. While admission counselor's are happy to meet with prospective students, these sessions are solely for your information and have no bearing on the admission decision.
<P>
<STRONG>Can I attend a Law School class?</STRONG>
<P>
Yes.  Arrangements can be made for you to sit in on a class.  Contact the Admissions Office for further details.
<P>

<STRONG>Does the Law School accept visiting students?</STRONG>
<P>
Yes. A student in good standing as a degree candidate at an accredited law school may be admitted to the Law School as an unclassified student in order to earn credit for transfer back to his or her home institution.  The majority of visiting students do their course work at the Law School in the summer, but fall and spring semester applications are accepted as well.  Admission will be based primarily on the availability of space.  Applicants must submit a completed application, the $55 application fee, a law school transcript, and a letter of good standing from the dean of the applicant's law school. Application deadlines for visiting students are July 1 for the fall semester, December 1 for the spring semester, and May 21 for the summer session.
<P>
<STRONG>Can you transfer to the Law School?</STRONG>
<P>
Yes.  A limited number of places is available for students who wish to transfer in after completing one year of legal studies at an ABA accredited school.  A maximum of 28 credit hours may be applied to the Law School's degree requirements. Applicants must  submit a completed application, the $55 application fee, a law school transcript, a record of LSAT scores, and a letter of good standing from the dean of the applicant's law school.  Application deadlines are July 1 for the fall semester and December 1 for the spring semester.
<P>
<A HREF="jd_app.htm">request an application for the J.D. program</A>
<P>


<A NAME="process">
<H2>The J.D. Admission Process</H2></A>

The entering J.D. class of the Law School is selected from a pool of approximately 6,500 applicants. This large number permits the Admissions Committee, which is composed of full-time faculty members, the Assistant Dean for Admissions, and the Director of Admissions, to be highly selective. A majority vote of the Committee is required for an applicant to be admitted.
<P>
The Admissions Committee begins to review completed files in December, though the majority of decisions are made in February, March, and April. The order in which files are selected for review is based on the completion date (i.e., the date the LSDAS report is received). Due to the large volume of applications received, it may take as long as three or four weeks from the time of receipt of an application for a file to become complete. And, during the busiest part of the year (January through April), it may take an additional six to eight weeks for a decision to be made on a completed file. Phone calls and letters only hinder this process. Applicants who wish to be informed of the status of their application should complete and submit the two postcards included in the back of this booklet. Applicants who need an early decision should complete their application in the fall.
<P>
All material submitted by the applicant (including the personal statement and letters of recommendation, if submitted) is considered before a decision is made. There are no inflexible standards, nor are there minimum grade-point averages or LSAT scores that are required. However, students whose undergraduate records and LSAT scores indicate a high probability of success in law study are in a favored position. Other factors considered in the admission decision include the undergraduate school attended and the student s major and trend in grades.
<P>
Consistent with the goal of providing an educationally stimulating and diverse environment, the Law School affirmatively seeks to recruit qualified members of groups (notably racial and ethnic minorities) that have been subject to discrimination in the past. This commitment includes considering all aspects of the applicant's personal and academic history in determining his or her potential for success in law school; conducting special recruitment programs; and awarding financial assistance upon a showing of financial need.
<P>
After the Admissions Committee has reviewed a file, a decision is made to admit, deny, or hold the application for a later review. Applicants are advised immediately of the decision, including placement in the "hold" category. Those admitted will receive a letter informing them of that action and requesting that a $100 deposit be submitted directly to the Admissions Office by April 15. Until this deadline has passed, a determination cannot be made regarding how many admitted applicants are seriously interested in coming to the Law School; consequently, the second review of applications in the hold category does not begin until after April 15. In late May, those admitted applicants who have submitted their $100 deposit are billed for a second deposit of $1,000, payable in mid-June. After the class is fully committed, the Admissions Committee may establish a waiting list and inform applicants that they will be admitted only if space becomes available.


