<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>LL.M. Admission</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P><A NAME="FAQ"></A></P>

<H2><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Frequently Asked Questions</FONT></FONT></H2>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>What LL.M. programs does
GW offer?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Specialized LL.M. programs
in <A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/5-2b.htm">Environmental Law</A>, <A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/5-2d.htm">Intellectual
Property</A>, <A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/5-2c.htm">Government Procurement</A>,
and <A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/5-2e.htm">International &amp; Comparative
Law</A>, and the <A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/5-2f.htm">General LL.M.</A>
degree. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>What is the General LL.M.?
What courses can be taken?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The General LL.M. allows
students to design their own program of study from the Law School's <A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/5-1d.htm">broad
ranging curriculum</A>. When applying for the General LL.M. program, you
must indicate an area of concentration and submit a proposed curriculum
and thesis topic. Your proposed program will be evaluated with other application
materials. Admission will depend in part on whether there is a faculty
member with the required expertise willing to serve as your curriculum
adviser and thesis supervisor. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Is it possible to pursue
the master's program on a part-time basis?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>All the specialized programs
are designed to be pursued either on a full- or part-time basis, and most
specialized courses are offered in the evening. The General LL.M. also
may be pursued on a full- or part-time basis, but students may find that
a number of their chosen courses are offered during the day. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>How much time is needed
to complete the degree?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Degree requirements should
be completed in one calendar year (full-time attendance) or two calendar
years (part-time attendance). An additional year may be allowed for completion
of the thesis. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>What are degree requirements?</B>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>24 credit hours, including
4 hours of thesis and the required number of credits in the field in the
specialized programs; attendance for a residence period of not less than
2 semesters, which should be consecutive; achievement of a grade point
average of 2.67 (for U.S. law school graduates) at the time all requirements
are met; and completion and acceptance of the thesis. Each student's overall
program (course selection and thesis topic) must be approved by the relevant
program director. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>What is required for the
thesis?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The thesis should be a paper
similar in quality and length to a law review article. It is not a dissertation
and need not be defended before a committee. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Is it possible to pursue
more than one specialty?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>LL.M. candidates may pursue
a dual specialization by completing course requirements in each area, and
by writing a thesis that intersects both subject areas. A dual specialization
requires admission to both programs, and may require additional course
work. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Are any joint degree programs
offered at the Law School?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>GW offers a joint LL.M./M.P.H
degree for students pursuing an LL.M. in Environmental Law. Candidates
must be admitted by both the Law School and the School of Public Health.
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>I've taken graduate law
courses elsewhere -- will they count toward my degree?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>No. Courses taken at other
institutions may not be counted for credit toward an LL.M. at GW Law School.
The only exception is up to 6 hours in courses taken at Georgetown University
Law Center through the consortium, but the student must already be a degree
candidate at GW. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>May I take one course
to see if I'm interested in the program?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Not for credit. You must
be a degree-seeking student to receive credit for a course. If only one
or two courses are desired, they may be taken on a not-for-credit or CLE
basis, for which only a certificate of completion is issued. Completion
of a course on this basis will not be counted later toward LL.M. degree
requirements. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>How many courses are required
to maintain full-time/part-time status?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Generally, full-time students
take 10 to 12 credit hours per semester, and part-time students between
4 and 6 hours. Relatively few courses are offered in the summer session,
so LL.M. students often use the summer to complete thesis requirements
or pursue independent research and writing projects. In order to receive
federal loans, a student must be registered for 5 hours for part-time status
or 9 hours for full-time status. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>How many students are
in the program?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Enrollment varies from year
to year, but generally there are 50-70 students in the Environmental program,
10-15 in Government Procurement, 10-15 in Intellectual Property, 45-55
in International and Comparative (including foreign attorneys), and 5-7
in the General program. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>What does the Graduate
Admissions Committee look for in an application? What are the standards
of admission?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>A high standard of academic
excellence demonstrated while obtaining the first law degree, a clear demonstration
of interest in the subject area, relevant work experience, maturity, preparation,
and the intellectual capacity for advanced law study. Each application
is evaluated on an individual basis -- there is no GPA &quot;cutoff&quot;
or other absolute criteria. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Will the LL.M. degree
help me find employment in my chosen field?</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The availability of jobs
in a given field and a given geographic market varies from year to year.
Students are encouraged to make the most of the resources of the Law School
(e.g., the Career Development Office, alumni networks, internships). However,
your total record of scholastic achievement is the most important variable
in finding a job; an LL.M. degree cannot completely compensate for an average
J.D. record. Most students are successful in obtaining employment in their
field of study. Program faculty, including adjuncts who are experts in
their field as well as full-time practitioners, work with students to help
them obtain employment. </FONT></FONT><A NAME="process"></A></P>

<H2><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Applying to the LL.M. Program</FONT></FONT></H2>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>U.S. law school graduates
applying for admission to the LL.M. program in Environmental Law, Intellectual
Property Law, Government Procurement Law or the General LL.M. should obtain
an application form from Graduate Programs Office, The George Washington
University Law School, Washington, DC 20052. (202)994-4500 or <A HREF="llm_app.htm">click
here</A> to request an application. The deadlines for such applicants are
June 1 for fall and November 1 for spring. Spring admission is granted
only with permission of the appropriate program director. Direct inquiries
to <A HREF="mailto:grad@main.nlc.gwu.edu">grad@main.nlc.gwu.edu</A> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>U.S. law school graduates
applying to the LL.M. program in International and Comparative Law should
obtain an application form from International Legal Studies Program Office,
The George Washington University Law School, Washington, DC 20052 (202)994-7242
or <A HREF="ils_app.htm">click here</A> to request an application. The
deadlines for such applicants are June 1 for fall and October 1 for spring.
Direct inquiries to <A HREF="mailto:ils@main.nlc.gwu.edu">ils@main.nlc.gwu.edu</A>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" HEIGHT=13 WIDTH=357><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.gwu.edu/"><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/gwu-logo.gif" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=50 WIDTH=50></A><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>
<A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/"><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/woodicon.gif" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=50 WIDTH=50></A>
</FONT></FONT></P>

</BODY>
