<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Frequently Asked Questions</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P><A NAME="FAQ"></A></P>

<H1><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Frequently Asked Questions
- International Legal Studies LL.M. Program for Foreign Law School Graduates</FONT></FONT></H1>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Do I need to have a law
degree to qualify for admission to the LL.M. program?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Yes. Students who hold any
of the following degrees or certificates are <B>NOT </B>eligible for the
program: a degree in international relations; a general bachelor's or master's
degree of arts; and patent examiner certificate or criminal prosecutor
certificate. You must have attended and graduated from a recognized law
faculty and the law degree received must be reflected on the university
transcript.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Is taking the TOEFL mandatory,
and is 600 really the minimum score? Can you accept a photocopy of the
score? How old can the score be?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The TOEFL is mandatory, except
for those applicants who have received their law degree from a university
where English is the language of instruction. If your score is under 600,
your file will still be considered and evaluated. No student is denied
solely on the basis of a TOEFL score. Photocopies of TOEFL scores are NOT
accepted. The score report must be sent directly to the International Legal
Studies Program Office by the TOEFL Testing Service and the applicant's
picture and signature must be on the score report. Scores older than two
years will not be accepted.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Are photocopies of official
transcripts accepted? What if the university in question refuses to submit
the transcript?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>No. Transcripts must be original
and must be submitted in a signed and sealed envelope by the registrar
of the university directly to the International Legal Studies Program Office.
In extreme circumstances, a notarized copy will be accepted, provided the
applicant has contacted the ILSP Office in advance and explained the situation.
If a university refuses to send a transcript and will provide it only to
the student, the student can submit the transcript provided in an envelope
signed and sealed by the university registrar.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Can a foreign attorney
start the program in the spring semester?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>No. A foreign attorney can
only start in the fall semester as the student is required to take the
&quot;Introduction to American Law&quot; course, which is offered in fall
only.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Are two letters of recommendation
mandatory, and must they be from law faculty?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Yes, two letters of recommendation
are required. They must be academic letters of reference, and should be
from law faculty. Professional letters of reference may also be submitted,
but they do not take the place of the academic references. Personal character
references may not be submitted in lieu of academic references.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>If an applicant wants
to apply for the Intellectual Property Law or Environmental Law program,
why does he or she have to be admitted to the International Legal Studies
Program? Will the academic program in question be different for foreign
students?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The International Legal Studies
Program was created specifically to admit and advise foreign attorneys
studying toward the LL.M. degree. The administrative staff, faculty directors,
and faculty advisers of the ILS Program are specially qualified to evaluate
transcripts from foreign institutions and other credentials submitted by
foreign applicants. Therefore, all applications must come to the ILS Program
Office, regardless of the specialization the applicant wishes to pursue.
The ILS Program staff are also specially qualified to advise foreign students
during their academic programs.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>While they are admitted to
the International Legal Studies Program, foreign LL.M. candidates in each
specialization pursue virtually the same academic program as their U.S.
counterparts and receive the same degree.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><B><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Are foreign law school
graduates in the LL.M. program separated from the rest of the law school
when taking courses, i.e., do they take special courses or are they free
to choose from the Law School's curriculum?</FONT></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Foreign attorneys are eligible
to enroll in virtually any course at the Law School, provided they have
obtained their adviser's approval. There is no separation of students,
and foreign attorneys attend classes ranging in size from 10 to 150 students
with the rest of the student body, which includes J.D., LL.M. and S.J.D.
candidates. </FONT></FONT></P>

<H2><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Applying to the International
Legal Studies Program</FONT></FONT></H2>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Graduates of foreign law
schools are admitted to degree candidacy in the Master of Laws (LL.M.)
program through the International Legal Studies Program.Through the ILS
program, students may apply for admission to one of the four specialized
LL.M. programs -- International and Comparative Law, Intellectual Property
Law, Environmental Law, or Government Procurement Law, or they may apply
to the General LL.M. degree program and design a course of study in American
law tailored to their individual needs. Admission decisions are made by
the director of the International Legal Studies Program in consultation
with the director of the appropriate specialized program. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Foreign law school graduates
should obtain an application form from International Legal Studies Program
Office, The George Washington University Law School, Washington, DC 20052
(202)994-7242 or click here to request an application. The deadline for
applications is May 1 -- admission to the ILS program is granted for the
fall semester only. Direct inquiries to ils@main.nlc.gwu.edu </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>ILS program students may
pursue the degree on a full-time or part-time basis. Students enrolled
in the program full-time are expected to complete degree requirements in
one academic year. If a student elects to attend part-time, the program
of study must be completed within three academic years. Students who wish
to attend part-time must so indicate on the application. Permission to
attend part-time is granted only in exceptional circumstances. </FONT></FONT><A NAME="enter"></A></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/llm_app.htm">Request
an application to the LL.M. program. </A></FONT></FONT></P>

<H2><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Entrance &amp; Degree Requirements</FONT></FONT></H2>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Entrance Requirements</B>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Foreign Law School Graduates
Applicants seeking admission to the International Legal Studies Program
must have earned a law degree with high academic standing from a duly accredited
law faculty of a foreign university. They must also demonstrate that they
have the requisite English language skills to undertake and complete their
studies (see below). Advanced standing is not granted for credit earned
while a candidate for the first law degree or for credit earned at other
institutions. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Language Test (TOEFL)</B>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Applicants who received their
law degree from an institution where English is not the language of instruction
must take the Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) and must attain
a score in the 600-point range to be considered for admission to the Law
School. Applicants are responsible for making their own arrangements to
take the test and should address inquiries to TOEFL, Educational Testing
Service, CN6151, Princeton, New Jersey 08641-6151, USA. On the application
for the test, the applicant should specify that the scores be sent to the
International Legal Studies Program Office of The George Washington University
Law School. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Degree Requirements</B>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>In order to earn the Master
of Laws degree, all foreign law school graduates must fulfill the following
requirements: completion of 24 credit hours, including the required curriculum
in the specialized programs; attendance for a residence period of not less
that two semesters, which should be consecutive; achievement of a cumulative
grade-point average of 2.33 at the time all requirements are met; completion
and acceptance of a thesis (may be waived for foreign law school graduates
-- see Thesis Option, below); and completion of Law 694, Introduction to
American Law.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Foreign law school graduates
are expected to complete all degree requirements in one academic year.
An extension for one semester may be granted by the director of the International
Legal Studies Program in exceptional circumstances.</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><B>Thesis Option</B> </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>While completion of a thesis
is generally required of LL.M. degree candidates, this requirement may
be waived for foreign attorneys in the ILS program with the approval of
the relevant program director. Students who obtain such a waiver must write
a substantive research paper in a seminar course or as an independent writing
project. An ILS student who chooses to write a thesis is assigned an adviser
from the full-time faculty who assists the student in developing a topic
and provides research guidance. The thesis is expected to be a major scholarly
paper comparable in quality and length to a law review article. </FONT></FONT><A NAME="profile"></A></P>

<H2><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>ILS Class Profile</FONT></FONT></H2>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Each year, more than 400
applications are received by the ILS program and some 50 to 60 students
are admitted. For the 1996-97 academic year, the entering class included
students from 27 countries -- Australia, Austria, Belgium, Brazil, Canada,
China (P.R.), Colombia, Costa Rica, the Czech Republic, Ecuador, Finland,
France, Gambia, Germany, India, Italy, Japan, Korea, Lebanon, Pakistan,
Peru, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Spain, Thailand, and the United
Kingdom. Students in the program come from a wide variety of academic and
professional backgrounds, from recent law school graduates to practitioners,
law teachers, and government officials. The national diversity and professional
experience of the ILS student body add an important dimension to the academic
and social life of the Law School. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" HEIGHT=13 WIDTH=357><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.gwu.edu/"><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/gwu-logo.gif" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=50 WIDTH=50></A><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>
<A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/"><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/woodicon.gif" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=50 WIDTH=50></A>
</FONT></FONT></P>

