<TITLE>Financial Aid</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<A NAME="tuition">
<H2>Tuition and Fees</H2>

Tuition and fees for the 1996-97 academic year are as follows:
<dl>
<dt>
J.D. candidates:
<dd>	
	Full-time J.D. ( 11+ credit hours)	$20,870<BR>
	Part-time J.D., each credit hour 	$735
<dt>
Master's degree candidates, each credit hour	$735
<dt>
Continuing Legal Education students, each credit hour	$735
<dt>
University Fee (charged all students registered on campus)	$30.50 per credit hour to a maximum of $457.50 per semester
</dl>
<dl>
<dt>
Special Fees and Deposits (non-refundable)
<dt>
Application fee (degree candidates)	$55
<dt>
First J.D. tuition deposit fee 	$100
<dd>
	Due by date specified in letter of admission
<dt>
Second J.D. tuition deposit fee	$1,000
<dd>
	Due by mid-June
<dt>
LL.M. tuition deposit fee	$500
<dd>
	Due by date specified in letter of admission
<dt>
Late registration 	$80
<dd>
	Beginning the first week of the semester
<dt>
Registration for continuous enrollment or leave of absence	$30
<dt>
Commencement participation fee 	$50
<dd>
	Charged all students who choose to participate in commencement 
<dt>
Late payment fee	$50
<dt>
Replacement of lost or stolen picture identification card	 $25
<dt>
Returned check fee	 $25
<dt>
Transcript fee	 $5
<dt>
Replacement of diploma fee	$50
</dl>
<A NAME="expense">
<H2>Estimated Living Expenses</H2>
Estimated living expenses for the 1996-97 nine-month academic year total $13,680. This estimate includes accommodations, transportation, books, food, health insurance, personal expenses, and loan fees. Living costs, of course, will vary with individual student lifestyles. These expenses are in addition to tuition and fee charges.

<A NAME="FAQ">
<H2>Frequently Asked Questions</H2>

To Come

<A NAME="process">
<H2>Applying for Financial Aid</H2></A>
There are a number of sources of financial assistance available to students at the Law School. In order to be considered for financial aid:
<P>
The student and his or her parents must register with PROFILE through <A HREF="http://www.collegeboard.org/">College Scholarship Service</A> (CSS) in Princeton, New Jersey. Registration forms are available from the Law Financial Aid Office.
<P>
The student and his or her parents must file a <A HREF="http://www.ed.gov/prog_info/SFA/FAFSA/">Free Application for Federal Student Aid</A> (FAFSA) and submit it to the federal processor. Forms are available from any college or university.
<P>
A signed copy of all pages, schedules, and W-2 forms of the student's federal tax return and a signed copy of all pages, schedules, and W-2 forms of his or her parents' federal tax return should be submitted to the Law School's Financial Aid Office.
<P>
A Financial Aid Transcript completed by each U.S. post-secondary school attended should be forwarded to the Law School's Financial Aid Office.
<P>
Applicants are urged to submit their FAFSA and PROFILE forms to their respective processors early in January so that a completed analysis can be received by the Law School by March 1. Accepted applicants whose CSS/FAFSA data reach the Financial Aid Office after March 15 cannot be guaranteed a decision by April 15, and available funds may then be limited.
<P>
Once a student's financial aid file is completed it will be reviewed for a determination of the applicant's eligibility to borrow Stafford Loan funds, as well as a decision regarding the Law School's sources of financial aid. No awards will be made to an entering student until the admission process has been completed.

<A NAME="source">
<H2>Sources of Aid</H2>
<H3>Law School Aid</H3>

<H3>Grants</H3>
There are a number of grants available to law students, based on financial need. Monies are awarded for the upcoming academic year only. In subsequent years, students' need must be reevaluated.

<H3><A HREF="http://www.ed.gov/prog_info/SFA/StudentGuide/1996-7/index.html">Federal Perkins Loans</A></H3>
Federal loans under this program are awarded by the Law School to a limited number of students on the basis of financial need. Repayment is at 5% and the maximum amount a student may receive cannot exceed a combined undergraduate and graduate total of $18,000. Interest and principal are deferred during the in-school period and for six months after the student ceases to be enrolled.

<H3>Loan Reimbursement Assistance Program </H3>
The Law School also provides assistance in repayment of legal education debt through its Loan Reimbursement Assistance Program (LRAP).  Graduates with educational debt who choose 
public interest employment may receive grants of up to $6,000 per year. Grant awards will depend on the nature of the employment, the applicant s commitment to public interest work, the applicant's and employer's financial need, and the amount of the applicant's educational debt.  The number and size of grants varies from year to year, depending on the number of applications and the availability of funds.  LRAP application forms are available from the Law School Financial Aid Office.

<H3>Other Sources of Aid</H3>

<H3><A HREF="http://www.ed.gov/prog_info/SFA/StudentGuide/1996-7/index.html">Federal Stafford Loans</a></H3>
Subsidized Stafford Loan eligibility is based on financial need, which is determined by the Financial Aid Office using the FAFSA analysis. It is possible to receive up to $8,500 a year at a variable rate of interest under this program. If the student qualifies for the need-based interest subsidy, the federal government pays the interest during the in-school period and for six months after the student ceases to be enrolled. If the student does not qualify for the subsidy, he or she may still receive the $8,500 Stafford Loan at the same interest rate, but the in-school interest accrues, and there is no post-enrollment grace period. Students who have never borrowed a Stafford Loan should request a Stafford application through a national lender from the Law School's Financial Aid Office.
<P>
Unsubsidized Stafford Loans are available to students at a variable interest rate, in amounts up to $10,000 per year. (Students who do not qualify for the interest subsidy on the first $8,500 Stafford Loan may receive an unsubsidized Stafford Loan of $18,500.)

<H3>Credit-Based Loans</H3>
There are several private loan plans available to credit-worthy applicants; a detailed chart of the private loans used by Law School students may be obtained from the Law Financial Aid Office. 
In general, this type of loan provides $1,500 to $20,000 per academic year, up to varying aggregate amounts, depending on the lender. Typically the interest rate is determined by adding 
percentage points to either the 91-day Treasury bill rate or the prime rate, and a guarantee fee and/or insurance fee may be charged. Some programs allow students to defer payments of interest and principal during enrollment. Repayment of such loans usually begins within 60 days of the student s last day of half-time enrollment, at which time both interest and principal become due. We urge applicants to examine their credit report in advance of applying for aid. A history of timely payments (not accounts paid in full) determines whether a student will qualify for credit-based loans.

