<head>
<TITLE>Full-and Part-Time Programs of Study</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<h2>Full-and Part-Time Programs of Study</h2>


Once admitted to the J.D. degree program, candidates may choose one of three options for their first year of study: the Full-Time Day Division, the Full-Time Day/Evening Division, or the Part-Time Evening Division. Each division has the same academic standards, and all required and core courses are taught by the full-time faculty. First-year Day Division classes generally are scheduled between 9 a.m. and 4 p.m. First-year Day/Evening Division classes generally meet between 3 and 7:40 p.m. First-year Evening Division classes generally meet between 5:50 and 7:40 p.m. For all divisions, the Legal Research and Writing and Introduction to Advocacy classes can be scheduled in the late evening between 7:50 and 9:40 p.m. After the first year, all full-time students must take the majority of their courses during the day.
<p>
Part-time students may be allowed to transfer to the full-time division after the first year, with the permission of the dean. Under the Law School's residency requirement, a full-time student normally will take six semesters of study, or three academic years, in order to complete the degree. A part-time student normally will take eight semesters, or four academic years, and one summer session. For students who change their status from full-time to part-time or vice versa, the number of semesters of attendance required to meet the residency requirement will vary proportionally.
<p>
  Students who attend full-time are expected to devote substantially all of their time during the academic year to study. First-year students in the full-time divisions are especially urged to refrain from outside employment. Upper-class students taking more than 10 credit hours of course work must limit outside employment to no more than 20 hours per week.


<p>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13>
<p>
