<html>
<head>
<TITLE>Clinical Programs</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<h2>Clinical Programs</h2>


<H4>The Jacob Burns Community Legal Clinics</H4>

The Community Legal Clinics Program was founded in 1971, and the Clinics were renamed in 1991 to acknowledge the generous support of Jacob Burns, LL.B. 24, LL.D. 70. The premise behind the Clinics  inception was to provide students with an unparalleled opportunity to experience the practical application of law while at the same time providing members of the community with critically needed legal services. All of the clinics share a common goal in spite of their diversity -- provide highly motivated law students the opportunity to develop skills as negotiators, advocates, and litigators within an exciting and supportive educational environment.
The clinical programs vary considerably in purpose, duration, requirements, and duties, and every year special projects increase the scope of this rich offering. Services are made available to Spanish-speaking residents of the area through the Clinics  several bilingual attorneys and students.

<H4>Administrative Advocacy Clinic/ Advocates for Older People (AOP)</H4>

Students represent indigent and elderly people in cases concerning retirement, veterans  disability claims, unemployment compensation and public benefits, probate matters, landlord-tenant rent 
disputes, and special education services. Students enrolled in Administrative Advocacy may request placement with AOP which provides legal services to older D.C. residents. The AOP program also runs a Volunteer Income Tax Program in the spring semester.

<H4>Civil Litigation Clinic</H4>

This clinic's court-certified students are permitted to counsel clients, draft pleadings, prepare cases for trial, conduct examinations of witnesses, and argue cases under the close supervision of 
the clinic s supervising attorneys. Many types of civil cases are handled such as landlord-tenant, small claims, family matters, and occasional appeals.

<H4>Consumer Mediation Clinic</H4>

Students may participate in this unique clinical program as early as the summer of their first year. Unlike the other clinical courses at the Law School, the Mediation Clinic does not act as an dvocate or represent clients. Rather, students act as neutral third-party mediators who assist local consumers and businesses in resolving disputes by negotiating mutually agreeable settlements. Students perform case intake, provide information and referrals, and mediate assigned cases involving a wide variety of consumer issues (debt collection, credit problems, defective goods and services, home improvement contracts, etc.). Students in this clinic develop and apply creative problem-solving techniques as well as learning substantive consumer law.

<H4>Domestic Violence Clinic</H4>

This clinic offers students the opportunity to engage in lawyering for social change while providing needed representation to victims of domestic violence. Third-year, court-certified 
students represent clients seeking civil protection orders and enforcing such orders in court. Students interview and counsel clients, draft pleadings, and prepare and try cases in court under 
faculty supervision. Students also work on battered women's self-defense cases with local public defenders and on reform projects seeking to improve the legal system's or community s response to domestic violence. An interdisciplinary approach is also stressed, through collaboration with a consulting psychologist and the GW School of Medicine and Health Sciences' Department of Emergency Medicine.

<H4>Federal, Criminal, and Appellate Clinic</H4>

Under faculty supervision, students litigate appellate cases, primarily direct appeals from criminal convictions in area courts of appeal. Third-year students eligible for court certification take responsibility for the whole case, from docketing through oral argument. The clinic also conducts studies of appellate court procedures and practice that have proven to be of benefit to the local bar.
Immigration Clinic
<P>
In this clinic, aliens subject to deportation or exclusion orders in immigration court are represented by students under faculty supervision. Students determine what forms of relief, if any, are available to their clients, and in appropriate circumstances represent their clients 
in hearings in open court.  Because the clinic s clients come from all over the world, cultural sensitivity is essential and foreign language skills are welcome.

<H4>Small Business Clinic/Community Economic Development</H4>

The clinic gives students practical experience in creating legal structures for new businesses by guiding local area entrepreneurs through the legal requirements necessary to start a new business. Students gain practical experience with client interviewing; drafting legal documents such as articles of incorporation, bylaws, agreements and contracts; and providing basic tax and business counseling. Students work closely with the project s supervising attorney in researching and drafting legal documents related to both profit and non-profit organizations.

<H4>Vaccine Injury Clinic</H4>

This clinic allows second- and third-year students, under faculty supervision, to represent individuals who have suffered serious vaccine-related injuries and who are seeking damages in trial and appellate proceedings before the U.S. Court of Federal Claims. The clinic s classroom component focuses on multidisciplinary (medical-legal) training in vaccine injury issues, and on lawyering skills such as client interviewing and counseling and cross examination of medical experts.  Students also work to evaluate the Claims Court s program as a model for tort reform.

<H4>Health Insurance Counseling Clinic</H4>

Second- and third-year students in this clinic provide advice and information and assist in providing legal represen-tation to older D.C. residents who are having difficulty with medical bills, Medicare, Medicaid, and other health insurance problems.  Students perform intake at the clinic office or by home visit, and take major responsibility for up to five cases during the semester.

<H4>Law Students in Court/Bankruptcy Clinic</H4>

This clinic was established in 1978 to provide assistance to low-income residents of the District of Columbia. Bankruptcy Clinic students handle a wide variety of legal and informal financial counseling services including client interviewing, preparation of consumer bankruptcy petitions and Chapter 13 Earner Plans, and negotiations of informal debt reduction and consolidation agreements.

<H4>The J.B. and Maurice C. Shapiro Environmental Law Clinic</H4>

This clinic was established in 1995 by a generous gift from the J.B. and Maurice C. Shapiro Charitable Trust. Under faculty supervision, second-, third-, and fourth-year students represent clients in environmental litigation in both the federal and state systems.  This work includes administrative, trial, or appellate actions, particularly citizen action suits, under a variety of environmental statutes such as the Clean Air Act, the Clean Water Act, the Endangered Species Act, and the Federal Facilities Compliance Act.

<H4>The Project for Older Prisoners (POPS)</H4>

The Project for Older Prisoners (POPS) encompasses a number of prison projects in which students are involved as volunteers or work for academic credit. Some students assist individual low-risk prisoners over the age of 55 to help them obtain paroles, pardons, or alternative forms of incarceration. In a typical case, a student will prepare an extensive background report on a 
prisoner to determine the likelihood of recidivism. If the risk is low, the student will then locate housing and support for the prisoner and help prepare the case for a parole hearing. Other students are involved in a Prison Environmentalism project which is working to introduce recycling and environmental industries in prisons. POPS runs a "Books for Crooks" program to help build prison libraries. Another project involves students in a study of the federal prison system and the sentencing guidelines for the U.S. Sentencing Commission. Recently POPS started a Women s Project. Professor Jonathan Turley formed POPS in 1988 while a professor at Tulane Law School, and the program continues to operate in Louisiana. GW Law School POPS 
operates largely in the D.C. metropolitan area, including Maryland and Virginia, and may extend to other states in the future. The program has received considerable media attention and growing bipartisan political support because it addresses a growing national problem: the aging of America's prison population.

<H4>Outside Placement</H4>

Students may also gain practical experience through outside placement with a wide variety of government agencies and private organizations. Students have received credit for their work as interns with organizations and agencies including the Department of Justice, the Environmental Defense Fund, the U.S. Attorneys Office, the D.C. Public Defender Service, the Women s Legal Defense Fund, Washington Legal Clinic for the Homeless, the Legal Aid Society, and Consumers Union. Students have also arranged to receive academic credit for their internships with District Court and Superior Court Judges.




