<head>
<TITLE>Environmental Law LL.M.</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<h2>Environmental Law LL.M.</h2>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13><p>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/env.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=202 ALIGN=left>
<P>
<H3>About the LL.M. in Environmental Law</H3>

The LL.M. program in environmental law was the first of its kind in the country. There are currently more than 100 students working toward the LL.M. in environmental law and a smaller number, enrolled in other specialties, who are broadening their expertise by including environmental law courses in their programs.
<P>
To earn the LL.M. degree in environmental law, students complete 24 credit hours that include a 
minimum of 12 hours in environmental law courses and 4 hours of thesis.
<P>
About two-thirds of environmental law graduate students attend full time and complete the program in one calendar year (two semesters and one summer).  Part-time students complete their degree requirements in two calendar years.  Admission to the program for both full- and part-time students is generally granted for the fall semester; spring admission may be allowed in special circumstances at the discretion of the program director.
<P>
A number of students enroll in the program part time while they continue to work.  Most do very well, but this requires a serious commitment as well as some planning and organization.  Those who are considering taking the program on a part-time basis are encouraged to discuss the demands of the program as related to the demands of their work with Professor Laurent Hourcl, co-director of the program, before applying.
<P>
<H3>Joint Degree with Public Health Program (LL.M./M.P.H.)</H3>

The Law School and the School of Medicine and Health Sciences offer a joint LL.M./M.P.H. program that includes a specialization in environmental-occupational health.  Students must be admitted to both degree programs separately.  Six credit hours of successfully completed course work may be transferred between programs.  In addition, an LL.M./M.P.H. candidate may use the Law School's required thesis to satisfy a portion of the special project requirement of the M.P.H. program.
<P>
<H3>The Environmental Lawyer</H3>

The Environmental Lawyer is a practitioner-oriented journal produced jointly by the Law School 
and the American Bar Association's Section on Natural Resources, Energy, and Environmental Law.  The journal is unique among environmental law reviews because of the peer review process 
submissions undergo prior to publication.  Professors Arnold Reitze and Elizabeth Glass Geltman 
are involved in the production of the journal, thus allowing for student-faculty interaction in a 
professional environment.
<P>
Although the staff of The Environmental Lawyer consists mostly of J.D. students, openings are 
available for LL.M. candidates interested in serving on either the editorial board or the staff.  Several editorial board slots are held open exclusively for LL.M. candidates, with a term of office running from September to May.  LL.M. students who assist J.D. students in the more complex substantive aspects of environmental law are an invaluable resource to The Environmental Lawyer.

<H3>The Thesis and Research Opportunities</H3>

Each student in the LL.M. program is required to write a thesis under the supervision of a member of the full-time faculty.  The thesis represents the student's synthesis of course work into a creative study that moves the law forward.  The faculty assists students in selecting cutting-edge topics, works with students on thesis development, and provides advice on potential publishing opportunities.  This major research project is a catalyst for student access to an exceptional variety of published and unpublished information sources.  Students develop opportunities to meet and discuss their ideas with some of the nation's leading policy and decision makers.  Most students who are interested in doing so publish their theses.

<H3>Internships</H3>

Students can individualize their degree programs through the Graduate Environmental Outside Placement course, which places students in internships with government agencies or nonprofit, environmentally related organizations.  Students can engage in legal analysis and policy formulation at locations such as the White House Office of Environmental Policy; the EPA; the Departments of Justice, Energy, Interior, and Defense; Congress; the Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund; The World Bank; the Environmental Law Institute; and the Center for International Environmental Law.  The placement program can be used by students with specialized interests in subjects such as wildlife preservation or historical property protection.  It can also be used to augment the student's research for the thesis.

<H3>Environmental Law Curriculum</H3>

The curriculum consists of a core of in-depth courses on the EPA's "media" statutes (the Clean Air Act and Clean Water Act, the Solid Waste Disposal Act, and "Superfund") and approximately 20 additional environmental courses and allows students to tailor their course of study to their individual learning and career objectives.  To supplement their programs, students also may choose from the wide-ranging curriculum of the Law School (in areas such as land use, government contracts, international law, the legislative process, and health care law) as well as courses in other schools of the University.
<P>
The environmental law curriculum is constantly updated to keep pace with changes in the field.  Recent course and seminar additions include a seminar that explores the controversial area of 
constitutional takings under environmental statutes, courses in environmental negotiations and 
environmental law issues for federal facilities, and a seminar involving environmental issues in 
federal procurement.
<P>
Most specialized environmental law courses are offered in the early evening, and many are taught by adjunct faculty members who are among the nation's leading public- and private-sector practitioners and experts in the areas they teach.
<P>
The courses listed below (except Environmental Law) count toward the minimum 12 credit hours in environmental law courses required for the LL.M. degree and customarily are offered each year.  Click on any course title to read its description.

<UL>
<LI>Environmental Law   
<LI>Air Pollution Control I   
<LI>Air Pollution Control II   
<LI>Water Pollution Control
<LI>Water Resources Law
<LI>Coastal, Navigation, and Wetland 	Resource Law
<LI>Energy Law
<LI>Natural Resources Law I
<LI>Natural Resources Law II
<LI>Control of Solid and Hazardous Wastes
<LI>Regulation of Pesticides and Industrial Chemicals
<LI>Nuclear Energy Law
<LI>Toxic Tort Litigation
<LI>Federal Facilities Environmental Law Issues
<LI>Environmental Issues in Business Transactions
<LI>International Environmental Law
<LI>International Trade and Environmental Law
<LI>Environmental Planning
<LI>Environmental Negotiations
<LI>Law, Science, and Technology Seminar
<LI>Graduate Environmental Outside Placement
<LI>Environmental Law Seminar
</UL>


