<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Government Procurement Law LL.M.</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win16; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<H2><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Government Procurement Law
LL.M.</FONT></FONT></H2>

<P><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" HEIGHT=13 WIDTH=357></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1> <IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/capitol.jpg" HEIGHT=202 WIDTH=200 ALIGN=LEFT>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<H3><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>About the Government Procurement
Law LL.M.</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The Government Procurement
Law Program is the only one of its kind in the country. To earn the LL.M.
degree in Government Procurement Law, students complete 24 credit hours
that include a minimum of 10 hours in government procurement law core courses
and 4 hours of thesis. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The experience of program
graduates in recent years confirms that procurement law continues to be
a vital area of interest to increasing numbers of legal employers. Acquisition
of goods and services by the federal government alone now accounts for
approximately $200 billion of the annual federal budget. Moreover, although
some areas of government procurement have been reduced in an era of fiscal
stringency, efforts to downsize government are likely to take the form
of contracting out functions traditionally performed by government personnel.
State and local government procurement adds significantly to the total
volume of government procurement and the associated legal practice opportunities.
In addition, the practice of government procurement law today increasingly
intersects with other disciplines of public law. For example, in recognition
of the important relationship of government procurement law and environmental
law, students in the LL.M. program may study both fields concurrently.
This dual specialization appears to be of significant interest to increasing
numbers of legal employers. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The LL.M. program in Government
Procurement Law has proven attractive both to attorneys with substantial
experience in the federal government and to those in the private practice
of law, as well as to more recent law school graduates. Conversely, because
of GW Law School's record of leadership in the field, program graduates
have been attractive to employers, many of which are located in the Washington
metropolitan area, the center of the practice of government contracts law.
Many graduates of our LL.M. program hold prominent positions in government
agencies, the Judge Advocate General s Corps, corporations, and private
law firms. Alumni of the program form a network that includes many of the
leaders of the government procurement bar. Alumni support for the program
helps to provide resources that allow the Law School to maintain its preeminent
reputation in this field of law. Recently the Law School obtained a bequest
from the estate of Justine Gubin in honor of her late husband, E.K. Gubin,
who played an important teaching role in the program. The Gubin gift has
been used to endow a professorial chair devoted to government contracts
law and provides important strength to the program. </FONT></FONT></P>

<H3><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Public Contract Law Journal</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The Public Contract Law Journal
is produced jointly by the Law School and the Public Contract Law Section
of the American Bar Association. It is the premier journal read by practitioners
in the field of government procurement law. The staff of the Public Contract
Law Journal consists of both J.D. and LL.M. candidates. Positions are available
to LL.M. candidates as members and officers of the journal or as members
of the journal s advisory board. The advisory board, composed solely of
LL.M. students, consults with journal members and officers on specific
government procurement issues that arise in the course of preparing the
journal, thereby providing graduate students with the option to participate
in the journal without committing the time necessary for membership. </FONT></FONT></P>

<H3><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The Thesis and Other Research
Opportunities</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Students in the LL.M. program
are required to write a thesis under the supervision of a member of the
full-time faculty. The student's faculty adviser assists in identifying
and selecting an appropriate topic and works with the student in developing
the focus and direction of the thesis. The thesis represents a culmination
of students formal academic study and challenges them to develop cutting-edge
expertise as they synthesize and rationalize existing doctrine, critique
the state of the law, and advance carefully grounded proposals for reform.
Program faculty are also available to assist students in locating publishing
opportunities for their theses. Additional opportunities for in-depth research
are provided through the government contracts seminar courses, which require
the preparation of a research paper. For many of these papers, students
may select and pursue a topic of their choosing, further developing their
expertise in an area of particular interest. Student research is supported
by the unique resources available to the Law School, including the unparalleled
collection of government procurement materials of the Jacob Burns Law Library,
a law librarian with expertise in the field of procurement law, and access
to government agencies and other institutions located in Washington, D.C.
</FONT></FONT></P>

<H3><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The Government Contracts
Program Conference and Research Center</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The Law School sponsors the
<A HREF="http://www.gwu.edu/~gcp/">Government Contracts Program Conference
and Research Center</A> as an extension of its academic program. The center
currently offers 34 continuing education courses, ranging from one to five
days in duration, for attorneys and other contracting professionals. The
center also sponsors symposia and other programs addressing issues of special
interest to the procurement community. LL.M. students in the Government
Procurement Law Program may attend any of these courses free of charge.
A separate brochure that describes the course offerings, programs, and
publications of the Government Contracts Program Conference and Research
Center is available by writing to the Government Contracts Program, 2100
Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 250, Washington, D.C. 20037-3202, or by
calling (202)223-2772. </FONT></FONT></P>

<H3><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Government Procurement Law
Curriculum</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The program curriculum includes
a group of core courses that all LL.M. degree candidates in the field are
expected to take: Formation of Government Contracts, Performance of Government
Contracts, and Government Contracts Cost and Pricing. Students are also
advised to take one or more of the Government Contracts Seminar courses
offered each year. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>The Government Contracts
Seminar courses enrich the core curriculum and provide topicality by covering
areas of longstanding interest as well as those chosen in response to current
developments in the field. A seminar on the intersection of environmental
law and government procurement has been offered on a regular basis. A recent
seminar addressed developments heralded by the newly enacted Federal Acquisition
Streamlining Act. In these seminars, the Law School's location makes possible
the use of guest speakers who are leading figures in the field. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Formation of Government Contracts
(4) Lees, Miller<BR>
Survey of the law pertaining to federal government procurement, including
analysis of the unique features of government contracting and a discussion
of the roles of Congress, the executive branch, and the courts in the procurement
process. Focus on contract formation, including techniques for awarding
contracts, and litigation and protests concerning awards. This is the first
half of the sequence of basic courses that is completed by Performance
of Government Contracts. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Performance of Government
Contracts (4) Lees, Miller<BR>
Study of the issues and substantive problems that arise during the performance
of government contracts. Topics include interpretation of specifications
and commonly used contract clauses, and analysis of the rights of the parties
when performance in accordance with the terms of the contract does not
occur. Procedures and forums for resolution of claims of breach of contract
and disputes relating to contract performance or administration are also
considered. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Government Contracts Cost
and Pricing (2) Knight<BR>
Legal aspects of government contract accounting principles and allowability
of costs. Cost accounting standards and cost allocation issues. Negotiation
of cost, profit, and price. Disclosure of cost accounting data. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Government Contracts Seminar
(2) Lees, Miller, Hourcle<BR>
Each year's seminars focus on particular matters of current interest in
the field of government contracts. One section usually focuses on issues
related to environmental law in government contracts. Seminars offered
in the 1995-96 academic year are described below. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Claims and Litigation covers
the processing of a contract claim from filing through resolution before
a Board of Contract Appeals. Students prepare several pleadings on the
simulated claims and participate in mock depositions and settlement negotiations.
Guest speakers include the Chair of the Armed Services Board of Contract
Appeals, faculty from the Army Judge Advocate General s School, and practitioners
from the government and private sector. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Litigating Protests covers
the processing of a bid protest from the identification of protestable
issues and preparation of a protest through the issuance of a decision
by the General Services Board of Contract Appeals or the General Accounting
Office. Students prepare several pleadings on the protest and participate
in a prehearing conference and a hearing on the merits of the protest.
Guest participants include a judge from the General Services Administration
Board of Contract Appeals, the associate general counsel of the General
Accounting Office, and practitioners from government and the private sector.
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Government Procurement and
Environmental Law focuses on the wide range of environmental issues presented
in the government contract formation and performance process, as well as
the manner in which federal procurement law may be used to advance the
goals of the environmental community and to implement environmental programs.
The seminar considers the nature and purpose of applicable environmental
procurement statutes and regulations; the selection of qualified environmental
contractors; the buying of green products and services and contract types;
the sharing of responsibility for clean-up and remedial efforts and inherent
problems at government and contractor facilities; applicable cost and pricing
principles; and current developments and initiatives in the environmental
law field. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Graduate Government Contracts
Placement (1 to 4) Lees, Miller, Schwartz<BR>
Students work on a project in the government contracts field under the
supervision of the faculty directors of the program and a lawyer practicing
government contracts law. The project may involve working with a government
agency, congressional committee, private practitioner, or nonprofit public
interest organization. For example, students have been placed with the
Armed Services Board of Contract Appeals, the General Services Board of
Contract Appeals, the Department of Justice, and the Office of Federal
Procurement Policy. Five hours of work per week are required for each credit.
Full-time students normally take this course during their second semester
and part-time students during their second year. </FONT></FONT></P>

<H3><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Government Procurement Law
Faculty</FONT></FONT></H3>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="fac/schwartz.htm">Joshua
I. Schwartz</A>, Professor of Law and Co-Director of the Government Procurement
Law Program<BR>
B.A., Harvard University; J.D., M.C.R.P., Cornell University<BR>
Professor Schwartz joined the law faculty in 1985. He teaches in the areas
of administrative law, government contracts, legislation, and property.
He was appointed co-director of the Government Procurement Law Program
in 1992. Following law school, Professor Schwartz clerked for Judge Marvin
E. Frankel of the U.S. District Court of the Southern District of New York.
He then joined the staff of the Justice Department, in what is now the
Environmental Division, specializing in appellate litigation with an emphasis
on administrative law and regulatory issues. From 1981 to 1985, Professor
Schwartz served as an Assistant to the Solicitor General in the Department
of Justice, briefing and arguing cases on behalf of the federal government
and its agencies before the Supreme Court. Among the issues handled in
that capacity were problems of sovereign immunity, equitable estoppel,
and judicial review of agency action. Since coming to the Law School, Professor
Schwartz's scholarship has concentrated on the obligations of federal agencies
to follow their own regulations and to abide by judicial precedents, and
the degree to which government agencies are subject to remedial principles
such as equitable estoppel. Professor Schwartz teaches the J.D.-level survey
course Government Contracts. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="fac/lees.htm">Frederick
J. Lees</A>, E.K. Gubin Professor of Government Contracts Law and Co-Director
of the Government Procurement Law Program<BR>
B.A., University of Virginia; J.D., American University<BR>
Professor Lees joined the Government Contracts Program Conference and Research
Center in 1985 and was director of that program from 1987 to 1991. He currently
serves as co-director of the Government Procurement Law LL.M. Program.
Before joining the Government Contracts Program, Professor Lees served
for 12 years as Chairman/Chief Administrative Judge of the Board of Contract
Appeals, National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA). He served
concurrently as Chairman of the statutory NASA Inventions and Contributions
Board. Earlier in his career, following service as an officer in the U.S.
Navy, Professor Lees was a patent examiner in the U.S. Patent and Trademark
Office; he later practiced intellectual property law on the legal staff
of NASA. He is a past president of the Board of Contract Appeals Judges
Association, and is currently active in the field of alternative dispute
resolution. From January 1989 to April 1990, he held an appointment as
Special Master in the Circuit Court for Anne Arundel County, Maryland,
to conduct the pretrial hearings in the precedential case of State of Maryland
v. Keene Corporation, et. al., involving major asbestos litigation. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="fac/miller.htm">Terry
Elaine Miller</A>, Adjunct Associate Professor of Law<BR>
B.S., Cornell University; M.A., Columbia University; J.D., American University<BR>
Professor Miller joined the Government Contracts Program Conference and
Research Center in 1992 and was deputy director of that program. In 1993
she became a visiting member of the faculty in the Law School's Government
Procurement Law Program. Previously, she practiced in the government contracts
practice group of the litigation department of Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver
&amp; Jacobson in Washington, D.C. Following law school, she clerked for
Judge Julia Cooper Mack of the D.C. Court of Appeals. Professor Miller
currently serves as an executive adviser to the IRS Tax Modernization Institute
and is engaged in independent consulting in the field of government contracts
law. She has taught extensively in both law school and continuing education
settings for government contractors, federal agencies, and international
entities including the United Nations and The World Bank. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>Stephen D. Knight, Professorial
Lecturer in Law<BR>
B.A., J.D., University of Virginia<BR>
Mr. Knight is a partner in the law firm of Kirkland &amp; Ellis in Washington,
D.C., where he counsels and represents clients in litigation on all aspects
of government contracts. His work centers on claims and disputes, government
contract cost accounting, cost allowability, Cost Accounting Standards,
defective pricing, government audits, contract compliance, and procurement
fraud. Mr. Knight has specialized in government contracts practice since
1978 and has published widely in the field. </FONT></FONT></P>

<P><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" HEIGHT=13 WIDTH=357><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>
</FONT></FONT></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.gwu.edu/"><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/gwu-logo.gif" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=50 WIDTH=50></A><FONT FACE="HELVETICA,ARIAL"><FONT SIZE=-1>
<A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/"><IMG SRC="http://128.164.161.15/woodicon.gif" BORDER=0 HEIGHT=50 WIDTH=50></A>
</FONT></FONT></P>

