<head>
<TITLE>Intellectual Property Law LL.M.</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<h2>Intellectual Property Law LL.M.</h2>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13><p>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/bulb.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=202 ALIGN=left>
<P>
<H3>About the Intellectual Property Law LL.M.</H3>



The Intellectual Property Law Program has grown  from a single patent law class taught in 1891 by the Commis-sioner of Patents to one of the most highly acclaimed programs of its kind among major U.S. law schools today.  The focus of the program is on patents, particularly  international and comparative aspects of the field.  With its extensive curriculum, expert faculty, and Washington, D.C.,  location, the program provides unique opportunities for students to be at the forefront of domestic and international patent  policy development. Enriching the formal program of study are the activities of  the Dean Dinwoodey Center for Intellectual Property Studies,  a graduate research institute. The Dinwoodey Center sponsors frequent programs on policy matters that bring together leading academics and jurists from all over the world.  
<P>
The Intellectual Property Law LL.M. Program is designed to provide law school graduates interested in teaching, public policy, or international and comparative aspects of the field with a broad-based curriculum and individualized support for their research. While student enrollment at the Law School numbers more than 1,700, enrollment in the Intellectual Property Law LL.M. program is limited to approximately 15 new students each year.  Because patent law remains the central aspect of the program, students are expected to enter with a basic knowledge of the field.  The student's goal should be to focus on a particular area of scholarship or practice issues, whether domestic, foreign, or comparative.
<P>
To earn the LL.M. degree in Intellectual Property Law, students complete 24 credit hours that include a minimum of 10 hours in intellectual property law courses and 4 hours of thesis. Admission to the program is generally granted for the fall semester; spring admission may be allowed in special circumstances at the discretion of the program director.Both full- and part-time programs of study are offered.  Full-time students usually complete the program within one calendar year (two semesters and one summer); part-time students usually complete the program in two calendar years.

<H3>Internships and Foreign Study</H3>
For many students, internships have proven to be one of the best ways to gain mentorship from members of the local intellectual property community.  Students are especially encouraged to seek internships with a circuit judge at the nearby U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.  Regular full-time clerkships, while highly competitive, are also an option for LL.M. students.  Students who arrange for an approved, nonremunerative placement may receive up to four hours of credit for their work, with five hours of work per week being required for each credit. Selected students also have the opportunity for foreign study during the summer or after graduation.  A number of program graduates have received fellowships at the Max Planck Institute for Foreign and International Patent Copyright and Competition Law in Munich or Chizaiken in Tokyo.

<H3>Intellectual Property Studies in the Nation's Capital</H3>
One of the great benefits of studying intellectual property law at GW is that the "real world" is at the student's doorstep. Across the Potomac River stands the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.  Nearby Capitol Hill is home to the Copyright Office and the House and Senate Judiciary Committees with principal jurisdiction for intellectual property cases.  The current climate of legislative activity in patents permits important opportunities for students to observe hearings conducted on Capitol Hill.  Some students work as interns on the Hill, while others participate in the preparatory work that takes place in the Administration and with the bar and trade associations.  The National Courts Building on Lafayette Square across from the White House (and four blocks from GW) houses courtrooms of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit and the U.S. Court of Federal Claims.  In addition, the Bar Association of the District of Columbia has a special intellectual property section that holds its council meetings at the University and actively welcomes student participation in its events.More than 1,000 patent attorneys in scores of law firms of all sizes practice in Washington. Full- and part-time work at these firms can provide an invaluable learning experience. The Law School has graduated far more patent lawyers than any other law school in the country.  These alumni are strongly represented in the local patent bar, and many alumni participate in the life of the school.

<H3>The Dean Dinwoodey Center for Intellectual Property Studies</H3>
The Dean Dinwoodey Center for Intellectual Property Studies is chartered by the University and 
funded in part by the Bureau of National Affairs in memory of its founder Dean Dinwoodey, J.D. 29.  Hundreds of intellectual property scholars and practitioners have participated in programs of the Dinwoodey Center, and each year a number of prominent lawyers and officials from around the world visit the Law School to conduct research and participate in Dinwoodey Center activities. Dinwoodey Center area projects have studied the patent and other intellectual property laws of foreign countries including Thailand, India, Poland, and Brazil.  The major focus of comparative study has been East Asia, with extensive studies focusing on China and Japan.  One facet of the Dinwoodey Center, the China Project, is coordinated by the Center's associate director, Andy Y. Sun. The China Project sponsors programs such as the recent China Week, which featured a series of discussions with leading Chinese government officials, judges, and professors.  Japanese studies have also been diverse, with numerous visits by delegations from Tokyo and reciprocal visits from Dinwoodey Center members.  Mr. Yoichiro Yamaguchi, who teaches Japanese patent policy at GW, is a regular participant in Dinwoodey Center activities and provides expertise based on his prior service in the Japanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry.  Relationships with Europe continue principally through an exchange of scholars, including those from the Max Planck Institute. The Dinwoodey Center also focuses on the need for domestic patent reform.  Conferences held in nearby Airlie, Virginia, have involved leading officials from all branches of government.  One conference produced an "Airlie Draft" proposing legislative reform involving a 20-year patent term, 18-month automatic publication of patent applications, and related measures.  All of these initiatives became part of the legislative and diplomatic processes and were the basis for Japan-U.S. bilateral agreements in 1994. One initiative was enacted into law as part of the Uruguay Round Agreements Act of 1994.  Vigilance over the examination process and regulatory reform are also of concern, and members of the Dinwoodey Center are active in the regulatory process. Graduate law students are integral to the development of Dinwoodey Center activities.  Two new endeavors, the India Project and the Rio Project, were recently established by program students.

<H3>Intellectual Property Law Curriculum</H3>



<UL>
<LI>Patent Law
<LI>Copyright Law
<LI>Trademark Law
<LI>Patent Policy and Practice
<LI>Licensing of Intellectual Property Rights
<LI>Chemical and Biotech Patent Law
<LI>Patent Enforcement
<LI>Computer Law
<LI>Biotechnology Patent Policy
<LI>Japanese Patent Policy
<LI>International and Comparative Patent Law
<LI>Intellectual Property Antitrust Seminar
<LI>Intellectual Property Law Seminar
<LI>Intellectual Property Issues Short Seminar
</UL>

<p>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13>
<p>
<A HREF="http://www.gwu.edu/"><img src="http://128.164.161.15/gwu-logo.gif" WIDTH=50 HEIGHT=50 border=0></A>
<A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/"><img src="http://128.164.161.15/woodicon.gif" WIDTH=50 HEIGHT=50 border=0></A>
</body>
