<html>
<head>
<TITLE>General LL.M.</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<h2>General LL.M.</h2>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13><p>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/scales.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=202 ALIGN=left>
<P>


The General LL.M. Program accepts a limited number of students to study in areas other than those covered in the specialized programs.  U.S. law school graduates applying to the General LL.M. Program must submit with the application a proposed program of study that includes courses to be taken and a general statement outlining the area of concentration for the thesis.  Upon admission the student will be paired with a faculty member in that area who will assist in further developing a curriculum to fit the student's specific needs and also provide supervision for the thesis.  Areas of interest are limited only by the availability of faculty advisers.
<P>
Recent General LL.M. candidates have focused in such areas as labor law, constitutional law, land development law, and corporate law and securities regulation.  Other possible areas of concentration may be determined by consulting the sections dealing with curriculum in the Law School Bulletin. The General LL.M. Program is directed by the associate dean for academic affairs.
<P>
Graduates of foreign law schools may also pursue the General LL.M. as a means of studying a range of issues in American law.  Such students must be admitted to the International Legal Studies Program.
<p>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13>
<p>
<A HREF="http://www.gwu.edu/"><img src="http://128.164.161.15/gwu-logo.gif" WIDTH=50 HEIGHT=50 border=0></A>
<A HREF="http://www.law.gwu.edu/"><img src="http://128.164.161.15/woodicon.gif" WIDTH=50 HEIGHT=50 border=0></A>
</body>
