<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
Thomas Buergenthal
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_buerge.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=147>



<h3>
Thomas Buergenthal
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Lobingier Professor of Comparative Law and Jurisprudence; Director of the Inter-national and Comparative Law Program
B.A., LL.D., Bethany College;J.D., New York University; LL.M., S.J.D., Harvard University; Dr.jur.(h.c.), University of Heidelberg and Free University of Brussels
<p>
<p>


Professor Buergenthal served as dean 
of the American University School of 
Law from 1980 to 1985. He was a judge 
of the Inter-American Court of Human Rights from 1979 to 1991 and also served as the Court s president in the mid-1980s. He now serves as the United States member of the U.N. Human Rights Committee.  In 1992 93, he was a member of the U.N. Truth Commission for El Salvador.  From 1989 to 1994 he was a judge and subsequently the president of the Admin-
istrative Tribunal of the Inter-American Development Bank. He is a member of several editorial boards including those of the American Journal of International Law, Encyclopedia of Public International Law, and The Human Rights Law Journal, and he was a member of the Advisory Board of the American Law Institute s Restatement (Third) on the Foreign Relations Law of the United States. He is honorary president of the Inter-American Institute of Human Rights (San Jos Costa Rica), an honorary vice president of the American Society of International Law, and serves on the Council of the Max Planck Institute for Public Inter-national Law (Heidelberg, Germany) 
and the International Institute of Human Rights (Strasbourg, France). Professor Buergenthal is the author of more than 
a dozen books and numerous articles 
on public international law, international human rights, the law of international organizations, and comparative law.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
