<h3>
Miriam Galston
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Associate Professor of Law<BR>
B.A., Cornell University<BR> 
Ph.D., University of Chicago<BR>
J.D., Yale University<BR>
<p>
<p>

Professor Galston taught the history 
of political thought at the University of Texas in 1976 and at Brandeis University from 1977 to 1979. She has written widely in the area of Islamic philosophy; her book Politics and Excellence: the Political Philosophy of Alfarabi was published in 1990. After law school, she was in private practice in Washington, D.C., for eight years, specializing in tax law. Since 
joining the faculty of the Law School 
in 1991, she has taught in the areas of jurisprudence, corporations, bankruptcy, and nonprofit organizations.
