<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
Beth Nolan
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_nolan.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=145>



<h3>
Beth Nolan
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Associate Professor of Law<BR>
B.A., Scripps College<BR>
J.D. Georgetown University<BR>
<p>
<p>


After serving as editor-in-chief of the Georgetown Law Journal, Professor Nolan clerked for the Honorable Collins J. Seitz of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit. She then held the position of attorney-adviser in the Office of Legal Counsel of the U.S. Department of Justice, where she advised on the 
constitutionality and interpretation of federal laws and programs as well as on issues of government power and 
government ethics. Professor Nolan joined the Law School faculty in 1985 and teaches courses in constitutional law and professional responsibility and ethics. She writes primarily in the field 
of government ethics. From spring 1993 through spring 1995, Professor Nolan 
was on leave from the Law School and served in the White House as Associate Counsel to the President. She was also appointed by President Clinton to be 
a member of the National Commission 
on Judicial Discipline and Removal.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
