<html>
<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
Stephen Allan Saltzburg
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_saltzb.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=143>



<h3>
Stephen Allan Saltzburg
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Howrey Professor of Trial Advocacy, Liti-gation, and Professional Responsibility<BR>
B.A., Dickinson College<BR> 
J.D., University of Pennsylvania<BR>
<p>
<p>



Professor Saltzburg clerked for U.S. District Judge Stanley A. Weigel in San Francisco in 1970 71 and for Associate Justice Thurgood Marshall during the 1971 term of the Supreme Court. He 
then began teaching at the University 
of Virginia, where in 1987 he was awarded a chair endowed by the UVA class of 1962 at its 25th reunion. During his years in teaching, he has done a substantial number of pro bono cases and has 
frequently been appointed counsel by federal trial and appellate courts. He 
has argued three times before the U.S. Supreme Court. In 1981, he established the UVA Trial Advocacy Institute, which continues to be one of the country s 
outstanding trial advocacy programs for lawyers and students. In 1988, Professor Saltzburg was named deputy assistant attorney general in the Criminal Division of the Department of Justice; he served as the Attorney General s ex officio 
representative on the U.S. Sentencing Commission. In 1994, the Secretary of 
the Treasury appointed Professor Saltzburg director of the Tax Refund Fraud Task Force. A recognized expert 
on sentencing and procedure, Professor Saltzburg has written widely on criminal justice and evidence issues. He serves 
as chair of the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia Civil Justice Reform Act Advisory Group. Professor Saltzburg joined the Law School faculty in 1990, and is director of the trial advocacy 
program. In 1993 he began the College 
of Advocacy at the Law School, an in-depth advocacy program co-sponsored by the Litigation Section of the D.C. Bar.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
