<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
Roger E. Schechter
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_schech.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=140>



<h3>
Roger E. Schechter
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Professor of Law<BR> William Thomas Fryer Research Professor of Law<BR>
B.A., George Washington University<BR> 
J.D., Harvard University<BR>
<p>
<p>

 

Professor Schechter joined the Law School faculty in 1980. Previously, he had practiced trade regulatory law with the New York City firm of Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison, and served as a judicial law clerk for the Honorable Paul H. Roney on the U.S. Court of Appeals 
for the Fifth Circuit. In 1990 he spent a semester as a visiting professor of law 
at the University of Virginia. Professor Schechter teaches the basic course in torts and other intellectual property 
and trade regulation courses such as copyright, antitrust, and unfair trade 
practices, and is a bar review lecturer on torts in numerous jurisdictions around the country. He is co-author of a casebook on unfair trade practices, and has written a student study guide on the subject; much of his writing concerns legal regulation of false advertising and the role of the Federal Trade Commission. 
His articles have appeared in a number of journals, including the University of Virginia Law Review, the Administrative Law Review, the University of Illinois Law Review, and the Antitrust Bulletin. He is also a member of the Editorial Advisory Board of the Advertising Law Anthology. Professor Schechter has twice received the Law School s Distinguished Faculty Service Award, selected by vote of 
the 1989 and 1994 graduating classes. 
He has also participated on several 
occasions in programs designed to 
help new law teachers develop 
effective classroom teaching skills.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
