<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory

</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_untitl.gif">



<h3>Eric Scott Sirulnik
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>

Associate Dean for Clinical Affairs 
and Research Development and Professor of Law
B.A., Franklin and Marshall College; 
J.D., Boston University;
LL.M., George Washington University
<p>
<p>

Dean Sirulnik began his association 
with clinical legal education as a stud-
ent prosecutor in the Suffolk County, Massachusetts, District Attorney s Office while in his third year of law school 
at Boston University. He continued his 
studies in this field by serving as a VISTA attorney assigned to the Neighborhood Legal Services Program of the District 
of Columbia while earning a Master of Laws degree at GW Law School. After a year of teaching law and the humanities at the undergraduate level at GW, he joined the faculty of the Law School, where he implemented and currently directs one of the country s largest and most well-respected clinical programs. As clinical director, he developed substantial clinical programs in civil litigation, law and aging, immigration law, small busi-ness law, and trial practice. Dean Sirulnik 
has received numerous grants for his 
clinical work, gaining recognition from 
the U.S. Administration on Aging, Legal Services Corporation, U.S. Department 
of Education, and U.S. Small Business Administration, among others. In 1994 he co-authored and successfully introduced the first ever student practice rule for the U.S. Court of Federal Claims. His classroom teaching has included torts, criminal law and procedure and a unique course 
on drugs and the law, which combines 
a practical skills-training format with an exploration of federal drug policy and substantive law. In 1994 he was appointed to the position of associate dean for 
clinical affairs and research development.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
