<html>
<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
John A. Spanogle
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_spanog.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=143>



<h3>
John A. Spanogle
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Professor of Law<BR>William Wallace Kirkpatrick Research Professor of Law<BR>
B.S.E., Princeton University<BR> 
J.D., University of Chicago<BR>
<p>
<p>



Professor Spanogle joined the Law School faculty in 1988. He has taught at the University of California at Berkeley, Vanderbilt University, University of Texas, University of Maine, SUNY at Buffalo, 
and Bond and Monash Universities in Australia. He has written many articles 
on commercial and consumer law. 
He drafted three Titles of Maine s state statutes on banking, commercial, and consumer law. A founding member of Ralph Nader s Public Interest Research Group, he is the co-author of the widely used casebook Consumer Law. Profes-
sor Spanogle is also the co-author of International Business Transactions, the most widely used casebook in its field. From 1982 to 1989, he was a member of the U.S. delegation to the United Nations Commission on International Trade 
Law and was the chief of delegation 
to its Working Group on Payment Systems. Professor Spanogle s research 
on the commercial law of other nations has resulted in books and articles on Egyptian agricultural law and Chinese commercial dispute resolution. During his 1991 92 sabbatical, he received a Fulbright Grant to be an adviser to the Polish Minister of Finance, which has led to his serving as a consultant to numerous international organizations on proposed commercial financing legislation.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
