<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
James Edward Starrs
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_starrs.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=142>



<h3>
James Edward Starrs
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Professor of Law and Forensic Sciences<BR>
B.A., LL.B., St. John s University, New York<BR> 
LL.M., New York University<BR>
<p>
<p>



Professor Starrs has been a member 
of the Law School faculty since 1964. 
He has taught courses in criminal law, criminal procedure, and property as well as an elective entitled Forensic Science. He completed his post-graduate work 
in criminal law at New York University, where he subsequently held a Ford Foundation Fellowship. Professor Starrs holds a joint appointment with the 
faculty of GW s Columbian School of 
Arts and Sciences, where he specializes in forensic science. Apart from co-authoring a leading textbook on scientific 
evidence, Professor Starrs has directed 
or participated in scientific investigations into the Lindbergh kidnapping, the Sacco and Vanzetti robbery-murders, the Alfred Packer cannibalism cases, the assassination of Senator Huey Long, the hatchet murders of the Bordens, the CIA-LSD related death of Frank Olson, the identification of Jesse James, and the mysterious death of Meriwether Lewis. He has written numerous articles on issues in forensic science and has written and edited The Scientific Sleuthing Review, a journal of legal and scientific information, for 20 years.  Professor Starrs is a distinguished fellow of the American Academy of Forensic Sciences.
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
