<head>
<title>
Faculty Directory
Harold C. Wegner
</title>
</head>
<font face="HELVETICA,arial" size=-1>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<br>



<img src="http://128.164.161.15/s_wegner.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=145>



<h3>
Harold C. Wegner
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Professor of  Law<BR>Director of the Intellectual Property Law Program<BR>Director of the Dean Dinwoodey Center for Intellectual Property Studies and Freedom of Expression<BR>
B.A., Northwestern University<BR> 
J.D., Georgetown University<BR>
<p>
<p>



Professor Wegner joined the faculty in 1989, after six years as an adjunct professor at the Georgetown University Law Center. He started his career in 1965 as a patent examiner; for most of his career he has been in private practice. He has held positions of leadership in several private-sector groups, including the American Intellectual Property Law Association, where he was a member of the Board of Directors. In 1975 76, Professor Wegner lived in Munich as a stipendiat of the Max Planck Society, serving as a research fellow at the Max Planck Institute for Foreign and International Patent, Copyright and Competition Law. In 1977, he was a kenshuin at the Kyoto University Law Faculty. Since 1985 Professor Wegner has been contributing to the crafting of a patent-harmonization treaty in Geneva as part of a United Nations World Intellectual Property Organization Committee of Experts; he is the only private-sector member whose involvement dates back to the initial meetings of the Committee. Professor Wegner often testifies on intellectual property issues before congressional committees and the Department of Commerce. 
<br>
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
