<h3>
Arthur E. Wilmarth, Jr.
</h3><img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" width=357 height=17><p>
Associate Professor of Law<BR>
B.A., Yale University<BR> 
J.D., Harvard University<BR>
<p>
<p>



Professor Wilmarth joined the faculty of the Law School in 1986, following eleven years in private practice. Prior to joining the faculty, he was a partner in the Washington, D.C., office of Jones, Day, Reavis & Pogue. Professor Wilmarth teaches courses in banking law, contracts, corporations, and American legal history. He is the author of several articles 
in the fields of banking law and Amer-ican legal history, and the co-author 
of a book on corporate law. Professor Wilmarth returned to the faculty in fall 1994, after a two-year leave of absence during which he practiced as a partner in the Lancaster, Pennsylvania, office of Barley, Snyder, Senft & Cohen.
<br>
</body>
