<head>
<title>
GWLaw Spring '97 PASS Info
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<font face="HELVETICA,ARIAL" size=-1>
<h5>GW Law School<br>
Records Office</h5><br><P>
<h4> PASS Information for Spring '97 Registration<br>
<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13></h4>


<H5><I>(Exerpt from The Evening Exchange Newsletter, by Frank Durand, Asst. Dean of
Student Affairs)</I></H5>
<ul>

     <li>PASS class requests will be turned in at the time of registration.  As a reminder, PASS
stands for <i>Priority Assured Seating System</i>.  Your PASS class should be the course you
most want/need in a given semester.  You will be given priority for a seat in that class over others
who do not designate that class as their PASS class.
</li>
     <li>The Records Office will make every effort not to bump students from their PASS class.
</li>
     <li>Students may designate as their PASS class any class that is OPEN or that is WAIT-
LISTED.
</li>
     <li>If students designate as their PASS class a wait-listed class, those students will be given
preference for a seat in that class.
</li>
     <li>Students may NOT designate as their PASS class any of the <i>legal clinics</i>.
</li>
     <li>The following classes will be wait-listed at registration: <i>all seminars, Trial Advocacy,
classes with fewers than 20 open seats.</i>
</li>
     <li><b>Students my NOT register for a wait-listed class unless they win a seat through the
lottery.  At registration, students interested in a wait-listed class must instead sign their names to
the wait list.</b>
</li>
</ul>



<p><br>
<h5><i>Updated: 10/28/96</i><br>

<img src="http://128.164.161.15/yline.gif" WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=13></h5>

<p>
</font>
