<title>Internet Update #17</title>
<meta name="Author" content="GWULAW">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">

</head>
<body>

<h1>Internet Update #17</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #17</h3>
<h3>JANUARY 1997</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the seventeenth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>


<ol>
   <li>Black Box:  Pan-Asia Web Directory*</li>
   <li>Building, Books, and Bytes:  Libraries and Communities in the Digital Age#</li>
   <li>Commercial News USA#</li>
   <li>Companies Online--Dun & Bradstreet and Lycos#</li>
   <li>EPA Announces Proposed New Air Quality Standards#</li>
   <li>FDIC Institution Directory#</li>
   <li>Harvard University Writing Center Online*</li>
   <li>HIV/AIDS:  The Global Epidemic#</li>
   <li>Internet Public Library Online Text Enhancements#</li>
   <li>Latin American Government Documents Project#</li>
   <li>National Endowment for the Arts*</li>
   <li>NetPubs International*</li>
   <li>Organization of American Historians*</li>
   <li>Overseas Development Council*</li>
   <li>Region-Specific News Sites:  (1) Central Europe Online, (2) Russia Today, and (3) Inside China Today#</li>
   <li>Simon Fraser University*</li>
   <li>Sociosite:  Going Dutch Sociology#</li>
   <li>Stanford Electronic Humanities Review*</li>
   <li>Sun Microsystems, Inc.*</li>
   <li>Tears of Shock*</li>
   <li>Ten Downing Street#</li>
   <li>Transnational Records Clearinghouse (TRAC) Drug Enforcement Information*</li>
   <li>Washington Post Job Hunting Online:  "What Color is Your Parachute:  The Net Guide"*</li>
   <li>Washington University's EconWPA:  Working Papers in Economics Archive*</li>
</ol>


<h3>This issue includes the following listserv:</h3>
<ol>
   <li>Site-tation:  Legal Site of the Week Mailing List</li>
</ol>

<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.orientation.com/">1.  BLACK BOX:  PAN-ASIA WEB DIRECTORY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.orientation.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Black Box, a Hong Kong-based interactive-media company, has created a multilingual directory on the World Wide Web that directs users to sites related to Asia.  The service, which lists subjects such as the arts, business, and culture, can be viewed in English, simplified Chinese, traditional Chinese, or Japanese."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://www.benton.org/Kellogg/buildings.html">2.  BUILDING, BOOKS, AND BYTES:  LIBRARIES AND COMMUNITIES IN THE DIGITAL AGE</a>
  <br>
  http://www.benton.org/Kellogg/buildings.html
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "The Benton Foundation, with funding from the W.K. Kellogg Foundation, has recently made this study available at their website.  It 'compares library leaders' visions for the future with the public's prescriptions for libraries[.]'  Using libraries as a focal point, it should provoke much thought about how other institutions that provide public information will be impacted by the digital revolution.  The study is based on 'a national survey to test public support for libraries in the digital age,' conducted in April of 1996.  At present the study is available in HTML, with an Adobe Acrobat (PDF) version forthcoming."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://www.cnewsusa.com/">3.  COMMERCIAL NEWS USA</a>
  <br>
  http://www.cnewsusa.com/
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "This site is the electronic version of an official publication of the United States Department of Commerce.  CNUSA is an American export catalog-magazine that is designed to promote U.S. products and services to more than 150 countries at a fraction of the cost of any other form of advertising.  The site is divided into two sections, one for importers and one for exporters.  The importer section contains a searchable directory of U.S. exporters and allows users to post special requests for products and services on an electronic bulletin board.  The exporter section contains information for signing up as well as information on what importers are looking for."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.companiesonline.com/">4.  COMPANIES ONLINE--DUN & BRADSTREET AND LYCOS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.companiesonline.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Dun & Bradstreet, the business information provider, along with the Internet search directory Lycos, has made available this database containing cursory information on over 60,000 public and private U.S. companies with websites.  The quantity of the database is more important at this site than the amount of data available about each site (which is rather scanty, even for the enhanced registered user's retrieval).  There are several search options, but the main feature of the site is a hypertext connection(s) to each retrieved company."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://ttnwww.rtpnc.epa.gov/naaqspro/">5.  EPA ANNOUNCES PROPOSED NEW AIR QUALITY STANDARDS</a>
  <br>
  http://ttnwww.rtpnc.epa.gov/naaqspro/
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "The United States Environmental Protection Agency has recently proposed new air quality standards for ozone and particulate matter, and information about these proposals is available at a newly established website.  The highlight of the site is the availability of fact sheets, along with full texts (in .zip format) of the new proposals.  There is also a listing of counties not meeting the current and proposed ozone and particulate matter standards, along with a map of counties not meeting the proposed ozone standard.  Also at the site is a fact sheet on how the proposed standards will affect your city or county."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.fdic.gov/">6.  FDIC INSTITUTION DIRECTORY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.fdic.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The U.S. FDIC has recently made its Institution Directory available.  This searchable database allows users to 'obtain demographic data and financial profiles of each FDIC-insured depository institution derived from quarterly reports filed with Federal regulators.'  Users can search by certificate number, bank, geographic location, charter, chartering agency, federal regulator, primary insurance fund, and asset and deposit size.  Retrieval can be sorted by any of 7 variables.  Information returned includes balance sheet and income, loan portfolio/asset quality, and balance sheet details.  Each report is linked to a glossary of terms.  Quarterly and annual data is available back to December 1993.  This is a significant addition to a site that already carries a staggering amount of information about United States banking."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ipl.org/reading/books/">7.  INTERNET PUBLIC LIBRARY ONLINE TEXT ENHANCEMENTS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ipl.org/reading/books/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The well known Internet Public Library has recently revised its online texts collection to make it available for searching and browsing by author, title, and Dewey Classification.  The significance of this enhancement lies in the way the site is organized.  Each entry is accompanied by bibliographic information, including title, author, date, Dewey Classification(s), and hypertext URL(s).  There is an interesting, though not yet perfected, feature that allows users to link to similar works.  A key feature is the listing of books under multiple classifications.  At present, the library contains pointers to over 3,700 books."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~wricntr/">8.  HARVARD UNIVERSITY WRITING CENTER ONLINE</a>
  <br>
  http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~wricntr/
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "Harvard University has created a site on the World Wide Web that provides students with access to online handouts, publications, and links to sites on the Internet related to writing.  Harvard undergraduates can schedule online appointments with peer tutors and receive assistance with assignments or gain access to online publications such as The Harvard Crimson."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://www.unaids.org/highband/document/epidemio/situat96.html">9.  HIV/AIDS:  THE GLOBAL EPIDEMIC</a>
  <br>
  http://www.unaids.org/highband/document/epidemio/situat96.html
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "Provided by the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS and the World Health Organization, this fact sheet provides up-to-date information on the progress of the worldwide AIDS pandemic.  It provides estimates as of December 1996 for new infections in 1996, people living with HIV/AIDS, HIV/AIDS-associated deaths in 1996, and cumulative AIDS information.  It also contains a geographic table of AIDS-related information.  It is connected to a much larger study (The Status and Trends of the Global HIV/AIDS Pandemic)."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://lib1.library.cornell.edu/colldev/ladocshome.html">10.  LATIN AMERICAN GOVERNMENT DOCUMENTS PROJECT</a>
  <br>
  http://lib1.library.cornell.edu/colldev/ladocshome.html
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "The Latin American Government Documents Project, provided by David Block of the Olin Library of Cornell University, attempts to 'organize and describe the many Latin American official documents now appearing on the Internet.'  The site is organized by country and agency, within subject themes that include statistical sources, executive documents, national legislative documents, national judicial documents, and subnational documents.  The contents of each site are briefly summarized.  This is a very well organized, concise pointer site that should be very useful to interested Internauts.  Note that most of the pointers are to Spanish language sites."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://arts.endow.gov/">11.  NATIONAL ENDOWMENT FOR THE ARTS</a>
   <br>
   http://arts.endow.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "National Endowment for the Arts offers access through the World Wide Web to 'arts.community,' a site that promotes ties between the arts and the public.  It contains information on NEA grants, publications, and reports, links to arts organizations, and access to 'arts.community,' an online monthly journal."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.netpubsintl.com/IPNews.html">12.  NETPUBS INTERNATIONAL</a>
   <br>
   http://www.netpubsintl.com/IPNews.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "NetPubs International offers access through the World Wide Web to the online edition of 'IP News,' a subscription-based newsletter that focuses on electronic publications as they relate to the academic and professional publishing community.  The first issue is available for viewing at no charge."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~oah/">13.  ORGANIZATIONS OF AMERICAN HISTORIANS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.indiana.edu/~oah/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Organization of American Historians maintains a home page on the World Wide Web that offers scholars access to information on the organization's activities, membership, and professional opportunities.  Users can get the online edition of the 'OAH Newsletter' or follow links to other resources of interest to historians."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.odc.org/">14.  OVERSEAS DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL</a>
   <br>
   http://www.odc.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Overseas Development Council provides access through the World Wide Web to the full text of research papers and commentary on international issues.  Topics include democratization, international trade, and environmental development.  The service contains a listing of senior staff members, program descriptions, and links to other resources."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
15.   REGION-SPECIFIC NEWS SITES
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.centraleurope.com/">(1) CENTRAL EUROPE ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.centraleurope.com/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.russiatoday.com/">(2) RUSSIA TODAY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.russiatoday.com/
   <br>
   <a href="http://www.insidechina.com/">(3) INSIDE CHINA TODAY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.insidechina.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "These three websites, all services of the European Information Network, bring English-language news and background to users each weekday.  Central Europe Online covers the Czech Republic, Poland, Hungary, Slovakia, and Slovenia; Russia Today gathers news about Russia, the Confederation of Independent States, and the Baltics; Inside China Today covers Mainland China, Hong Kong and Macao, and Taiwan.  All three sites offer current headlines (along with the time that they were most recently updated), business news, travel information, and links to local media.  News stories are drawn primarily from Reuters.  Each site has its own system of organization, which, though easy to navigate, is not directly consistent with that of the other sites.  An archive holds issues dating back two weeks.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.ccsp.sfu.ca/calj/">16.  SIMON FRASER UNIVERSITY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.ccsp.sfu.ca/calj/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Simon Fraser University offers access through the World Wide Web to the tables of contents of more than 40 Canadian scholarly journals.  The site, based on material from the Canadian Association of Learned Journals, links users to the home pages of each journal and includes a description of the publication, how to contact the editors, and the contents of all previous years.  The full text of some journals is also available."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://www.pscw.uva.nl/sociosite/">17.  SOCIOSITE:  GOING DUTCH SOCIOLOGY</a>
  <br>
  http://www.pscw.uva/nl/sociosite/
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "This site, provided by Albert Benschop of the Sociological Institute of the University of Amsterdam, is a large meta-site that is international in scope and European in flavor, although there are also pointers to non-European sites.  Its main page contains annotated pointers to sites in 24 main topic areas from data archives to subject areas (106 at this time, from activism to work).  Sites are accompanied by brief annotations, and when geographic breakouts are available, they often contain the Dutch, then European, then non-European sites.  Unfortunately there is no search utility, which would help users navigate the hundreds of pointers."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://shr.stanford.edu/shreview/index.html">18.  STANFORD ELECTRONICS HUMANITIES REVIEW</a>
  <br>
  http://shr.stanford.edu/shreview/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "Stanford University offers access through the World Wide Web to the full text articles featured in The Stanford Electronic Humanities Review.  The site contains articles from a diversity of viewpoints on topics such as artificial intelligence and religious tradition."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.suned.com/">19.  SUN MICROSYSTEMS, INC.</a>
   <br>
   http://www.suned.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Sun Microsystems Inc. has created a virtual campus on the World Wide Web for exploring nine areas of technological developments in education, including administration, distance learning, intranet/internet, and high-performance computing; features audio and video clips from the company's education specialists, information on current projects, and demonstrations of new applications."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.snunit.k12.il/rabin/">20.  TEARS OF SHOCK</a>
   <br>
   http://www.snunit.k12.il/rabin/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Hebrew University of Jerusalem offers access through the World Wide Web to 'Tears of Shock,' a virtual photographic exhibit that follows the events and emotions in Tel Aviv following the assassination of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.number-10.gov.uk/">21.  TEN DOWNING STREET</a>
   <br>
   http://www.number-10.gov.uk/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The British Prime Minister's Office has recently opened a website, 10 Downing Street.  Although it does contain selected Prime Minister's speeches, transcripts, and interviews, Prime Minister's biographies (back to Harold Macmillan at present), and a tour of #10, its greatest utility is as an entry point to British executive department government sites.  The Cabinet Ministers' Biography section contains information on 23 ministers and links to cabinet websites.  There is also a page of government department pointers."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://trac.syr.edu/tracdea/">22.  TRANSACTIONAL RECORDS CLEARINGHOUSE (TRAC) DRUG ENFORCEMENT INFORMATION</a>
   <br>
   http://trac.syr.edu/tracdea/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Syracuse University and Transactional Records Clearinghouse offer access through the World Wide Web to information on drug enforcement in the United States including background information on the Drug Enforcement Agency, text of the criminal statutes it enforces, and statistics on prosecutions and convictions."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://washingtonpost.com/parachute/">23.  WASHINGTON POST JOB HUNTING ONLINE:  "WHAT COLOR IS YOUR PARACHUTE:  THE NET GUIDE"</a>
  <br>
  http://washingtonpost.com/parachute/
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "The Washington Post offers access through the World Wide Web to </i><u>What Color is Your Parachute:  The Net Guide</u><i> by Richard N. Bolles.  The site presents the author's views on how to conduct online job searches, recommendations on useful online job listings, and advice on posting resumes."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
  <a href="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/">24.  WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY'S ECONWPA:  WORKING PAPERS IN ECONOMICS ARCHIVE</a>
  <br>
  http://econwpa.wustl.edu/
</dt>
<dd>
  <i>From the announcement:  "Washington University provides access through the World Wide Web to an archive of working papers in economics.  The site is divided into 22 subject areas, including microeconomics and macroeconomics, teaching, and economic history.  The site allows researchers and students to submit announcements, abstracts, or papers and links to other resources."</i>
</dd>

<p>

</dl>


<center>
<h2> ~ L I S T S E R V S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <b>1.  SITE-TATION:  LEGAL SITE OF THE WEEK MAILING LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Site-tation is a distribution list for 'Site-tation' (Legal Site of the Week) and 'What's New' on the ABA Network.  Site-tation is a page of the ABA Network that presents a different legal web site each week.  The ABA Network (http://www.abanet.org) is updated daily, and once a week What's New on the ABA Network is posted to the web site and now in a mailing list."  To subscribe:</i>
<p>
<i>Send mail to:</i>  listserver@abanet.org
<br>
<i>With the message:</i>  subscribe site-tation
</dd>

<p>

</dl>

<hr>

<i>Internet Update</i> is compiled by Leslie A. Lee, Reference Librarian at the Jacob Burns Law
Library, and is issued monthly as a service to the George Washington University Law School
community.

