<title>Internet Update #5</title>

<meta name="Author" content="GWULAW">
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">

</head>
<body>

<h1>Internet Update #5</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #5</h3>
<h3>JANUARY 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the fifth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>BosniaLINK#</li>
  <li>California State Bar</li>
  <li>Electronic Policy Network</li>
  <li>EPA's Acid Rain Program</li>
  <li>EPA's Government Information Locator Service (GILS)</li>
  <li>EPA &amp; Ozone Depletion</li>
  <li>EuroDocs (Primary Historical Documents from Western Europe)#</li>
  <li>Government Technology</li>
  <li>GPO Access -- FREE!#</li>
  <li>Guided Tour of the War on Drugs</li>
  <li>Law of Cyberspace:  Resources on the Internet</li>
  <li>Newsweb</li>
  <li>Office of Management and Budget (OMB)</li>
  <li>University of Michigan Government Documents Center</li>
  <li>Water Quality Association (WQA)</li>
</ol>


<h3>This issue includes the following gopher sites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>Bosnia Peace Treaty (Dayton Peace Agreement)</li>
</ol>


<center>
<h2>~ W E B S I T E S ~</h2>
</center>


<dl>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.dtic.dla.mil/bosnia/">1.  BOSNIALINK</a>
   <br>
   http://www.dtic.dla.mil/bosnia/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "BosniaLINK is the official Department of Defense
Information system about U.S. military activities in Operation 'Joint Endeavor', the
NATO peacekeeping mission in Bosnia.  The system is provided by the Office of the
Assistant to the Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs.  All information in
BosniaLINK is publicly released information from the U.S. government of NATO
headquarters.  BosniaLINK contains operation maps, fact sheets, news releases,
biographies of key commanders and leaders, and transcripts of briefings, speeches,
and testimony."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.calbar.org">2.  CALIFORNIA STATE BAR</a>
   <br>
   http://www.calbar.org
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Approaching the Third Millennium, the California Bar
is online!"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://epn.org/">3.  ELECTRONIC POLICY NETWORK</a>
   <br>
   http://epn.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Electronic Policy Network offers access through
the World Wide Web to articles, reports, and information on economic policy in the
United States, including access to three online magazines:  The Health Policy
Page, Economics and Policy, and Welfare and Families."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/docs/acidrain/ardhome.html">4.  EPA'S ACID RAIN PROGRAM</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/docs/acidrain/ardhome.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The website maintains sections on laws, regulations and
agreements; student resources; environmental benefits of acid rain control; and
pollution prevention.  Also featured is the SO2 Allowance Trading Program, a
market-based allowance trading system that enables regulated utilities, rather than
a governing agency, to decide the most cost-effective way to use available
resources to comply with the acid rain requirements of the Clean Air Act. 
Additional features are 'What's New' and a list of acid rain-related resources."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/gils/">5.  EPA'S GOVERNMENT INFORMATION LOCATOR SERVICE (GILS)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/gils/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The EPA's GILS website currently offers access to GILS
records, which describe the Agency's information resources, via two routes:  a
WAIS search engine and browsable subject headings.  Included at the site are
documents relevant to he origin and development of the government-wide GILS
effort, uch as OMB Circular 95-01 and the National Archives and Records
Administration guidance document on GILS core records, as well as PA specific
documents related to the Agency's GILS strategy and implementation."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/docs/ozone/index.html">6.  EPA &amp; OZONE DEPLETION</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/docs/ozone/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  This website contains information about the science of
ozone depletion, regulations in the US designed to protect the ozone layer, flyers
about the UV index, information for consumers, and other topics [from the
Stratospheric Ozone Protection Division Web Page]."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://library.byu.edu/~rdh/eurodocs/">7.  EURODOCS</a>
   <br>
   http://library.byu.edu/~rdh/eurodocs/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Primary Historical Documents from Western Europe, is
provided by a bibliographer at Harold B. Lee Library, Brigham Young University. 
The site includes pointers to documents and full text works for Medieval and
Renaissance Europe, Europe as a Supernational Region, and over 20 Western
European Countries. Materials are transcribed, translated, or facsimiles of the
originals."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.govtech.net">8.  GOVERNMENT TECHNOLOGY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.govtech.net
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "At this site you'll find solutions and resources for
governance in the Information Age.  This includes current and back issues of
Government Technology Magazine, information on our conferences, events and
special publications, as well as links to a wealth of resources.  This site is under
construction and will be updated regularly."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs">9.  GPO ACCESS -- FREE!</a>
   <br>
   http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Beginning 12/1/95, the U.S. Government Printing
Office (GPO), which operates GPO Access, dropped the subscription fee previously
required for use outside the Federal Depository Library Program gateways.  GPO
Access offers electronic access to congressional bills, calendars, documents, and
reports; titles such as the Congressional Record (and its index) and the 1995-96
U.S. Government Manual; as well as Economic Indicators, GAO Reports, Public
Laws, the U.S. Code, and the Unified Agenda."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.drcnet.org/">10.  GUIDED TOUR OF THE WAR ON DRUGS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.drcnet.org/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "You've entered the website of the Drug Reform
Coordination Network (DRCNet), 'Drug Policy Central' on the Internet.  Our
position is that the evidence on drug policy overwhelmingly favors
decriminalization and that reform is needed immediately."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www-law.lib.uchicago.edu/lib/cyberdoc.html">11.  LAW OF CYBERSPACE:  RESOURCES ON THE INTERNET</a>
   <br>
   http://www-law.lib.uchicago.edu/lib/cyberdoc.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>Lyonette Louis-Jacques, Foreign &amp; International Law Librarian and Lecturer in Law at the D'Angelo Law Library, University of Chicago Law School, has made her short guide on "The
Law of Cyberspace:  Resources on the Internet" available on the World Wide Web.</i>
</dd>

<p>


<dt>
   <a href="http://www.m2.com/">12.  NEWSWEB</a>
   <br>
   http://www.m2.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Newsweb offers access through the World Wide Web to
national and international news and information about broadcasting, electronic
publishing, marketing, and telecommunications."</i>
</dd>
<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/omb">13.  OFFICE OF MANAGEMENT AND BUDGET (OMB)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.whitehouse.gov/WH/EOP/omb
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) has just
opened a new World Wide Web site[.]  This new site (available only on the Web)
currently offers a healthy number of circulars and bulletins in HTML format."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.lib.umich.edu/libhome/Documents.center/docnews.html">14.  UNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN GOVERNMENT DOCUMENTS CENTER</a>
   <br>
   http://www.lib.umich.edu/libhome/Documents.center/docnews.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The University of Michigan Government Documents
Center provides a 'Documents in the News' page.  Taken from official sources, this
page has full text documents on such subjects as Yitzhak Rabin's assassination,
Bosnia, the Oklahoma City Bombing, the Ebola virus, the United Nations
Conference on Women, the G7 Summit, term limits, and the Unabomber, among
many others."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.wqa.org">15.  WATER QUALITY ASSOCIATION (WQA)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.wqa.org
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The WQA Information Server offers a variety of water
quality resources, including:  The WQA Glossary of Terms; 'Water Quality Basics'
presented in a question and answer format; WaterReview Consumer Reports;
WaterReview Technical Reports; and links to other related Internet sites.  The
website also offers background information on the Water Quality Association and a
'What's New' Section."</i>
</dd>

</dl>


<center>
<h2>~ G O P H E R  S I T E S ~</h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <b>1.  BOSNIA PEACE TREATY (DAYTON PEACE AGREEMENT)</b>
   <br>
   GOPHER to gopher.igc.apc.org, then follow the path:<br>
</dt>
<dd>
<i>Select:  </i>PeaceNet<br>
<i>Select:  </i>Balkans/Ex-Yugoslavia<br>
<i>Select:  </i>Dayton Peace Treaty (22 Nov 95)<p>

<i>Contains the full text of the Bosnia Peace Treaty.</i>
</dd>

</dl>

<hr>

<i>Internet Update</i> is compiled by Leslie A. Lee, Reference Librarian at the Jacob Burns Law
Library, and is issued monthly as a service to the George Washington University Law School
community.

