<h1>Internet Update #6</h1>

<center>
<h3>THE GEORGE WASHINGTON UNIVERSITY LAW SCHOOL</h3>
<h3>JACOB BURNS LAW LIBRARY</h3>
<h3>INTERNET UPDATE #6</h3>
<h3>FEBRUARY 1996</h3>
</center>

Welcome to the sixth issue of the <i>Internet Update</i>, a listing of new and noteworthy websites,
gopher sites, and listserv &amp; newsgroup information.
<p>

<h3>This issue includes the following websites:</h3>

<ol>
  <li>California State Senate</li>
  <li>College and University Home Pages#</li>
  <li>CNN Financial News:  Grapevine#</li>
  <li>EPA Emergency Response Notification System (ERNS)</li>
  <li>GPO Access -- New Searchable Databases: (1)  Privacy Act Issuances 1993 Compilation, (2) 
Government Information Locator Service (GILS), (3)  Congressional Record, Volume 142 (1996), (4)  Congressional Record Index, Volume 142 (1996), (5) Federal Register, Volume 61 (1996) and (6)  History of Bills and Resolutions (1996)</li>
  <li>Human Rights Library#</li>
  <li>Internal Revenue Service's Digital Daily Site#</li>
  <li>Legal Information Institute's New Services:  (1)  U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals Search Engine
and (2)  BigEar:  Current Awareness Service</li>
  <li>Listserv List Reference</li>
  <li>Marketplace of Political Ideas#</li>
  <li>Monthly Catalog of the United States Government Publications#</li>
  <li>NativeWeb#</li>
  <li>Netglos (Multilingual Glossary of Internet Terms)</li>
  <li>New York Times Online#</li>
  <li>NEWSPlace for News & Sources</li>
  <li>PBS's Online News Hour#</li>
  <li>Plain English Guide to the Clean Air Act</li>
  <li>Supreme Court Oral Arguments Online#</li>
  <li>The United States at the United Nations</li>
  <li>The Vatican#</li>
</ol>

<h3>This issue includes the following gopher sites:</h3>


<ol>
  <li>State of the Union Archive#</li>
</ol>
<p>

<h3>This issue contains the following listservs:</h3>


<ol>
  <li>ALLUNY-L (Association of Law Libraries of Upstate New York, Inc.Listserv)</li>
  <li>CUSEEME-Law Video Conferencing Listserv</li>
  <li>Groundwater Mailing List</li>
  <li>NativeWeb Mailing List#</li>
</ol>


<center>
<h2> ~ W E B S I T E S ~ </h2>
</center>

<dl>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.sen.ca.gov/">1.  CALIFORNIA STATE SENATE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.sen.ca.gov/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "California State Senate provides public access through
the World Wide Web to a non-partisan database of information related to the state. 
Users can obtain biographies f Senators, legislative rules, pending ballot
propositions, Senate bills, codes, committee listings, and district maps."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.mit.edu:8001/people/cdemello/univ.html">2.  COLLEGE AND UNIVERSITY HOME PAGES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.mit.edu:8001/people/cdemello/univ.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "College and University Home Pages offers pointers to
the home pages of over 2300 colleges and universities in 77 countries.  Either
alphabetical and geographic listings are available for browsing.  It also includes a
small list of  users hat believe to be good examples of school home pages, and a ink
to a final class project done at Columbia University's College which surveyed over
450 School home pages."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://cnnfn.com/grapevine/">3.  CNN FINANCIAL NEWS:  GRAPEVINE</a>
   <br>
   http://cnnfn.com/grapevine/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "A relatively new section of the CNN Financial News site
is called Grapevine, and aptly so since the page begins with the line 'Fresh from
the Rumor Mill.'  What follows is a small collection of tidbits about money, public
relations, or deals gone bad, along with a Tip of the Day.  Link to the Financial
News main page for a wide range of meatier stories and current market
information."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/ERNS">4.  EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE NOTIFICATION SYSTEMS (ERNS)</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/ERNS
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The ERNS database is the most comprehensive source
of notifications of oil discharges and hazardous substance releases in the United
States.  ERNS is supported by the cooperative data sharing effort of EPA, the
Department of Transportation, and the National Response Center.  Since 1986,
more than 300,000 release notifications have been recorded in ERNS."  ERNS can
also be accessed through EPA's gopher server (gopher.epa.gov) and FTP server
(ftp.epa.gov/pub/gopher/ENRS)."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/">5.  GPO ACCESS -- NEW SEARCHABLE DATABASES</a>
   <br>
   (1)  Privacy Act Issuances 1993 Compilation
   <br>
   (2)  Government Information Locator Service (GILS) Records
   <br>
   (3)  Congressional Record, Volume 142 (1996)
   <br>
   (4)  Congressional Record Index, Volume 142 (1996)
   <br>
   (5)  Federal Register, Volume 61 (1996) 
   <br>
   (6)  History of Bills and Resolutions, Volume 142 (1996)
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>Click on the link, "Select Search and retrieve Full Text Online Via GPO Access From Over 50 Databases.  Scroll down to the list of documents.  Click on the desired database and enter search terms in the designated box.</i>
</dd>

<p>


<dt>
   <a href="http://www.umn.edu/humanrts">6.  HUMAN RIGHTS LIBRARY</a>
   <br>
   http://www.umn.edu/humanrts
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Human Rights Library of the University of
Minnesota holds a collection of over 90 of the most important human rights
instruments -- treaties, declarations, and other materials -- together with
authoritative citations.  The documents are easily accessed by subject matter or
searched by keyword.  In addition, the site offers information about the work of the
human rights treaty bodies, including general comments and recommendations,
decisions and views of the U.N. Human Rights Committee, and other materials. 
Links to other useful sites containing information about human rights and relevant
resources are also provided."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/">7.  INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE'S DIGITAL DAILY SITE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.irs.ustreas.gov/prod/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Internal Revenue Service has opened a 'Digital
Daily' on the Web.  The site is friendly and light-hearted, graphically rich, and
easy to sue.  It offers a searchable interface to 600 tax forms and publications for
businesses and individuals, ready to download.  Sections devoted to 'Tax
Regulations in English,' tax information for business, and an IRS newsstand with
tips about your taxes will help you get started early this year.  A note on how many
days until April 15 may also provide incentive."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   8.  LEGAL INFORMATION INSTITUTE'S NEW SERVICES
   <br>
   <a href="http://www3.law.cornell.edu/Harvest/brokers/circuit-x/fancy.query.html">(1)  U.S. CIRCUIT COURT OF APPEALS SEARCH ENGINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www3.law.cornell.edu/Harvest/brokers/circuit-x/fancy.query.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The LII is pleased to announce formally the existence of
two new services.  The first is a search engine which permits comprehensive
searching of all U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals decisions mounted on the Internet,
with a specialized easy-to-use interface for the more common types of queries as
well as a more complex but powerful interface with makes use of the full power of
the Harvest/Glimpse search engine.  Cases are searchable by party name and cite
(subject to some limitations spelled out on the Web page).</i>"
</dd>
<br>
<dt>
   <a href="http://barratry.law.cornell.edu:5123/notify/buzz.html">(2) BIGEAR:  CURRENT AWARENESS SERVICE</a>
   <br>
   http://barratry.law.cornell.edu:5123/notify/buzz.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The second new 'toy' will already by familiar to many of
you:  our Net current-awareness service known (for the time being, at least) as
BigEar.  We have obtained the cooperation and assistance of the Cornell Law
Library, who are adding commentary to selected entries which BigEar culls from
the Net.  BigEar listens to a variety of law-related listservs and newsgroups.  From
each, it selects messages which contain references to Net documents, and
constructs a convenient cumulative listing which shows the title of the document, a
link to it, and a link to a message 'announcing' it on the listserv."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.lsoft.com/lists/listref.html">9.  LISTSERV LIST REFERENCE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.lsoft.com/lists/listref.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Listserv List Reference is a great source for finding
information about any of the over 7,500 public listservs on the Internet.  It is a Web
interface to LISTSERV Lists database at L-Soft International.  Lists can be
browsed by host site, country, and size if the list subscription exceeds 1,000. 
Subscriber numbers are kept up to date.  Subscription information is provided, as
is each list's configuration.  While this site is used extensively by list owners, it also
provides useful information to potential subscribers to Listserv Lists."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://info.lib.uh.edu/politics/markind.htm">10.  MARKETPLACE OF POLITICAL IDEAS</a>
   <br>
   http://info.lib.uh.edu/politics/markind.htm
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Marketplace of Political Ideas site is now offered
by the University of Houston Libraries.  A collection of pointers to the full range of
candidates and issues is available, such as Democratic sites, Republican sites,
third party sites, non-partisan sites, political groups on the Left, Right, and
'Fringes,' and a variety of political science pointers."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/">11.  MONTHLY CATALOG OF THE UNITED STATES GOVERNMENT PUBLICATIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.access.gpo.gov/su_docs/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Monthly Catalog of the United States Government Publications, with records from January 1994 to the present, is available via the Web.  Records are searchable by title, publication year, Superintendent of Documents (SuDoc) Class Number, Depository Item Number, and Government Printing Office (GPO) Sales Stock Number.  Once your item has been retrieved, you can use the site to locate the nearest federal depository library where it is available, as well as the nearest GPO Bookstore where it can be purchased."  To access, click on the link, "Search a Comprehensive Catalog of Government Information Products (MoCat)."</i>
</dd>
 
<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://web.maxwell.syr.edu/nativeweb/">12.  NATIVEWEB</a>
   <br>
   http://web.maxwell.syr.edu/nativeweb/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "NativeWeb, a rich source of information and documents
about indigenous peoples, has moved to a new location and has been expanded
since we reported on it last year.  The site seeks to 'provide a cyber-place for
Earth's indigenous peoples.'  The site at present provides pointers to North and
South American indigenous peoples' resources, and promises in future to provide
sources for Asia and Africa."  For information on how to subscribe to NativeWeb's
listserv, please refer to the listserv section of this Internet Update."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://wwli.com/translation/netglos/netglos.html">13.  NETGLOS (MULTILINGUAL GLOSSARY OF INTERNET TERMS)</a>
   <br>
   http://wwli.com/translation/netglos/netglos.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Netglos is a multilingual, alphabetical glossary of
Internet terms from alias to WWW.  Presently, the glossary is available in English,
French, and Norwegian.  It is under various states of construction in other
languages, including German, Spanish, and Chinese, and is planned for Bahasa
Indonesia, Portuguese, and Hebrew.  Netglos is a voluntary, collaborative project
by a number of translators and other professionals."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/">14.  NEW YORK TIMES ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://www.nytimes.com/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The New York Times has opened a Website which
includes much of the content of the daily.  Also featured is a 'cyberTimes' section,
with the latest news on computer and Internet developments, as well as a 'New York
Times Navigator,' with pointers to sites used most often by Times reporters. 
Domestic users may use the service free of charge after registering.  Foreign users
must subscribe."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.niu.edu/newsplace/">15.  NEWSPLACE FOR NEWS & SOURCES</a>
   <br>
   http://www.niu.edu/newsplace/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>This site contains links to "White House '96," including biographies of the
Presidential candidates, preliminary Presidential Primary and Caucus dates,
comments by political analysts and journalists, humor, and more.</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.pbs.org/newshour/">16.  PBS'S ONLINE NEWS HOUR</a>
   <br>
   http://www.pbs.org/newshour/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "PBS's Online News Hour debuted on the Internet
[during the week of January 15, 1996].  The site, rich in graphics, offers selected
transcripts from the top stories of each show.  Also available are 'Background
Briefings' -- selected transcripts on subjects of topical interest, such as Bosnia, the
Federal Budget, and Medicare.  An 'Online Forum' will 'allow visitors to the
Online News Hour to communicate with experts, news makers, and opinion leaders,
on a wide variety of subjects.'"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.epa.gov/oar/oaqps/peg_caa/pegcaain.html">17.  PLAIN ENGLISH GUIDE TO THE CLEAN AIR ACT</a>
   <br>
   http://www.epa.gov/oar/oaqps/peg_caa/pegcaain.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "As the title indicates, this guide offers n explanation of
the Clean Air Act and its various provisions in simple, straightforward language."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://oyez.at.nwu.edu/oyez.html">18.  SUPREME COURT ORAL ARGUMENTS ONLINE</a>
   <br>
   http://oyez.at.nwu.edu/oyez.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "Unedited Oral Arguments before the Supreme Court
offers audio files of complete oral arguments before the Supreme Court in landmark
cases.  The site currently includes:  United States v. Nixon, Roe v. Wade, Griswold
v. Connecticut, and Pennsylvania v. Casey, among others.  The arguments are in
RealAudio format.  Professor Jerry Goldman, a political scientist at Northwestern
University, created the site and states it is the beginning of an ambitious project to
digitize 400 hours of audio files."</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.undp.org/missions/usa/index.html">19.  THE UNITED STATES AT THE UNITED NATIONS</a>
   <br>
   http://www.undp.org/missions/usa/index.html
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>Madeleine Albright, U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations provides answers to
the questions, "What does the United States get out of the United Nations and why
should we support it?"</i>
</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <a href="http://www.vatican.va/">20.  THE VATICAN</a>
   <br>
   http://www.vatican.va/
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "The Vatican has established an official and attractive Website under its own top-level country domain. Total content currently consists of two messages from Pope John Paul II:  Christmas 1995 and The Celebration of the World Day of Peace January 1996.  However, you can read both in your choice of 7 languages, and a form is provided for sending email to the Vatican."</i>
</dd>

</dl>

<center>
<h2>~ G O P H E R  S I T E S ~</h2>
</center>


<dl>

<dt>
   <a href="gopher://www.polisci.nwu.edu">1.  STATE OF THE UNION ARCHIVE</a>
   <br>
   gopher://www.polisci.nwu.edu
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "If you are interested in what past presidents have said in their State of the Union Addresses, try Northwestern University's valuable State of the Union Archive
gopher.  It offers the full text of all State of the Union Addresses from Harry Truman's in 1846 to Bill Clinton's in 1995.  Also included are five selected Addresses from Franklin D. Roosevelt."  Also available at gopher://www.polisci.nwu.edu:70.</i>
</dd>

</dl>

<center>
<h2>~ L I S T S E R V S ~</h2>
</center>


<dl>

<dt>
   <b>1.  ALLUNY-L (ASSOCIATION OF LAW LIBRARIES OF UPSTATE NEW YORK, INC. LISTSERV)</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "ALLUNY-L is an unmoderated list for the general activities of the
Association of Law Libraries of Upstate New York, Inc.  The main goals of the Association are to
develop and advance standards of law.  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>send to:</i>  listproc@cornell.edu<br>
<i>with the message:</i>  subscribe ALLUNY-L &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>2.  CUSEEME-LAW VIDEO CONFERENCING</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>To subscribe:</i>
<p>
<i>send to:</i>  listserv@assocdir.wuacc.edu<br>
<i>with the message:</i>  subscribe cuseeme-law &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>3.  GROUNDWATER MAILING LIST</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>From the announcement:  "A new mailing list has been established to facilitate global discussion
of groundwater and related issues."  To subscribe:</i>

<p>

<i>send to:</i>  majordomo@ias.champlain.edu<br>
<i>with the message:</i>  subscribe GROUNDWATER<p>

</dd>

<p>

<dt>
   <b>4.  NATIVEWEB</b>
</dt>
<dd>
   <i>For a description of the content of NativeWeb, please refer to the NativeWeb listing under
websites.  To subscribe to the NativeWeb mailing list:</i>

<p>

<i>send to:</i>  LISTSERV@THE CITY.SFSU.EDU<br>
<i>with the message:</i>  SUB NATIVEWEB &lt;your name&gt;

</dd>

